<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Is About To Endorse Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Advisers close to failed Republican candidate John McCain
say he has decided to endorse former rival George W. Bush at their summit
tomorrow, despite misgivings about the Texan's agenda. The Arizona senator is
said to have determined after a series of events -- including a weekend
telephone conversation with the presumptive GOP nominee -- that he didn't want
to wait any longer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Love Bug Suspect Is Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Accompanied by FBI agents, Philippine police
raided an apartment in Manila on Monday and arrested a bank employee who along
with his girlfriend is suspected of links to the ''ILOVEYOU'' virus that has
overwhelmed computer networks around the world. But relatives of the man, Reomel
Ramones, said they believe the real culprit may be a third person who lived in
the apartment -- the girlfriend's unemployed sister, who recently graduated from
a computer school that a U.S. security firm has linked to the ''Love Bug''
virus.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Burns Near Los Alamos
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A fire set to clear underbrush at a national
monument that lost control forced the closure of the Los Alamos National
Laboratory Monday and sent at least 500 people from their homes. A separate fire
200 miles southeast near Ruidoso burned 4,500 acres and forced the evacuation of
at least 200 homes. High wind caused problems with both fires, and Gov. Gary
Johnson declared a state of emergency. ''we're going to stay as long as we
can,'' said former Rep. Bill Redmond, R-N.M., a Senate candidate whose home was
among 1,000 placed on evacuation alert in Los Alamos.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
O'Connor's Funeral Is Held
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor was buried Monday beneath the St.
Patrick's Cathedral altar that was his pulpit for 16 years, after a funeral Mass
that drew thousands of mourners, from presidents to ordinary parishioners.
O'Connor, 80, died Wednesday of a brain tumor. Attending the funeral were
President Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton; ex-President George Bush;
presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush; Gov. George Pataki, and
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philly Adopts All-Uniform Rule
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia adopted a policy tonight requiring all
students to wear uniforms in 256 public schools, the first big-city district to
do so. Most parents who spoke opposed uniforms for Philadelphia's 217,000
public-school students. The measure, which goes into effect immediately, does
not call for a single, Roman Catholic-school-style uniform; instead, schools
could decide individually how students should dress.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Justice Dept Said Ready To Sue LAPD
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Justice Department stands ready to file a police
misconduct lawsuit against the city of Los Angeles, U.S. officials said Monday,
but will give city authorities time to try to work out a voluntary settlement
instead. Bill Lann Lee, acting assistant attorney general for the department's
civil rights division, met with officials for over an hour, then issued a
statement outlining the federal government's position. ''Today we notified
officials of the city of Los Angeles, the Police Commission and the LAPD that
the Civil Rights Division has been authorized to file a police misconduct
lawsuit,'' Lee's statement said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nationwide strike ends in Norway
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- A strike that threatened European automobile production
was called off Tuesday after Norway's largest union and employers agreed on a
new contract in all-night talks. The deal was reached in the sixth day of a
strike by 84,600 union members, which the union had threatened to turn into
Norway's second largest labor conflict by pushing the number of strikers to over
102,000 on Tuesday. The deal was reached just two hours before that deadline.
Even though the new offer also has to be put to a vote by union members,
strikers were returning to work immediately pending the outcome of that
referendum.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall; Dollar Up Vs Yen
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Tuesday following a retreat in
technology shares on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 255.97 points, to 17,943.99 at
the end of the morning session. In New York, the Nasdaq was down 147.44 at
3,669.38 and the Dow Jones industrial average ended up 25.77 at 10,603.63.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Defeat 76ers 103-97
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Jalen Rose scored 30 points and the Indiana Pacers,
despite not making a field goal over the final seven minutes, beat the
Philadelphia 76ers 103-97 Monday night to take a 2-0 lead in the Eastern
Conference semifinals. The Pacers scored their final 10 points on free throws,
starting with two by Rose that put Indiana ahead 95-73 with 5:53 to play. The
best-of-seven series shifts to Philadelphia for Game 3 on Wednesday and Game 4
on Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
