<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug law reformers, others, seek Legislature's attention  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's Rockefeller drug laws are
wasting money and people's lives, but most of all they are harming
the children of those convicted of them, two recently paroled
narcotics offenders said.
</P>
<P>
   The drug law reform demonstration the women spoke at Monday was
one of several events planned this week in Albany as groups try to
influence the state Legislature and Pataki to act on issues
outstanding in the lawmakers' 2000 session.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature finished adopting a budget last Friday for the
2000-01 state fiscal year. It is expected to be in session for six
or seven more weeks before adjourning, possibly for the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Bartlett and Jan Warren were both granted clemency in
December 1999 by Pataki, making them immediately eligible for what
proved to be successful parole hearings. Both women had served more
than half their sentences of at least 15 years to life under the
state's mandatory drug laws which date back to Nelson Rockefeller's
era as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It feels good to be free,'' Bartlett told about 200 people
gathered for a rally at the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said the drug laws are primarily hurting the children of
the men and women who are behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't ask for us to be stupid, we did that all on our
own,'' Warren said. ''But they're paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett added, ''We all know that we made a mistake. We're only
human. ... But did our mistake warrant the time they gave us?''
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers remembered the late Cardinal John O'Connor at
the rally, which was held at the same time as funeral services were
getting underway for O'Connor at St. Patrick's Cathedral in
Manhattan. The state's Roman Catholic bishops, headed by O'Connor,
came out in favor of reforming the Rockefeller drug statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Al Lewis, the 1998 Green Party candidate for governor who is
running for U.S. Senate this year, pointed to the Capitol and told
those attending the rally that they were ''just as responsible as
the fools who sit in that building'' for not insisting that the
drug laws be reworked.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, best known as ''Grandpa'' in ''The Munsters'' television
series of 1960s, said it became common after World War II to ask,
''What did the good Germans do?'' about the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are responsible, we, because somebody is going to say 30
years from now, 'What did the good people of New York state and the
United States do?'' he said of the drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   The top Republican in the state Legislature, Senate Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno, and the state's chief judge, Judith Kaye, have
also called for reform of the Rockefeller drug laws. Pataki, who
last year proposed changes that opponents said did not go far
enough, has not modified his plan this year.
</P>
<P>
   Upward of 10,000 public employees and retirees plan to rally at
the Capitol today to push for establishment of a permanent
cost-of-living adjustment to public retirees' pensions. Pataki
indicated last week he supports such increases tied to some gauge
of living expenses such as the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues which are certain to be considered by the
Legislature -- though not necessarily acted on -- between now and its
expected adjournment include:
</P>
<P>
   --Sex assault reform. The Senate, Assembly and governor have all
called for laws to be toughened, but have been unable to agree on a
single approach.
</P>
<P>
   --Juvenile justice reform. Pataki and the Senate have been
pushing harsher penalties for young criminals, but Assembly
Democrats have been wary of too-stringent punishments for some
youthful offenders whose lives can be redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   --Privacy issues. Protecting the privacy of New Yorkers,
especially against internet crooks and snoops, has become something
of a hot topic at the Capitol. But there has been no accord on
distilling various proposals into one bill.
</P>
<P>
   --Teacher violence. Teachers' unions are fighting to increase
penalties for violence against teachers.
</P>
<P>
   --HMO accountability. Doctors' and medical consumer groups want
to rein in what they say are health maintenance organizations with
too much power, especially in making medical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   --Cameras in court. Bruno and Pataki have said they want to pass
legislation, but long-standing opponents in the Assembly remain
opposed to opening courtrooms to television and still cameras.
</P>
<P>
   --Anti-smoking. Bills before the Legislature include those to
raise the legal age of purchase for tobacco from 18 to 19 or to 21
and to toughen the state's restrictions on smoking in public
places.
</P>
<P>
   --Gun safety. Pataki, the Senate and Assembly have all promised
to work toward passage of bills to require trigger locks and other
measures to keep dangerous guns out of the hands of young people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 0016 </TRAILER>
