<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Partially Closes Los Alamos  </HEADLINE>
By DEBORAH BAKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A fire set to clear underbrush at a
national monument that got out of control forced the closure of the
Los Alamos National Laboratory Monday and sent at least 500 people
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   A separate fire 200 miles southeast near Ruidoso burned 5,400
acres and forced the evacuation of at least 200 homes.
</P>
<P>
   High wind caused problems with both fires, and Gov. Gary Johnson
declared a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to stay as long as we can,'' said former Rep. Bill
Redmond, R-N.M., a Senate candidate whose home was among 1,000
placed on evacuation alert in Los Alamos. An additional 500 homes
on the west side of town were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, which has scorched more than 3,000 acres, was about a
mile away from the nearest homes Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos fire spokesman Jim Paxon said cloudier, cooler
weather helped firefighters Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This cloud cover is a godsend. ... We are very confident
things are going in the right direction,'' said Paxon, a Forest
Service spokesman assigned to the multiagency fire team.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the fire was earlier downgraded from an estimated
5,000 acres Monday to 1,935 acres that were actually mapped with
aerial infrared radar, fire spokeswoman Rita Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was set Thursday by National Park Service to get rid of
excess underbrush and deadwood at the Bandelier National Monument,
home of ancient Indian ruins and 70 miles of hiking trails.
</P>
<P>
   Park Superintendent Roy Weaver took responsibility for the
blaze, saying he believed conditions had been just right for the
park's annual regimen of prescribed burning, designed to keep the
park's backcountry from becoming a ''tinder box.'' The Park Service
had planned to burn just 900 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seemed to be the right balance of fuel, moisture,
temperature and wind,'' Weaver said at a news conference. But the
humidity didn't get as high as hoped and wind was higher than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear research lab's explosive materials are secured in
nonflammable concrete and metal buildings surrounded by earthen
berms about a half-mile from the fire, lab spokesman John Gustafson
said. The closest radioactive materials were about three miles from
the fire, spokesman Kevin Roark said.
</P>
<P>
   Only essential personnel reported for work Monday at the lab,
Department of Energy officials said. Public schools were closed and
Los Alamos County told most of its workers to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's human error to mess with Mother Nature when it's
hot and windy -- it's stupid,'' said Holly Harmston, owner of a Los
Alamos cafe shut down because of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say this fire season could rival the one in 1996, when
intense fires threatened communities in wooded areas.
</P>
<P>
   That year, almost 17,000 acres burned near Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory: http://www.lanl.gov/worldview
</P>
<P>
   Bandelier National Monument: http://www.nps.gov/band
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
