<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clay Animation Studio Teaches Art  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER KIMURA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Brad Schiff walks around with plastic
boxes containing miniature lips that pucker, frown, shout and
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the lead animators for Portland's Will Vinton Studios,
Schiff makes Claymation puppets. Under his care, little lips and
eyeballs take on realistic facial expressions and bits of clay are
given fluid movement in the form of M&AMP;M ''spokescandies'' and the
dancing California Raisins.
</P>
<P>
   ''We make extra eyeballs because they do get lost,'' said Sean
Dickson, who works with Schiff in the studio's art lab.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson and Schiff's latest project is NFL commercials featuring
smack-talking sportscasters James Brown and Terry Bradshaw as
cartoonish characters. Six 15-second spots are airing this month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they animated the first season of Thurgood Stubbs and
his inner-city family in the Fox sitcom, ''The PJs.'' The show,
which featured Eddie Murphy as Stubbs' voice, will begin its second
season this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot of work,'' said Schiff, who has worked at the
studio for 2{ years. ''But it's a lot of fun. It's hard and it's
frustrating, but I get to play for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty participants from around the country -- including art
directors, advertising executives, broadcast and production
directors -- converged on Will Vinton Studios recently for workshops
on the artistic, technical and marketing aspects of animation.
</P>
<P>
   At the Animation Camp, now in its seventh year, Schiff taught a
workshop on stop-motion animation -- the method that brought fame to
the studio in 1986 with the wildly popular ''California Raisins''
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The tools of the trade include clay bits, silicone molds and
wire puppet skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to do animation; I want to learn how the pros do it,''
said Michael Corbeille, a senior art director for a Chicago-based
ad agency who is working on ads for McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   At the camp's character development lab, David Altschul, Will
Vinton's president of advertising, stressed that the key to any
effective commercial is a storyline with a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all too easy to put sunglasses and feet on a character
and make them warmhearted,'' Altschul said. ''Something needs to be
imperfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-plus spots the studio has made in the past five years for
Mars Inc.'s M&AMP;M Mars subsidiary typically play upon three
conflicts, Altschul said: short characters in a tall-person's
world, animated characters in a human's world, or the end-all
plight -- being edible in a hungry world.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The characters') own real personalities are in this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While endearing themselves to viewers, the animated spots also
accomplish the obvious goal: moving the product. Altschul said the
M&AMP;M spots have boosted the chocolate candy's sales by $250 million
in the United States and overseas during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Will Vinton Studio was founded in 1975, it has evolved
with technology, combining digital work with their brand-name
Claymation style in spots for Kikkoman, Nissan, Sony Playstation,
Domino's Pizza and others.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little bit of an education process -- to think more
broadly,'' said Tom Turpin, CEO of the studio and a former
multimedia division chief for the Virgin Group. ''Technology is
changing, costs are coming down,'' he said. ''There's a lot of
things to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Animation Camp participants gained hands-on lessons creating
computer-generated images with a program that maps a character's
three-dimensional movement.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie animators also got their hands dirty, molding their
own chunks of clay against a white screen while a studio expert
took stop-motion sequences at intervals. The end result -- a
10-second film clip of moving clay.
</P>
<P>
   They also dabbled in animation with sand and title sequences,
tried a hand at posing the actual puppets from ''The PJs,'' and
learned Pixelation, a method of photographing an object and moving
it at intervals to give the appearance that it's moving by itself.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound more like play than work, but Claymation takes
patience.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a character's model and texture through a series of
mouse clicks and obscure commands could take up to two weeks,
computer wizard Shawn McInerney said. ''Animation is not the
fastest thing in the world,'' he said. ''It's like watching grass
grow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 0029 </TRAILER>
