<HEADLINE> Union, Red Cross optimistic that mediations will lead to a deal  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Red Cross officials and their unionized
workers have both expressed optimism that a new round of
negotiations will end week-old walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Over 200 technician-drivers, nurses, and phlebotomists walked
off the job May 1, resulting in the cancellation of blood drives
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were expected to head back to the bargaining table
today for the first time since April 27.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think rational heads will prevail and we should reach an
agreement. We've modified some of our outstanding issues,'' said
Jeffrey Jump, chief negotiator for the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees, Local 3145.
</P>
<P>
   The union is seeking better pay, benefits, scheduling and
retirement packages, said Jump. Current pay ranges from $10 to $22
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The agency contends it has made a fair and generous offer. In a
recent statement, the Red Cross said a strike would not affect
Connecticut's blood supply, but a prolonged walkout could
''seriously affect the region's ability to collect and distribute
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're hopeful that this will be resolved,'' said Red Cross
spokeswoman Lynn Townshend.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is made, workers could be back on the job as early as
Wednesday afternoon, Jump said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime the Red Cross has relied on blood from other
areas to maintain its supply. One blood drive in Norwalk remained
open Monday, and Madison was to be the sole location Tuesday,
Townshend said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight blood drives across the state were canceled Monday and
nine were off for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Townshend said the strike has not hurt the agency's service.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hospitals have been happy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bradford Sherbune at Hartford Hospital said blood supplies
are steady and no surgeries have been postponed or canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy to say, so far things are fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Zaorski, a spokeswoman at Yale-New Haven Hospital also
reported no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Red Cross has been able to supply us with our usual supply
of blood,'' she said. ''Let's hope everything straightens out
soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
