<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motion for new trial rejected  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- A judge has rejected former New Milford
police Officer Scott Smith's claims of juror misconduct, and upheld
his conviction on manslaughter charges.
</P>
<P>
   Smith faces up to 40 years in prison when he is sentenced
Thursday for shooting a suspect in the back at point-blank range.
He was convicted in March.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles D. Gill on Monday said there was little evidence
of any juror misconduct during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyer, John J. Kelly, had cited nine instances of
possible misconduct, including allegations that one juror flashed a
badge and claimed special knowledge of police procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm obviously disappointed,'' said Kelly. ''But the denial
will be an additional appellate issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill met last week with all 12 jurors, questioning them about
some of the allegations. Kelly and prosecutors were present, but
could not ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're pleased, but not surprised,'' said Waterbury State's
Attorney John Connelly, who prosecuted the case. ''We felt all
along these allegations were unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 34-page ruling Monday, Gill said that while one juror had
admitted violating his order not to visit the crime scene, it did
not affect the outcome of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gill said the badge allegation could not be supported.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court, after listening and observing all 12 jurors on the
subject, finds that there is absolutely no basis for this claim of
misconduct,'' Gill wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Gill also rejected allegations two jurors had notes with them in
the jury room. Two jurors apparently had lists of questions they
wanted to discuss, which Gill said does not amount to misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the three jurors who said misconduct may have
occurred were well-intentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court hopes that with the reading of this opinion that
those three jurors will better understand the process and see the
law in a new light,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Acting New Milford police Chief Colin McCormick left the
courthouse without commenting on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 28, is the first Connecticut police officer to be charged
with murder for an act in the line of duty. He said he shot suspect
Franklyn Reid after a foot chase in December 1998 because he
believed Reid was reaching for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the shooting, Reid, 27, was unarmed. A short
folding knife was discovered in the pocket of a jacket found a few
feet away from his body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 0105 </TRAILER>
