<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yale hosts new National Center for Children Exposed to Violence  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Yale's school of medicine is opening a
new center devoted to a single children's health issue -- violence.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 2.8 million reports of child abuse a year,
and 9 million children witness violent acts, school officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Children Exposed to Violence is being opened to
raise awareness of the lasting scars of violence for children and
to help to researchers and people working with children who have
been victims or exposed to violence, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Attorney General Eric Holder announced plans for the
new center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Behind each statistic is a vulnerable, feeling child,'' Holder
said.
</P>
<P>
   The center's objective is to prevent violence and children's
exposure to violence, intervene early and effectively with children
and hold perpetrators accountable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yale Medical School Dean Dr. David Kessler said the school was
gratified to be chosen to host the national center.
</P>
<P>
   The center will ''increase capacity of communities and
individuals across the country to respond to the complex needs of
children whose psychological and physical health is challenged
through exposure to the effects of violence,'' Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   The work of the center had been the responsibility of the U.S.
Justice Department. It is being moved to Yale to ensure its future,
Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven and Yale were a natural fit because of the city's long
community policing effort with the Yale Child Study Center that has
brought together the resources and connections other cities need to
combat abuse, Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine communities connected through the Justice Department's Safe
Start project will get training through the center. They will
coordinate child welfare, police, courts, doctors and schools to
prevent an overall approach to preventing violence and treating
children who are the victims.
</P>
<P>
   The other Safe Start communities are: Baltimore, Chicago,
Rochester, N.Y., San Francisco, Spokane, Wash., Chatham County,
N.C., Washington County, Maine, Pinellas County, Fla. and
Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
