<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Connor's legacy: still confronting the age in which he lived  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Even after death, Cardinal John O'Connor's
unwavering opposition to abortion, the death penalty and euthanasia
rang out from the altar of St. Patrick's Cathedral, a clear
indication of his legacy this time delivered as part of his eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a great legacy he has left us in his constant reminder
that the church must always be unambiguously pro-life,'' Cardinal
Bernard Law said during Monday's funeral Mass for New York's
longtime spiritual leader.
</P>
<P>
   The remark sparked 75 seconds of applause, then a standing
ovation that spread from the back of St. Patrick's to the front,
where President Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and other politicians were seated.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the political heavyweights favor abortion rights, but
they eventually stood, too, some without applauding.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see he hasn't left the pulpit,'' a smiling Law said of
O'Connor, his close friend, who died last week at age 80 after a
long battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the only ovation to reverberate through the great
cathedral. In a fond farewell, mourners broke into applause again
just as the cardinal's mahogany coffin was disappearing from their
view on its way to a crypt beneath the altar. Among them was
8-year-old Alexander Garrett, who has one leg but propped himself
on crutches in the front aisle to wave good-bye.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm here to see him for the last time,'' said the boy, who
remembered that O'Connor once gave him a rosary.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 clergy took part in the ceremony, archdiocesan
spokesman the Rev. Paul Keenan said. Among them was Bishop Edward
Egan, of Bridgeport, Conn., the perceived front-runner to replace
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   So many priests wanted to help celebrate the Mass that some had
to do so from 40 rows back in the pews.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paul Tolve, chaplain of the Westchester County
Corrections Department, said he went to St. Patrick's on Monday
because O'Connor had ordained him into the priesthood in 1984, soon
after the archbishop -- not yet a cardinal -- came to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to offer back what I could,'' Tolve said. ''He meant
a lot to me, and I always remembered that bond of ordination.''
</P>
<P>
   In a gentle demonstration of that devotion, hundreds of the
priests who filed past the cardinal's coffin touched it lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a kind of blessing,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   The principal celebrant was Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Vatican
secretary of state, whose presence was ''a gift from Pope John
Paul,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lord, we don't complain because you have taken him from us,''
Sodano told the 3,500 people. ''But rather we will thank you for
giving him to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Clintons and Giuliani, other notables at the Mass
included Vice President Al Gore, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, former
President George Bush, New York Gov. George Pataki, Sens. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer and the cardinal's two sisters
and brother.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the church, hundreds of people stood behind police
barricades in record 91-degree heat, some mouthing the prayers and
hymns as the funeral Mass was broadcast over loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew Cardinal O'Connor; he was a man gifted by God with
wisdom and understanding,'' said Joan Gray Jangarathis, of Short
Hills, N.J. ''I had to be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Law's sermon, which praised O'Connor for making ''this pulpit
unique in the history of the Catholic Church in the United
States,'' was followed by a eulogy from Cardinal William Baum,
formerly of Washington and now in the Roman Curia. Baum said
O'Connor should be remembered for ''confronting the age in which he
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a slow, mournful procession up and down the aisles of
the church as pallbearers carried the coffin to its crypt, which
was inscribed simply with a cross, a coat of arms and ''John
Cardinal O'Connor, 1920-2000. Archbishop 1984-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the family returned from the entombment, organ, trumpet
and choir broke into a thunderous, triumphant hymn, ''Lift High the
Cross,'' which also was performed when O'Connor was installed as
head of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the Mass of the Resurrection,'' Jangarathis said outside,
''and God gives us hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 0106 </TRAILER>
