<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police: More officers, community efforts extend crime decline  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Putting more officers on the beat and
improving relationships with the community has paid off as violent
crime continues to decline in the state and nation, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Violent crimes fell 7 percent nationwide and dropped in the
state's five largest cities in 1999, according to preliminary
figures from the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The downward trend, which extends back to 1992, is now nearly
three times longer than the second-longest decline, from 1982
through 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury Police Chief Edward Flaherty attributed the trend to a
shift toward community policing, a philosophy encouraging
partnerships between officers and the people they protect.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking for long-term solutions rather than just
responding to calls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal police departments have taken advantage of federal
grants which have paid for 100,000 more local officers nationwide,
said Cromwell Chief Anthony Salvatore, president-elect of the
Connecticut Police Chiefs Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're forming partnerships with the community, trying
different methods such as bicycle patrols and foot beats in major
urban areas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The good economy, and low unemployment, also has kept some
people from committing crimes of desperation, Salvatore said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts caution the decline is slowing and could be
bottoming out.
</P>
<P>
   ''The challenge is to be sure the numbers don't go back up to
any great degree,'' said Professor James Alan Fox of Northeastern
University in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's record prison population provides only ''temporary
relief,'' Fox added, ''because those people will come out of prison
and many will still have inadequate skills and bad attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI figures show that New Haven had the highest number of
violent crimes -- including murder, rape, aggravated assault,
burglary, larceny and arson -- with 12,009, a 9 percent drop from
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport, where crime fell 8.5 percent to 8,285, had the most
murders (30) and was ranked 69th of 226 cities tracked in the
number of murders committed.
</P>
<P>
   In Waterbury, total crime fell 11 percent to 6,400 in 1999.
Stamford saw a 23 percent decrease to 3,448.
</P>
<P>
   Violent crimes in Hartford fell 14 percent to 10,261 -- an
effect, police officials said, of a focus on quality of life issues
such as public drinking and loitering.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things like that create an opportunity and attitude for people
to engage in more serious crimes,'' said spokesman Sgt. Neil Dryfe.
''If you're hanging out on a corner waiting for someone to rob and
are arrested for loitering, you're never going to get the chance to
commit that robbery.''
</P>
<P>
   Crime was down not only nationwide, but also in every region of
the nation and in suburbs, rural areas and cities of all sizes,
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI figures come from more than 17,000 U.S. police agencies
and extend back to 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.fbi.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
