<HEADLINE> Princeton To Alter China Program  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Princeton University officials have agreed
to change its summer language program in Beijing after Chinese
educators said textbook references to the country's
population-control policy and the independence of Taiwan are
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at Beijing Normal University, the site of
Princeton's 9-year-old program, also objected to lessons that
referred to Chinese drivers not yielding for pedestrians and the
behavior of wildly cheering crowds at a volleyball game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, things that hurt the feelings of the Chinese people
cannot appear in teaching materials,'' said Chen Fu, vice president
of Beijing Normal University's Foreign Chinese Education College.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said she wasn't aware of orders from higher authorities to
the school telling it to alter Princeton's materials.
</P>
<P>
   After a Beijing Normal teacher wrote a critical article about
the program, the Chinese university officials told the Princeton
professor who runs it, C.P. Chou, to delete eight lessons and alter
large parts of others in textbooks
</P>
<P>
   Chou said Monday he will make the required changes in time for
the nine-week program to begin at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the university banned one of the program's
textbooks, ''A Trip to China,'' Chou said. Officials objected to
lessons that stated there was no toilet paper in public bathrooms
in China, among other things, Chou said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important for the program, for us to make decisions about
what to teach and what not to teach,'' said Chou. ''But that's not
(how) the host institution sees it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 120 students plan to attend this summer's program,
considered one of China's most prestigious. The $3,900 program
offers four levels of language classes, beginner to advanced, for
undergraduates. The majority of students who attend are American;
one-third come from Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Link, Princeton's leading Chinese-language scholar and a
co-director of the program, said the textbooks do not take a
political position on issues such as Taiwan and the family planning
policy, which limits most couples in China to only one child.
</P>
<P>
   He said the goal was simply to compel students to try to express
themselves in a new language.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to have the students want to say something,''
said Link. ''Then you can correct their language.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the changes have nothing to do with his involvement
with the program. Link, who has written articles critical of China
on human rights issues, was stopped in Beijing in 1996 and ordered
to return to America, and has not been issued a visa since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
