<HEADLINE> Nebraska, W.Va. To Hold Primaries  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN O'HANLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Two of Nebraska's highest-ranking officials
squared off today in a Republican primary for the seat being
vacated by Sen. Bob Kerrey, the only Democrat in the state's
congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Don Stenberg and Secretary of State Scott Moore
were expected to lead the four-way GOP primary, with the winner
likely to take on former Gov. Ben Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who spent two terms in office and left in 1999 with an
80 percent approval rating, faced token opposition in the
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   In another closely watched race today, former University of
Nebraska football coach Tom Osborne had two opponents in a GOP
congressional primary. Although farming and other issues have
dominated the race, voters in this football-crazy state are clearly
fascinated with Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   In West Virginia, Republican Gov. Cecil Underwood faced a
painting contractor, a housewife and an unemployed construction
worker in the GOP primary. Underwood, 77, was so confident that he
did not campaign and planned to spend election night watching a
minor league baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   The more dramatic West Virginia race was for the House seat
being left by Rep. Bob Wise, who is running in the Democratic
primary to challenge Underwood.
</P>
<P>
   Four Democrats were vying for the seat Wise has held since 1982,
including Secretary of State Ken Hechler, an 85-year-old former
congressman whose political career dates back to the New Deal. He
faces popular state Sen. Martha Walker, Harrison County
Commissioner Beth Taylor and lawyer Jim Humphreys, who spent $3
million of his own money and leads in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will face Republican Shelley Moore Capito, a member
of the state House of Delegates and the daughter of former Gov.
Arch Moore Jr., the state's only three-term governor.
</P>
<P>
   There were also presidential primaries today in Nebraska and
West Virginia, but both were essentially meaningless since George
W. Bush and Al Gore have sealed their parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   In Nebraska, Republicans were giddy when Kerrey, a rare Democrat
in the conservative state, declined to run for a third term. Kerrey
instead will become president of New School University in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg, who recently defended Nebraska's ban against so-called
partial birth abortions before the Supreme Court, had been running
for the Senate for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerrey's decision prompted Moore, one of Stenberg's most
prominent backers, to enter the race. Moore has raised $224,000
this year, compared with $144,000 for Stenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Agribusinessman David Hergert and former state Sen. John DeCamp
were also on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne considered running for the GOP Senate nomination but
instead decided to seek the House seat held by Republican Bill
Barrett, who is retiring after five terms.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne's opponents, longtime state GOP leader John Gale and
state Board of Education member Kathy Wilmot, have tried not to let
the former coach's celebrity hinder their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, who coached Nebraska for a quarter-century and led the
Cornhuskers to three national championships in the 1990s, would
face Democrat Rollie Reynolds in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people in the state of Nebraska have had a chance to
see me operate up close and personal for 25 years,'' Osborne said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 0115 </TRAILER>
