<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Blood Thinner Shows Promise  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A new class of blood thinner shows promise in
warding off dangerous blood clots after surgery and is more
convenient to take than the standard drug, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary study of the medication on people undergoing
knee or hip replacement surgery, those who took the new drug had
half the chance of developing clots in their legs compared to those
given the usual treatment of injections of the anti-clotting agent
heparin.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Myerson, a national spokesman for the American Heart
Association and a cardiologist at Johns Hopkins University, said
that while the test results were a good start, it was too early to
tell how well the drug will work and whether it is safe.
</P>
<P>
   The study, presented Friday at a blood clotting conference in
Portugal, was paid for by Anglo-Swedish pharmaceutical company
AstraZeneca, which developed the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ''This medicine appears promising,'' said Myerson, who was not
connected with the study. But, he added, ''while the data look
excellent, it would be premature to recommend the medication be
used on a widespread basis.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the next step was for other researchers independent of
the drug maker to replicate the findings in their own studies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages of the experimental drug, which does not
yet have a name, is that is can be injected or taken as a pill,
whereas heparin must be injected, said Dr. Bengt Eriksson, a
professor of orthopedic surgery at the Sahlgrenska University
hospital in Gothenburg, Sweden, who headed the study.
</P>
<P>
   Clots form during surgery when the wall of a blood vessel is
broken and particles in the blood called platelets become activated
to plug the break.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest worry with an anti-clotting drug is that it will
cause bleeding because there is such a slim margin between it doing
its job and overdoing it.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pill given after surgery to prevent clots -- warfarin
-- but it must be carefully monitored with regular blood tests to
ensure it is not making the blood too thick to flow freely or too
thin to form a scab over a cut.
</P>
<P>
   Foods containing vitamin K, such as green leafy vegetables,
affect warfarin's performance by encouraging several of the
clotting substances the drug targets. That makes it difficult to
maintain the right concentration of the drug in the blood.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been searching for a new type of drug that could
overcome some of those problems.
</P>
<P>
   The new drug prevents clots in a different way from both heparin
and warfarin, acting in the final stage of the formation of a blood
clot by inhibiting the activity of a substance called Thrombin.
</P>
<P>
   Thrombin converts a clotting factor dissolved in the blood into
long strands that radiate from the clump and form a net to entrap
more platelets and blood cells so that the clump can grow bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Heparin and warfarin intervene earlier in the clotting process,
producing a knock-on effect on actions that would occur later.
</P>
<P>
   Eriksson said that because the new drug is broken down
differently and its performance is not affected by vitamin K, the
concentration of the medicine does not swing as much and regular
blood tests are not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   During the experiment, 285 people were given the new drug, first
by injection right before the operation and then as a pill
afterward twice daily for about 8 days. Another 308 were given one
heparin injection, and another fake one, a day.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors x-rayed the subjects' legs at the end of the study to
check for blood clots. A total of 43 in the experimental group, or
15 percent, had clots, while 87, or 28.2 percent, of the people on
heparin had developed them.
</P>
<P>
   The occurrence of bleeding was about the same, and there
appeared to be no adverse reactions to the new drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 0126 </TRAILER>
