<DOCNO> APW20000509.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Leader Still Rides High  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- With less than three weeks to go
before President Hugo Chavez's re-election bid, Venezuela's economy
is mired in recession, and unemployment and crime are at historic
highs -- enough to cripple even the best of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet polls show Chavez with a 20-point lead over his closest
rival in the May 28 vote. Though not assured, his victory is
extremely likely.
</P>
<P>
   Most Venezuelans believe the 45-year-old former coup leader when
he promises that the fruits of his ''Bolivarian revolution'' will
soon be felt. For better or worse, he has connected with the
Venezuelan people like few leaders before him, even though he no
longer enjoys the 80 percent-plus approval ratings he had a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Going into its sixth election in little more than a year,
Venezuela is a poorer nation than it was when Chavez took office in
February 1999. It is also more dangerous and more divided, with a
future far less certain.
</P>
<P>
   But in the slums and shantytowns that are home to the majority
of the South American nation's 23 million people, hope has been
rekindled.
</P>
<P>
   With fiery rhetoric invoking the ideals of 19th century South
American liberator Simon Bolivar, Chavez has capitalized on the
failure of successive governments to distribute the country's vast
oil wealth more equitably.
</P>
<P>
   He has done away with the traditional political parties that
ruled Venezuela for decades. The only other candidate with a chance
to win on May 28, Francisco Arias Cardenas, helped Chavez stage his
failed 1992 coup attempt and shares Chavez's claim of independence
from the country's discredited political class -- although Arias has
since accused the president of abandoning the ideals behind their
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chavez has been a successful revolutionary,'' said pollster
Luis Vicente Leon. ''He's made it so that the entire national
debate today is taking place only within his Bolivarian movement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president's destruction of the old political order has
not been accompanied by the construction of a new one.
</P>
<P>
   The country has fallen into a kind of political and economic
limbo after Chavez pushed through a new constitution last year.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a power vacuum from the new constitution, Chavez's
leftist coalition hand-picked an interim legislature, a new supreme
court and a national electoral council in moves that critics
denounced as an assault on the separation of powers.
</P>
<P>
   The political uncertainty may help explain why, for the first
time in memory, a boom in international oil prices has not
translated into a recovery for the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his ''social revolution'' has been supported by
elections, critics say Chavez has meant less democracy for
Venezuela because of a dangerous concentration of power in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters insist the limbo will end with this month's
elections for president, a new unicameral legislature, governors,
mayors and local councils -- part of the new constitution's
requirement for ''re-legitimizing'' public powers.
</P>
<P>
   But the electoral process itself has come under fire for being
stacked against the opposition. Last week, the Carter Center issued
a report expressing concern over the ''high level of uncertainty
and distrust generated by the provisional nature of the legal
framework and the method of appointment of the electoral
authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the Bolivarian revolution looks more like mob rule.
When Arias tried to campaign in a Caracas slum last Friday, Chavez
supporters threw bricks, food and trash at him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Chavez asked his supporters to refrain from hurling
objects at Arias ''because indifference hurts more than a rock.''
He added: ''The people cannot understand how someone who once spoke
of revolution is now allied with the most rancid oligarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Venezuela's middle and upper classes have
flocked to Arias, seeing in him their best chance of unseating
Chavez. For them, hating the president has become a national
pastime.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest theater ticket in Caracas is a show called ''The
Re-constituents,'' a play on words of the pro-Chavez assembly that
rewrote the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   During a performance last week, comedian Laureano Marquez said
he'd like to see more of Chavez's longwinded speeches that often go
on for hours. ''While he talks, he's not governing, and that's a
strategic advantage,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez knows he doesn't need middle and upper class Venezuelans
to win elections.
</P>
<P>
   But to govern successfully, he does need their money and
expertise. Considering last year's capital flight of $5 billion and
widespread ''brain drain,'' they are giving neither.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Ochoa Antich, defense minister during Chavez's 1992
coup attempt, said most army officers have also thrown their
support behind Arias and are ready to wrest power away from Chavez
as soon as he loses popular support.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm almost sure that within a short time, there will be a
military conspiracy in Venezuela,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
