<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Web Site Contains His Cartoons  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE PFLEGER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore as the Terminator? In his dreams. Or,
it turns out, in his cartoon collection.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's official Web site now boasts some of Gore's
favorite jabs from his personal collection of local and national
editorial cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   There's Democrat Gore, after his makeover for the presidential
campaign, with wild new hair and a pair of lungs in hand -- a
reference to a sometimes criticized interview in which Gore said
that to win a candidate has to ''rip your opponent's lungs out and
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Hasta la vista, baby,'' a Terminator-esque Gore says.
</P>
<P>
   Or check out President Clinton thanking Gore -- on crutches -- for
hurting his Achilles' tendon in 1994 as part of an alleged plan
''to keep the focus on health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's collection includes some of the more gentle jokes he's
suffered throughout his years in public life. Absent are some of
the artists' favorite spoofs of Gore, including his more recent
claims about inventing the Internet or inspiring the movie ''Love
Story'' with his wife Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican presidential rival, George W. Bush, doesn't boast
a similar collection for cyber-consumption. But aides and friends
occasionally give the Texas governor political cartoons that poke
fun at him, said Bush spokesman Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has about 30 cartoons framed at the Governor's Mansion,
McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   No word on the size of Gore's collection, though over the years
he has accumulated many cartoons as gifts from friends and
sometimes the artists.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to take jokes about reinventing government best --
three out of five cartoon strips on his Web site feature the veep's
pet project.
</P>
<P>
   In one, bureaucrats from the ''Federal Bureau of Horse &AMP; Buggy
Right of Ways'' panic when they see Gore is coming.
</P>
<P>
   In another, Clinton sends Gore, a train engineer, to Capitol
Hill on the ''Big Government'' express for wind tunnel tests.
</P>
<P>
   And a brontosaurus symbolizing big government rents the Al Gore
workout video -- ''Streamlining Government'' -- to slim down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Finish chewing that branch, and let's begin,'' Gore barks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net: http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/OVP/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 0138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
