<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Gunned Down at S. Leone Rally  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- British troops moved to secure
Freetown's airport for the possible evacuation of its citizens
following clashes in the capital that left four dead. The country's
notorious rebel leader also disappeared from his U.N. guard,
prompting fears of more unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations late Monday began evacuating some of its 266
nonessential civilian employees. Another 55 were staying in
Freetown, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official, meanwhile, told the United
Nations that the U.S. Air Force was prepared to fly a battalion of
U.N. peacekeepers from Bangladesh -- roughly 700 to 800 soldiers --
in coming days. The United Nations wants to speed up deployment of
that battalion and two others scheduled to arrive by mid-July,
bringing the U.N. force up to its full strength of 11,100.
</P>
<P>
   Following the shootings in Freetown, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard
described Sierra Leone's peace process as being in ''deep
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ''All we can do is hope that this isn't the beginning of the
return to civil war,'' he said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of British citizens and other foreign nationals poured
into one of the city's two main hotels, clutching passports and
suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   A Sierra Leonean woman who said rebels had killed her husband
and four of their children last year waited in a hotel courtyard
with her 9-year-old daughter -- a British citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to lose her, too,'' she said, holding her
daughter's shoulder as she waited to send the girl away to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone, among the world's least developed countries, was
brutalized during eight years of civil war, which ended with a
peace accord last July that created a power-sharing government. In
principle, that deal included the rebel Revolutionary United Front
and its leader, Foday Sankoh, whose forces killed and maimed
thousands during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The preparations for a mass exodus of foreigners follow chaos
that broke out Monday in front of Sankoh's house. At least 5,000
marchers rallying for an end to hostilities overwhelmed U.N. troops
guarding the house, throwing rocks and singing a song with lyrics
calling for Sankoh to be beheaded and castrated.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel fighters, standing behind the U.N. troops, fired through
the U.N. ranks, spraying the crowd with automatic weapons and
rocket-propelled grenades.
</P>
<P>
   People began to flee in panic, and dozens were wounded in the
shooting and subsequent stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, soldiers from all the country's factions cruised the
streets of this West African coastal city, pointing machine guns
from their vehicle windows.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio broadcast late Monday, Sierra Leone's president,
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, deplored the violence and called on all armed
forces to leave the streets and return to their bases.
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted that Sankoh could not be located. ''An
investigation is now being undertaken to determine where he is,''
Kabbah said.
</P>
<P>
   Corinna Schuler, a Johannesburg, South Africa,-based journalist
for The Christian Science Monitor, said she took shelter in a small
building at Sankoh's compound during the stampede. Two Sierra
Leoneans who joined her were killed when rebels discovered them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will let you go because you are a journalist,'' the soldier
told her. ''I want you to tell those boys, they must never come to
protest at Foday Sankoh's house again.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan renewed his call for a
well-equipped rapid reaction force, but there appeared to be little
appetite for such intervention among Western countries.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative to U.S. troops, the United States approached
Nigeria on Monday about possibly sending in a force. The Nigerians
were being approached because of delays in deploying the three
remaining battalions of U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Sierra Leone has become increasingly chaotic
since a regional force pulled out last week.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. and rebel officials tried Sunday to assure residents that
the situation had calmed, despite a battle between their own forces
Saturday and 500 peacekeepers being held hostage by the RUF. At
least one peacekeeper is believed to be dead.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of British troops were in Freetown to prepare for
the possible evacuation of its citizens, although British Defense
Secretary Geoff Hoon did not rule out supporting U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
