<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charges To Be Filed Against Chmura  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) -- Charges will be filed next week in a
sexual assault case involving Green Bay Packers tight end Mark
Chmura.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Bucher said Monday that he received
preliminary test results from the state crime laboratory, and
charges would be filed next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're plowing ahead,'' he said. ''We're going to file
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucher said that the type and number of the charges ''and
against whom will be announced on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Chmura, 31, and a friend, Robert J. Gessert, 43, were arrested
April 10 by Hartland police. Chmura is accused of having sexual
intercourse with a 17-year-old girl at a post-prom party at
Gessert's house on April 9, while Gessert is accused of sexual
contact with an 18-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   Bucher said in court April 10 that both men could be charged
with third-degree sexual assault, a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were also focusing on two potential drinking-related
citations: for allowing or failing to prevent underage drinking on
one's premises, and for procuring, selling or dispensing alcohol to
minors.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Boyle, Chmura's attorney, said Monday that Chmura's
version of what happened was different from that of the 17-year-old
girl.
</P>
<P>
   ''When all is said and done, I think the picture is going to be
much different than what people think,'' Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Bucher and Boyle said they planned to meet this week before
Bucher makes his final decision on charges for Monday's previously
scheduled court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle said Bucher had not informed him of the results of the lab
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura's future with the Packers is in doubt. Packers coach Mike
Sherman recently said he was taking a ''wait-and-see attitude'' on
whether Chmura would be invited to the team's mini-camp which
starts May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura did not attend the Packers' mini-camp April 28-30 after
Sherman suggested Chmura should spend time with his family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
