<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz, Blazers Set for Game 2  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Utah Jazz have been running the same
old plays -- John Stockton to Karl Malone and back again -- for
nearly 15 years, and they're not about to shake things up after one
lopsided loss to the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just need to play our basketball, do the things we do to
make us good,'' Stockton said Monday as the Jazz prepared for
tonight's Game 2. ''To go and try to change that right now doesn't
make any sense. We know we have a good team. We have to play a
certain way to be good, and if we don't do that, we're awfully
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah certainly was that during the fourth quarter of Game 1
Sunday, when the Jazz missed nine of their first 10 shots and were
outscored 29-14 on the way to a 94-75 loss. Whether the short
recovery time after the first round was to blame, or it was
Portland's strong defense late in the game, the Jazz looked nothing
like the proud team that made the conference finals five times
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt like they were going to come out and deliver the first
blow and play with a lot of energy and intensity,'' Portland's
Scottie Pippen said before practice Monday. ''But they were not the
same team. ... We can expect a totally different team to come out
(tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers know that a loss tonight would cost them homecourt
advantage in the best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals and
make their 19-point Game 1 rout irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ''Game 2 is always the most important game for the home team,''
Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said. ''It's the one you have the
biggest chance of slipping up in, the best chance of a letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz coach Jerry Sloan knows his team is outmatched, however.
Utah has lost four straight to Portland this season and hasn't won
on the Blazers' home court in 13 tries.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is who we are,'' Sloan lamented. ''I'd like to say we're
a different team. I'd like to say, 'Well, all of a sudden Michael
Jordan is going to show up and play for us,' but that isn't the way
it works. We just have to go with who we are and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had another strong playoff performance, scoring 20 points
and exploiting a mismatch against Jazz guard Jeff Hornacek. The
6-foot-8 Pippen scored 13 points in the second half, most of them
while he was being defended by the 6-4 Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek, who also had trouble guarding Steve Smith in the high
post, said he expects to stay on Pippen. But Sloan criticized his
team for standing around and not helping Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everybody in America knew that they were going to post
us up, except four other guys watching,'' Sloan said. ''Yeah, they
made some shots, but their offensive rebounds kill you too. When
you stand and watch and then you don't rebound, what are you
supposed to do? Start switching players around? No, I don't do
that. Hornacek's a pretty good player. I have no less confidence in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, the only Utah starter who consistently worked hard and
contributed, is expected to play despite straining a ligament in
his left knee on a freak play late in the second quarter Sunday.
Malone was on the bench when teammate Armen Gilliam dived for a
ball and hit Malone's chair, causing him to twist his knee.
</P>
<P>
   Malone came out strong in the third quarter, scoring 12 points
to keep the Jazz in it until they wilted in the fourth. He finished
with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   Malone skipped Monday's practice, which amounted to little more
than shooting around. His no-show might have had less to do with
his knee than his annoyance at the media. Malone, who lost to
Jordan's and Pippen's Chicago Bulls twice in the NBA Finals, cursed
and cut an interview short after a reporter asked about Pippen's
dominance in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's fine,'' Hornacek said of Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know Karl will be there,'' Stockton said. ''If his
leg's broken, we know he'll be there and play well, and you can't
really stop and think about it. That's the way it is; just go
play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
