<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Reclimbing World's Hockey Ladder  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA BULMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- Two years ago, the United States
left the World Hockey Championships humbled and humiliated, on the
brink of relegation to sport's international 'B' pool.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Americans are headed for the quarterfinals, unbeaten in
the tournament with stunning wins over the NHL-stacked host Russian
team and the heavily favored Swedes, champions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the Americans have modest goals, they might find
themselves in the medals round if they manage to beat their
quarterfinal opponent, yet to be determined with second-round play
still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal this year was not to go down, to be eliminated,''
said American coach Lou Vairo, who worked behind the U.S. bench at
the 1984 Olympic Games in Sarajevo. ''Our second goal was to
qualify for the quarterfinals, and now we've done that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we have to win our game Thursday or we go home. But we
might be able to advance to the medal round.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to this year's success appears to be Vairo's laid-back
approach, allowing the players to just play.
</P>
<P>
   ''We tell them to handle the puck, play and have fun, enjoy
themselves,'' Vairo explained. ''We don't yell, we don't punish, we
don't bench people.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here to represent our country. The players give us their
commitment and full heart. We don't ask them to win a game, just
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who have won the championships just twice since
they began in 1920 -- the last time in 1960 -- finished a mediocre
sixth last year after the NHL's top stars turned down an invitation
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, with few exceptions, the United States' best
players skipped the annual championship in Europe or couldn't make
it because their teams were still locked into the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Americans ended up with 13 NHL grinders, and
filled out the rest of the lineup with minor league, college and
European league players.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary Flames veteran Phil Housley, the NHL's all-time American
scoring leader, has been the team's anchor, while four members from
last year's team have made the return trip: Vancouver forward Darby
Hendrickson, who is making his fifth appearance at the worlds;
Nashville forward David Legwand; Montreal defenseman Eric Weinrich;
and Boston College defenseman Mike Mottau.
</P>
<P>
   These championships represent a chance to restore the United
States' position as a world hockey power. The Americans have done
little to maintain their image since their stunning victory over
Canada in the final of the inaugural World Cup of Hockey in
Montreal in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   With virtually an identical team to '96 at the Nagano Games, the
United States failed to even medal, and sullied its image by
trashing rooms in the Olympic Village following its quarterfinal
elimination by the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, no Olympians went to Switzerland for the
world championships. The players who did go suffered a string of
embarrassments, including a humiliating 4-0 loss to Italy, a team
with no National Hockey Leaguers, and a historical 3-1 round-robin
defeat to France, coached by Herb Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the relegation round, the United States was forced to
compete in a last-chance tournament the following autumn in order
to claw its way back into the 'A' pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have two wonderful assistant coaches and I have great
players,'' said Vairo. ''I tell them everyday 'you guys are great.
I love you.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
