<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers Expect Desperate Penguins  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- It's Game 6, and the Pittsburgh Penguins are
in big trouble. They trail the series 3-2, and Jaromir Jagr is
hurting and might not play.
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar scenario to the Penguins, who found themselves
in this same predicament a year ago and escaped. Whether they do so
tonight depends greatly on Jagr, who has a leg injury -- and, of
course, the Philadelphia Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago tonight, the Penguins seemed headed for their first
playoff series victory over the Flyers, leading the Eastern
Conference semifinals 2-0 after winning twice on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But three games, three losses and an injured Jagr later, the
Penguins are one loss away from elimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers also find themselves one game away from the Eastern
Conference finals against the Devils, largely because of the
momentum they generated by winning twice in overtime last week in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we learned our lesson in the first two games,'' said
Flyers rookie defenseman Andy Delmore, who has five goals in the
series -- as many as Jagr. ''I don't believe there's overconfidence
in this locker room. We know that Pittsburgh has the great
firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Penguins don't have nearly as much without Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr had five goals in the first three games but, after
dominating Game 3 with two goals and an assist, was clearly off his
game in the Flyers' 2-1, five-overtime victory in Game 4. He lacked
his normal breakaway speed and had few good scoring chances despite
playing nearly 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr barely played because of an injured leg in the Flyers' 6-3
victory Sunday in Game 5, and didn't practice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the NHL's leading scorer in the playoffs and the
regular season estimated his chances of playing tonight as 90
percent. But there were mixed signals Monday from his teammates
concerning his availability.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr missed nearly a month of the regular season with thigh and
hamstring injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''As well as he has played, it would be natural to say, 'Oh, my,
what are we going to do if he can't play?' '' forward Robert Lang
said. ''But it's not a big deal. We've got to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins have rallied from 3-2 deficits to win a series four
times since 1991, with the most recent comeback occurring last year
against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Jagr unexpectedly came off the bench despite a thigh
injury to score the tying and winning goals as the Penguins rallied
to beat top-seeded New Jersey in Game 6. The Penguins then ousted
the Devils in Game 7 in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we can't rely on Jaromir Jagr to win the game for us,''
defenseman Darius Kasparaitis said. ''I hope history is on our side
again, but you can't look at it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Flyers will go into the game expecting the worst:
Jagr in uniform and the Penguins desperate to keep the series, and
their season, going.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect he'll come out playing,'' coach Craig Ramsay said.
''He's a great competitor. Everyone's seen him over the years come
up with big games at big times. We expect the best from Jaromir
Jagr.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Flyers forward Rick Tocchet, a one-time Jagr teammate in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ''Knowing him, he'll throw his A-plus game at us,'' Tocchet
said. ''I think he was disappointed in the overtime game and
Sunday's game. He's a little frustrated, but he'll get his 48 hours
of rest and give it all he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Flyers already know they can win in Pittsburgh -- their
two overtime victories gave them control of the series -- they seem
especially eager to avoid a Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to play equally desperate to get it over with because
we definitely don't want to come back for Game 7,'' rookie
goaltender Brian Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   If Jagr can't play, the Penguins need production from several
forwards who haven't been very effective in the series -- namely
Josef Beranek and Rene Corbet -- or a goal or two from Alexei
Kovalev, who has only one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect to win the games here and losing hurt us a lot,
especially the two overtime games,'' defenseman Darius Kasparaitis
said. ''But I think it's time our luck turned around for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
