<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hockey Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Tuesday, May 9:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia at Pittsburgh (7 p.m. EDT). The Flyers, leading
3-2, seek to complete their comeback from an 0-2 deficit in their
Eastern Conference semifinal series.
STAR:
Monday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Petr Sykora, Devils, scored 18 seconds after the opening
faceoff in New Jersey's 3-0 series-clinching win over Toronto.
SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   According to the Elias Sports Bureau, Toronto's six shots on
goal in Monday night's 3-0 series-ending loss to New Jersey were
the fewest shots in any NHL game since the start of the expansion
era in 1967.
SIGNINGS:
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus Blue Jackets, who start play in the 2000-01 season,
signed free-agent forwards Jonathan Schill and Mathieu Darche on
Monday, bringing the number of players under contract with the NHL
expansion team to three. The team signed Niagara University goalie
Greg Gardner last week.
SLUMP:
</P>
<P>
   When the Toronto Maple Leafs lost 3-0 to New Jersey on Monday
night, it guaranteed that they would not win the NHL championship
for the 33rd straight year. Toronto has only reached the conference
finals four times since its 1967 Stanley Cup title, including last
year's loss to Buffalo.
STAYING IN THE STATES:
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's elimination from the playoffs assures that the Stanley
Cup will be won by a franchise from the United States for a record
seventh straight season, following Montreal's victory in 1993. The
only other time U.S. teams won the Cup six years in a row was from
1936-41.
SIDELINED:
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Maple Leafs defenseman Alexander Karpovtsev, who missed
the final two periods of Game 5 after being slashed in the ribs,
did not play Monday night in the season-ending 3-0 loss against New
Jersey. Karpovtsev was injured Saturday night when Devils forward
Claude Lemieux slashed him in the ribs from behind. The injury led
to a rapid heartbeat and forced Karpovtsev to sit out the rest of
the game. Karpovtsev was taken to a hospital for precautionary
reasons and was back at Air Canada Centre following the game.
SOUR FEELINGS:
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Penguins remained angry Monday at Philadelphia
defenseman Luke Richardson for shooting a puck directly into
defenseman Bob Boughner's chest, with Boughner promising to get
back at Richardson. Richardson teed up a slap shot from the red
line and fired it into Boughner's chest during the second period of
the Flyers' 6-3 victory Sunday. The Penguins felt Richardson's shot
was a deliberate intent to injure. Richardson drew a two-minute
penalty for unsportsmanlike conduct.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't shoot the puck. It is an ongoing problem for our
hockey club. They want to see the back of the net before ... when
you play a good defensive club, they take care of the play.'' --
Toronto coach Pat Quinn after his team's NHL record-low six shots
in a season-ending 3-0 loss to New Jersey on Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 0203 </TRAILER>
