<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils 3, Maple Leafs 0  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Eliminating the Toronto Maple Leafs
and getting to the conference finals for the first time since
winning the Stanley Cup in 1995 was as easy as 3-2-1 for the New
Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   That's actually a cumulative 3-2-1, or six, the NHL record-low
number of shots Toronto had against Martin Brodeur on Monday night
as the Devils posted a 3-0 win to clinch their best-of-seven
Eastern Conference semifinal series 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a great effort,'' said Devils defenseman Scott
Stevens, whose play was the biggest reason the Maple Leafs never
got going offensively. ''We didn't give them anything. We didn't
want to give them life. We didn't want to go back to Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   Any hope the Maple Leafs had of forcing a Game 7 in Toronto on
Wednesday night evaporated in the opening 18 seconds when Petr
Sykora took a kick pass from Patrik Elias and wristed it past
goaltender Curtis Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   That was the only goal the Devils would need as Toronto went
meekly in extending its Stanley Cup drought to 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   The only real scoring chance the Maple Leafs had came 7:35 into
the game when Brodeur swatted away a backhander by Igor Korolev on
Toronto's first shot. The Leafs would add two more shots in the
first period, two in the second and one early in the third, and
that would be it.
</P>
<P>
   The Elias Sports Bureau said the six shots were the fewest
permitted in a regular season or playoff game since the start of
the expansion era in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to shoot, but it's tough to shoot when you're
outside the red line and you have the puck,'' said Maple Leafs
captain Mats Sundin, who did not score in the series. ''We just
didn't create enough chances. We spent pretty much the whole series
in our own end and in the neutral zone.''
</P>
<P>
   While injuries to Yanic Perreault, Bryan Berard and Nik Antropov
hurt the Maple Leafs, New Jersey's defense was outstanding,
possibly the best it has been since winning the Cup in 1995 under
Jacques Lemaire.
</P>
<P>
   The team since then has gone through one disappointment after
another, missing the playoffs in 1996 and then being eliminated
early the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a long time,'' Brodeur said after picking up his
second shutout of the series and eighth in his playoff career.
''We've had a lot of disappointments in the past. We're kind of
turning the page. Winning the first round was not enough. We're
there and we're tasting it. Hopefully, we'll keep going the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey will play the winner of the Philadelphia-Pittsburgh
series which Philadelphia leads 3-2 with Game 6 at Pittsburgh
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a big step for us, but we have a lot of work ahead of
us,'' Stevens said. ''It was a great accomplishment after our past
history of having trouble in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took command of the game 25 seconds into the second
period when defenseman Ken Daneyko and Sykora set up Jason Arnott
in front for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie John Madden closed out the scoring with an empty net goal
with six seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's previous playoff low for shots was 13 in a 3-0 loss to
Philadelphia on April 15, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't shoot the puck,'' Leafs coach Pat Quinn said. ''It
is an ongoing problem for our hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leafs forward Garry Valk said the shots total wasn't
right.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we probably ended up with 13 or 14,'' he said. ''They
always do that in this rink. They don't count as many as they have
so it looks like you're not in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' old record for fewest shots allowed was 13 in a 4-2
loss to Pittsburgh last year.
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Larry Robinson tried not to look at the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like watching water boil,'' he said. ''You keep watching
it and it's not going to boil. I think there were three minutes
left and I looked up and thought it was 16. I said it can't be six,
but I looked up again and it was six. That's quite an
accomplishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
