<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korean Students Intrude US Embassy  </HEADLINE>
By JAE-SUK YOO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Three leftist students, shouting
''Yankee go home,'' jumped the wall of the U.S. Embassy in central
Seoul today but were soon arrested, South Korean police said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost simultaneously, 19 other students were also arrested
outside the embassy for staging an anti-U.S. demonstration, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police indicated that they would file formal charges against
them.
</P>
<P>
   The three students, assisted by three others, scaled the front
wall of the embassy and scattered dozens of leaflets demanding an
end to the U.S. military presence in South Korea, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said one student tossed leaflets from the top the
stone wall, while two others ran around the embassy compound,
shouting ''Yankee go home.''
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen South Korean police entered the embassy compound
and hauled away the protesters in 10 minutes, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the students came close to the main embassy building
which was guarded by U.S. marines, they said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare trespassing of the U.S. facility by South Korean
activists. The embassy is heavily guarded by South Korean police,
and anti-U.S. student activism has little public support.
</P>
<P>
   In the leaflets, the students, identifying themselves as members
of the ''anti-U.S. youth salvation group,'' alleged that the United
States rules South Korea as a colony.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States must stop its interference policy and
withdraw from this land before it is too late,'' the leaflets said.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean leftist students echo the policies of communist
North Korea. They claim that the presence of the 37,000 U.S. troops
in South Korea hinders unification of the divided Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The students also demanded Washington's apology for the alleged
mass killings of unarmed South Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers
during the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   They, in particular, demanded a speedy U.S. Investigation of the
alleged massacre of hundreds of South Korean civilians at No Gun
Ri, a hamlet in central South Korea, in July 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Citing dozens of surviving villagers and American veterans, The
AP reported in September that retreating U.S. soldiers
machine-gunned some 400 civilians cowering under a railroad tunnel
at No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and South Korean governments then began investigations
into the No Gun Ri incident. The U.S. government said it would
finish an investigation before the 50th anniversary this year of
the Korean War on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   ''Marking the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of the Korean
War, people's anti-U.S. voice becomes louder and louder,'' students
said in the leaflets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 0241 </TRAILER>
