<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Center Stage'  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTY LEMIRE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Center Stage'' works best when it's about the dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet scenes are choreographed and performed exquisitely,
whether they are traditional performances of ''Romeo and Juliet''
or more contemporary creations. They are breathtaking and glorious
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, in between the dance sequences, the actors are
allowed to talk. This is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers from the American Ballet Theater and other prestigious
companies play some of the film's key roles. But just because they
can dance doesn't mean they can act. And usually, they can't.
</P>
<P>
   ''Center Stage'' is about a group of young dancers who join the
fictitious American Ballet Academy, the nation's premier school,
which feeds into the world's greatest ballet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Like ''Fame,'' there is an opening sequence in which we see each
of the main characters get accepted into the academy. And because
there is entirely too much exposition, we learn who each of them is
pretty quickly.
</P>
<P>
   There's Jody (Amanda Schull, a dancer with the San Francisco
Ballet who looks eerily like Jennie Garth from ''Beverly Hills
90210''), who is beautiful, blond and winsome. She finds out fast
that her body and form aren't ideal and doubts whether she belongs
in the academy.
</P>
<P>
   Saucy Eva (Zoe Saldana) comes from the tough streets of Boston
and has little respect for the academy's rigid ways. She shows up
late for class, chews gum and sasses the instructors, but is
amazingly talented.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck-up Maureen (Susan May Pratt), every instructor's favorite,
has perfect form. She also has a pushy stage mother, an eating
disorder and no personality.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie (Sascha Radetsky of the American Ballet Theater)
literally walks into a room of fellow newcomers and says, ''I just
got in from Seattle. My girlfriend dumped me for leaving her
there.'' Not much mystery there. He's one of the few straight male
dancers and has a crush on Jody.
</P>
<P>
   But Jody -- and every other girl -- lusts after Cooper (Ethan
Stiefel, an ABT principal dancer), a charismatic principal with the
American Ballet Company and a budding choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows them as they struggle, compete, fall in love
and get their hearts broken. It's fun to watch their various
methods of breaking in fresh toe shoes -- pounding them on the
floor, in the shower, in door jambs, with cigarette lighters -- and
spying on their rigorous rehearsals is sort of a voyeuristic
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Center Stage'' was filmed at Lincoln Center and throughout New
York, and director Nick Hytner often asked the professional dancers
in the cast for input, so many of the off-stage moments ring true.
</P>
<P>
   All the adults, though, are two-dimensionally single-minded and
uncaring.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gallagher, one of the few real actors in the cast, plays
Jonathan, the rigid academy director. Like Debbie Allen's character
in ''Fame,'' he gives an intimidating welcome speech to his new
students. Later, he has discouraging words for Jody, such as, ''I
just want you to really think if this is the right place for you.''
That's about the extent of his character.
</P>
<P>
   We know, of course, that Jody will shine by the end. The outcome
of all the various plots are pretty easy to figure out from the
start. Only the dancing makes getting there bearable.
</P>
<P>
   ''Center Stage,'' a Columbia Pictures release, was written by
Carol Heikkinen (''The Thing Called Love,'' ''Empire Records'').
Susan Stroman and Christopher Wheeldon were the choreographers. It
is rated PG-13 for language and some sensuality, and runs 1 hour
and 53 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
