<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Announces Internet Initiatives  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Associated Press is introducing a series of
Internet initiatives to enhance the value of its state news reports
and political coverage to members, president and CEO Louis D.
Boccardi told the AP annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of 1,546 member newspapers gathered Monday on
the first day of the Newspaper Association of America's convention.
</P>
<P>
   AP Chairman Donald E. Newhouse opened the session, which
included a conversation between Boccardi and Alan Diaz, the
photographer who took the news cooperative's photographs of Elian
Gonzalez being removed from the home of Miami relatives last month.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the program were a panel on the 2000 election and talks
by Vice President Al Gore and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi said the coming year would bring ''an ever-stronger
world and national news report; further exploration of the
opportunities and challenges the Internet presents, (and) sharper
focus on better performance on all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   He announced the introduction of the AP Election Center, ''for
online readers who want as much detail as they can get on the
candidates, the issues and the campaigns from the White House to
the statehouse.'' This will be an Internet service that members can
link to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   AP will also offer a site called AP Politics, designed as a
resource for reporters and editors covering campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet initiative called Your AP will allow editors to
access election results in November as soon as the come into the AP
system, rather than waiting for updates to move on the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll know what we know when we know it,'' Boccardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Your AP will be an ongoing resource that keeps members up to
date on the AP news report and developments within the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi said state news reports soon will be delivered in a
format that will enable editors of online editions to post them
easily to newspaper Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The AP's continuing commitment to improving state reports has
led to two new Chicago-based positions, Boccardi said. One is a new
writing coach -- AP's third -- and the other is a new deputy director
of state news.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Gore said he was open to a change in federal
rules that prohibit the same company from owning a newspaper and TV
or radio station in the same area, although he noted that it is up
to the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also said he supported revising estate tax laws that create
hardships for families trying to pass a newspaper on from one
generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who spoke at the event's luncheon, said President
Clinton was approaching his summit talks with Russian President
Vladimir Putin with an open mind on the subject of U.S. missile
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton decides later this year whether to proceed with an
anti-missile program, he will weigh potential threats as well as
the merits of the technology and the costs, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who will meet with Clinton in Moscow June 4-5, strongly
opposes even the limited program Clinton is considering -- 100
launchers and improved radar designed to stop intercontinental
ballistic missiles that some administration officials are convinced
North Korea, Iran and other so-called ''rogue states'' could fire
at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, the photographer, said on the morning the 6-year-old Elian
was seized by federal agents, ''I had the instinct, the hunch, that
something was going to go down.'' Diaz said when the raid began he
sprinted into the house and set up in the room where the boy was
being hidden in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   His overriding memory of the raid? ''All I could hear, and all I
could remember, was Elian crying,'' Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi also moderated a discussion of political campaigns with
three AP correspondents. The panel, titled ''A Conversation:
Campaign 2000,'' included Walter Mears, AP vice president and
Washington columnist; Ron Fournier, chief political writer in
Washington; and Marc Humbert, New York State political editor based
in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Mears noted candidates try to avoid negative attacks on their
opponents these days because they think voters don't like it. But
Fournier pointed out that ''the new form of negative campaigning
seems to be to accuse your opponent of going negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the meeting began with the announcement of election
results for the board of directors, held by all-mail balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Four incumbents and three new members were elected to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Elected to new terms were John J. Curley, chairman and CEO,
Gannett Co. Inc., Wilmington (Del.) News-Journal; Newhouse,
president, Advance Publications Inc., Newark (N.J.) Star-Ledger;
John W. Madigan, chairman, president and CEO, Tribune Co., Chicago
Tribune and Orage Quarles III, publisher, Raleigh (N.C.) News &AMP;
Observer.
</P>
<P>
   New members are Walter E. Hussman Jr., president and CEO, WEHCO
Media Inc., Arkansas Democrat-Gazette; Julie Inskeep Walda,
publisher, Fort Wayne (Ind.) Journal Gazette; and Sue Mayborn,
president and publisher, Temple (Texas) Daily Telegram. Walda was
selected to fill one year left in the term of Richard J.
Harrington, who is stepping down. Mayborn was selected to represent
a city of less than 50,000 population.
</P>
<P>
   At a reorganization meeting later in the day, Newhouse,
president of Advance Publications Inc. and of The Star-Ledger of
Newark, N.J., was re-elected chairman of the AP. David E. Easterly,
president and COO of Cox Enterprises Inc., representing the Dayton
(Ohio) Daily News, was elected vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Boccardi was re-elected president and chief executive officer of
the news cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Other AP management officers re-elected to one-year terms were
Patrick T. O'Brien, senior vice president and chief financial
officer; James M. Donna, vice president and secretary; and vice
presidents Vincent J. Alabiso, Claude E. Erbsen, Mears, John W.
Reid, Thomas E. Slaughter, Wick Temple and James R. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan P. Wolman, executive editor, also was elected vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel M. Boruch was re-elected treasurer, and Salvatore Focella
and Ann Randolph were re-elected assistant treasurers. Other AP
management officers re-elected were assistant secretaries Lilo
Jedelhauser and Greg Groce.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
