<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Tuesday, May 9, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   WWP Nears Acquisition of Y&AMP;R
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Britain's WPP Group PLC would become the world's
largest advertising and marketing company under terms of an
agreement in principle which sources say the company has reached to
buy Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. The deal valued at about $4.7 billion in
stock is still subject to approval by the boards of both companies
and their shareholders and could still fall apart, sources said.
The deal would be the richest ever in the advertising industry,
where multinational companies are choosing agencies with the reach
and expertise to deliver their sales messages to consumers around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Lego, Spielberg Team on Movie Kit
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Steven Spielberg is teaming up with toy industry
giant Lego to create a digital movie-making kit that lets children
create and edit their own films. The Lego Studios Steven Spielberg
MovieMaker will not appear in stores until November. The
film-making kit is the latest example of Lego's aggressive move
toward integrating technology with its classic building blocks. It
already has a number of popular CD-ROM games in stores and also has
had great success with its Lego Mindstorms, high-tech robots that
can be manipulated using microcomputers.
</P>
<P>
   Napster Copyright Defense Rejected
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A judge has rejected Napster Inc.'s defense
against a music industry lawsuit that it is protected by digital
copyright law. The Recording Industry Association of America sued
Napster, alleging copyright infringement and related state law
violations. The association accused Napster of encouraging users of
the company's software and computer servers to trade copyrighted
music online without permission. Napster said the company's service
is legal because it does not directly provide the copyrighted music
-- only the means to get it.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, GE Team on Satellite TV
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- BellSouth Corp. and a unit of General Electric
reportedly will team to offer digital television via satellite in
the telephone company's nine-state turf. BellSouth would become the
first regional phone company to compete with the satellite services
such as the DISH Network and DirecTV, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution reported today. The deal would expand
BellSouth's potential market for entertainment services from a
handful of cities to 14 million households.
</P>
<P>
   BMW Agrees To Sale of Rover Cars
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Germany's BMW agreed today to sell the ailing
Rover car group to a British consortium that mounted a dramatic,
come-from-behind effort to take over the business and save
thousands of jobs. The Phoenix consortium, headed by former Rover
chief executive John Towers, said contracts have been signed. BMW
said the ''symbolic purchase price'' was 10 pounds, or $16.
However, BMW added that it has agreed to lend Phoenix $765 million
to help the consortium get Rover off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Down 87; Dow Off 4
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower in quiet early trading
today as investors assessed the market for technology stocks after
yesterday's sharp drop. Cisco Systems, which was pummeled following
a negative article in Barron's magazine, again slid 1{ to 61\. But
with few major economic indicators coming out and the next meeting
of the Federal Reserve Board a week off, stock trading has been
slow in recent sessions. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 4.24 at 10,599.39. On the NYSE,
decliners led advancers 1,253-1,062. And the Nasdaq composite index
was down 87.79 at 3,581.59.
</P>
<P>
