<P>
   Futures' Stock Trading Gets Support
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Americans may soon have a new financial product
to buy and sell: futures contracts on individual stocks. The push
to approve single-stock futures got a boost yesterday with
endorsements at a U.S. Senate hearing by federal regulators and the
heads of Chicago's big financial exchanges -- who are eager to offer
anything that might help fend off the threat from upstart
electronic challengers. If a small number of regulatory issues are
settled, single-stock futures could be put to a vote in Congress by
October.
</P>
<P>
   NTT DoCoMo To Buy Into KPN Mobile
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese mobile phone giant NTT DoCoMo Inc. is
buying a 15 percent stake in a Dutch cellular phone company for
$4.63 billion to gain a foothold in Europe. NTT DoCoMo said today
it expects to complete the purchase of a stake in KPN Mobile NV,
the cellular phone subsidiary Royal KPN NV, as early as June. The
stake in KPN Mobile will give NTT DoCoMo a platform across Europe
and Asia from which it will be able to develop high-speed, third
generation mobile phones, which will allow users to surf the
Internet and watch videos.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Wins Round in Java Suit
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Microsoft was victorious yesterday in its
battle with Sun Microsystems over the Java programming language as
a federal judge dismissed Sun's claim that Microsoft had broken
copyright laws. Sun had sued Microsoft for designing a Windows-only
version of Sun's Java technology, which was incompatible with other
software. Sun said it represented both copyright infringement as
well as a breach of their licensing contract. The judge said the
dispute was solely a contractual one. Sun's breach-of-contract
claims against Microsoft are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Japan PC Shipments Exceed TVs
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The number of personal computers shipped in Japan
jumped 32 percent during fiscal 1999, exceeding shipments of
televisions for the first time. Computer makers shipped 9.94
million PCs to Japanese distributors during the 12 months ended
March 31, up from 7.38 million in fiscal 1998, the Japan Electronic
Industry Development Association said today. By comparison, 11.1
million PCs were sold in the United States in just the last three
months of the period, according to research firm Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle Unveils $199 Web Device
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Unbowed by the failure of a bare-bones computer
five years ago, Oracle Corp. chairman Larry Ellison unveiled a $199
Internet machine yesterday targeted at the education and consumer
markets. Unlike a personal computer, the device lacks a hard drive.
Instead, users who connect it to the Internet will be able to check
e-mail and surf the Web. Ellison said Oracle, the giant database
software company based in Redwood City, Calif., will donate more
than 1,100 of the machines to 23 Dallas schools.
</P>
<P>
   Most Asian Markets Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower today on
the back of an overnight tumble in the U.S.-based Nasdaq Stock
Market. Japan's Nikkei Stock Average fell 355.42 points, or 1.95
percent, to close at 17,844.54, the lowest finish since Oct. 28. In
Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index fell 124.10 points, or 0.8 percent,
closing at 14,776.90. The Hang Seng fell more than 250 points at
one point before recovering slightly on bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Jobless claims	   Thursday: Retail sales
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Producer price index
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Business inventories
</P>
<P>
   AP Financial NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA
