<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tech stocks gave up early advances and turned
lower in quiet trading this morning, while blue chip shares edged
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Resuming Monday's trading pattern, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 6.85 at 10,610.48 in midmorning trading, while the
Nasdaq composite index was off 70.98 at 3,598.40.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 8.20 at 1,415.97.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks had started the day slightly higher but resumed
their decline as traders took profits from a moderate rally on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which was pummeled Monday following a negative
article in Barron's magazine, fell another 1} to 61 in early
trading, and Hewlett-Packard fell 3 11/16 to 132. Other tech shares
also edged lower. Cisco reports earnings after the close of trading
today.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, which announced earnings that beat analyst estimates,
rose 1 11/16 to 65 1/16 in early trading.
</P>
<P>
   With few major economic indicators coming out and the next
meeting of the Federal Reserve Board a week off, stock trading has
been slow in recent sessions. Monday was the quietest session of
the year so far.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 7.23 today at 492.23.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues edged out advancing ones by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 291.96 million
shares, slightly ahead of Tuesday's quiet levels.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas markets also had declines. In Tokyo, the benchmark
Nikkei stock average tumbled 355.42 points, or 1.95 percent, to
close at 17,844.54 points, its lowest level in six months.
</P>
<P>
   European stock indexes were lower in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
