<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frequent Fliers Favor Continental  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Readers of Frequent Flyer magazine ranked
Continental as their favorite airline.
</P>
<P>
   Continental was top-rated for both long-haul and short-haul
flights, leading second-place TWA in the poll conducted by the
magazine and the survey firm J.D. Power and Associates. The
magazine announced the results Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Continental scored 123 points for flights of more than 500
miles, followed by TWA at 121, Southwest with 108 and United with
the industry average of 100 points on the magazine's scoring
system.
</P>
<P>
   For the shorter flights Continental received 122 points, TWA had
117 and Southwest 107.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine declined to make public scores of airlines falling
below the industry average, but listed them in alphabetical order.
</P>
<P>
   On short-hauls they were America West, American, Delta,
Northwest, US Airways and United. The same lines fell below average
on long routes except United, which scored right at the average.
</P>
<P>
   Factors contributing to the scores were on-time performance,
ease of airport check-in, flight attendants, seating comfort, gate
factors, flight availability and scheduling, aircraft interior,
frequent-flier programs and food service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1201 </TRAILER>
