<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Drops 60; Dow Off 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in quiet trading today as technology
shares gave up early gains and pulled other market sectors lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 60.31 at 3,609.07, while the
Dow Jones industrial average was down 3.35 at 10,600.28.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 6.77 at 1,417.40.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks had started the day slightly higher but resumed
their decline as traders took profits from Friday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which was pummeled Monday following a negative
article in Barron's magazine, fell 1/16 to 62 11/16, and
Hewlett-Packard fell 1 13/16 to 133~. Other tech shares also edged
lower. Cisco reports earnings after the close of trading today.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the downtrend in tech stocks, shares of 3Com rose
sharply after the maker of computer network equipment said it would
complete the spinoff of Palm Inc. several months ahead of schedule.
3Com shares rose 4 7/16 to 48[ while Palm shares fell 3{ to 28}.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, which announced earnings that beat analyst estimates,
rose 1 5/16 to 53 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   With few major economic indicators coming out and the next
meeting of the Federal Reserve Board a week off, stock trading has
been slow in recent sessions. Monday was the quietest session of
the year so far.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 7.30 today at 492.78.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues edged out advancing ones by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 412.77 million
shares, slightly ahead of Tuesday's quiet levels.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas markets also had declines. In Tokyo, the benchmark
Nikkei stock average tumbled 355.42 points, or 1.95 percent, to
close at 17,844.54 points, its lowest level in six months.
</P>
