<HEADLINE> SUNY chancellor announces economic development post  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The State University of New York is creating
an administrative position to foster development between businesses
and the university system, Chancellor Robert King said.
</P>
<P>
   The job will help promote SUNY as an engine of economic
development, King said in today's edition of the Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   The economic development position will be responsible for
overseeing creation of a database that would include research
specialties, academic programs and grants at each of the system's
64 schools. The database would be accessible to corporations
interested in moving into the state or retraining existing workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is an incredible quality and diversity in the
universities in our state that our business community hardly knows
about,'' King told an audience at the annual forum of the Public
Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   King expects to name someone to the post within the next few
weeks. SUNY spokesman E.J. McMahon said a salary has not yet been
determined for the new post.
</P>
</TEXT>
