<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators want parents asked before kids are mined for marketingsurveys  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elementary school children were asked to fill
out a 27-page booklet called ''My All About Me Journal'' that was
really a marketing survey for a cable television channel.
</P>
<P>
   Technology firms have provided schools with free computers and
Internet access in return for the right to monitor students' Web
activity by age, gender and ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   In neither of these cases or countless others were parents asked
if they wanted their children to be mined for marketing
information, Sens. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and Richard Shelby,
R-Ala., said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two are pushing legislation aimed at shielding children from
marketing and advertising research conducted in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our children should be instilled with knowledge, not tapped
for information on their spending habits. Their privacy, and that
of their parents should be respected, not exploited,'' Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would require that parents be told in writing
exactly what information about their children will disclosed in a
commercial survey, whether the child can be identified by the
information, to whom the information will go and for what purpose
it will be used. Parents will also be told how much class time will
be spent filling out the survey and what the school expects to get
from the business in return.
</P>
<P>
   Parents would then have to give written permission in order for
their children to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is strictly limited to commercial surveys, Shelby
stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It focuses on the most questionable conduct by specifically
exempting certain activities such as curriculum development, test
assessment, and college and other post-secondary education
recruiting efforts, among others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both senators acknowledged that financially strapped schools
often have little choice but to accept business ''gifts'' with
strings attached. This bill would simply let parents in on the
process. ''Would you allow them to come into your home and question
your 7-year-old without your permission?'' Dodd asked.
</P>
<P>
   The measure will be introduced early this week as an amendment
to a sweeping bill regulating virtually all federal education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   While that bill appears seriously stalled, the amendment will at
least get people talking about the issue of privacy in schools, the
senators said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1301 </TRAILER>
