<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Govt. Workers Get Cheaper insurance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Long-term health care insurance would be made
available at lower cost to federal employees and retirees,
including the military, under legislation passed unanimously
Tuesday by the House.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which goes to the Senate, would use the buying power
of the huge federal and military work force to attract lower-cost
bids from private insurers to provide the coverage. Some estimates
indicate costs could be reduced by 15 percent to 20 percent,
supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   Those eligible for the program would include spouses, children,
adopted children, stepchildren and stepparents of federal civilian
and military employees and retirees. They would be responsible for
paying the premiums and could choose to have them deducted from
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsor, Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla., said the
measure will ''bring peace of mind for many Americans by reducing
their long-term health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4040.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
