<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government To Track Sea Bass  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is launching a system to track
a fish that has become increasingly popular in U.S. restaurants
under the name of Chilean sea bass.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation experts have become concerned that the sharp rise
in popularity of this fish is leading to overfishing. The new
tracking system, being implemented internationally, will help
determine the actual amount of fish being caught.
</P>
<P>
   The fish, also known as Patagonian and Antarctic toothfish, are
caught in the Southern Ocean, which surrounds Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. National Marine Fisheries Service, part of the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, will handle the monitoring
effort, which will require documentation of all of these fish
imported into the country or shipped through the U.S. to another
country.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Dalton, director of NOAA Fisheries, said ''tracking and
monitoring this import product will discourage unlawful harvest and
give U.S. consumers confidence that the seafood they eat is legally
and sustainably caught.''
</P>
<P>
   International management of toothfish is organized by the
Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living
Resources. Member of the organization are countries that fish or do
research in the Southern Ocean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1332 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000509.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tech Shares Pull Europe Stocks Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks were dragged lower Tuesday as
technology shares responded to jitters in the United States, and
the telecommunications sector continued to suffer from negative
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Most European bourses opened to losses after waking up 4 percent
drop on the Nasdaq Stock Market Monday. Shares were down another 2
percent Tuesday. Volume was low, however, as investors remained
nervous about tech volatility and a potential U.S. interest rate
hike later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Europe doesn't seem to be following Nasdaq down as much as
could be expected,'' said Sharon Coombs, analyst at HSBC. ''It is
really telecoms, which are the flagship of Europe's new economy,
that are hurting European bourses.''
</P>
<P>
   The telecom sector fell Tuesday on fears over mobile licenses
fees and concerns over further consolidation in the sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has become much more difficult for European telecom stocks
after the expense of the U.K. license bids and the breakdown of the
merger between Telefonica and KPN,'' said HSBC's Coombs. ''They'll
need much stronger growth to justify themselves now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, was down 7.64 points at
433.65. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 102.4 points at
5,182.7.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell
6.62 points to 386.29, while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index fell
111.8 points to 4,926.3
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 1.5 percent to 6,123.8, as
interest rate worries and technology and telecom losses took their
toll, and Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index also fell 1.7 percent on tech
and telecom losses to 7,280.54. The Paris CAC-40 Index was down 2.2
percent to 6,369.61.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1338 </TRAILER>
