<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In rematch, conservative assemblyman has help in challenge againstRoukema  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- No stranger to contested primaries, Rep. Marge
Roukema had an uncomfortably close brush with defeat two years ago
when she beat fellow Republican Scott Garrett by 1,700 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett is back, and this year he has help. The Club for Growth,
a new group advocating ''the Reagan vision of limited government
and lower taxes,'' is helping him raise money. Former presidential
candidate Steve Forbes endorsed him, as did Republican Rep. Tom
Coburn of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Roukema, the longest-serving woman in the House, has stood for
years as a symbol of a perennially threatened species in Congress --
the moderate Northeast Republican. Unlike most House members, she
draws opposition in primaries even after two decades in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why do you think they do this to me all the time?'' Roukema,
R-Ridgewood, mused during a recent interview in her office, noting
that fellow New Jersey moderates Rodney Frelinghuysen and Bob
Franks do not attract the same degree of intraparty competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I weren't a woman,'' she continued, ''they wouldn't be
doing this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her critics say Roukema is a target at election time because of
her record, not her gender.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're asking voters to look at her record for 20 years, and to
look at my record for 10 years,'' said Garrett, 40, a member of the
state Assembly since 1990. ''If you do, you'll see she has a record
of raising taxes many times, of opposing tax cuts a number of
times, and increasing the role of federal government in the areas
of health care and education.''
</P>
<P>
   Roukema, 70, insists she is fiscally conservative but in line
with her district on social issues. She points to endorsements by
Republican leaders, including House Speaker Dennis Hastert, to
prove her conservative credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Roukema says her 1998 response to Garrett's challenge was too
subdued. ''This year we're certainly going to wage a very
aggressive campaign, and have been,'' she said. ''I'm not letting
anything slip by.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Roukema-Garrett match will be favored in the
fall against Democrat Linda Mercurio, an adjunct professor at Seton
Hall Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Roukema and Garrett share a party affiliation, but little else:
</P>
<P>
   --Roukema supports abortion rights, which Garrett opposes.
</P>
<P>
   --Garrett favors school vouchers, which Roukema considers a
threat to public education.
</P>
<P>
   --Garrett would allow people to put a substantial amount of their
Social Security payroll taxes into privately run investment
accounts. Roukema said diverting money to private accounts could
undermine the whole idea of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   --Roukema supports the main campaign finance reform proposal
pending in the House; Garrett says it would protect incumbents and
limit free speech.
</P>
<P>
   --Garrett favors term limits, which are opposed by Roukema,
seeking her 11th term in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Roukema and her five Republican colleagues from New Jersey last
year helped Democrats approve a controversial health insurance
reform measure that included a new right to file lawsuits. Roukema
stands proudly behind that vote as a blow for ''patient
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett, by contrast, says congressional efforts to regulate
health insurance are fundamentally misguided. ''I believe that
federal regulation of insurance should end, and go back to
states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the two candidates disagree on Roukema's
record on taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett accuses Roukema of voting for ''some of the largest tax
increases in U.S. history.'' But Roukema voted against the tax
hikes implemented under President Clinton in 1993 and President
Bush in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on the matter, Garrett said Roukema supported a 1982 tax
increase -- one written chiefly by Republican Sen. Bob Dole and
signed by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Roukema, ''He's campaigning against me now for
something that was passed in 1982?''
</P>
<P>
   She highlighted the tax cuts she supported, from Reagan's tax
cut in 1981 to the GOP's unsuccessful $792 billion proposal in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Leila Bate, executive director of the Club for Growth,
acknowledged that Roukema has voted with her party to pass large
tax cuts, but added: ''She only does it after much kicking and
screaming, and we believe that it would be better to have someone
who is rock solid at his core, who knows instinctively what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   As in 1998, Roukema has been endorsed by the party chairmen in
the four counties fully or partially in the 5th Congressional
District: Warren, Sussex, Passaic and Bergen. But Garrett won three
of the counties in 1998, losing only in Bergen, Roukema's base and
the largest county in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett said some people voted for Roukema in 1998 to give her
one more term but will not be as generous this time. ''I've had a
number of people say that after 20 years, it's time to jump ship --
that is the phrase that people use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if 20 years in Congress have diminished Roukema's enthusiasm
for the job, she doesn't show it. In fact, a victory by Roukema
could give her a piece of history if Republicans retain control of
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Her seniority, combined with House Republican rules limiting
committee chairmen to six years, have Roukema in line to chair the
House Banking Committee beginning next year. She would be the first
woman to chair a major committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1425 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
