<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge blocks Newark ordinance banning ATM fees for noncustomers  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Bankers have temporarily blocked a Newark
ban on fees for noncustomer use of automatic teller machines, using
the same arguments that derailed a similar ordinance adopted by
Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   A federal lawsuit requesting a permanent injunction charges that
the city's ordinance is pre-empted by laws that leave regulation of
banks to federal and state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Such ordinances have also been stopped in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit by two industry groups and six banks was filed
Thursday, and U.S. District Judge Joseph A. Greenaway Jr. that day
granted their request for a temporary restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   A date for a hearing on the injunction has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark City Council had voted 9-0 on Wednesday to adopt the
ordinance, which found ATM fees have ''increased at an alarming
rate'' in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   If upheld, the ordinance requires the approval of Mayor Sharpe
James, who reportedly supports the concerns of the bankers. James
spokeswoman Pamela E. Goldstein said Tuesday she did not know what
the mayor would do.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Woodbridge ban, Newark's includes independently owned
ATMs, often found in small groceries, in addition to those operated
by banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodbridge ban was temporarily restrained in February by
Greenaway, who found the banks provided ''overwhelming evidence''
that the ordinance was pre-empted by federal and state banking
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The judge may consolidate the two cases.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of banning ATM fees claim that banks are charging
much more than what the transactions cost them.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Bankers Association, which brought the suits
against Woodbridge and Newark, counters that most banks lose money
on ATM transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Woodbridge, in Middlesex County, was the first New Jersey town
to adopt an ATM-fee ordinance. Newark, the state's largest city, is
the second.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, a statewide ban on ATM fees has been upheld only for
banks chartered by the state government. The state Supreme Court in
Connecticut rejected a statewide ban similar to Woodbridge's
proposal. In California, the bans are on hold in San Francisco and
Santa Monica while the courts consider the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1429 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000509.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel OKs Kosovo, Colombia Funds  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Appropriations Committee approved
emergency aid today for victims of U.S. natural disasters, for
anti-drug efforts in Colombia and peacekeeping in Kosovo after
voting to restrict future American action in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal by committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, for $7.2
billion in assistance grew to roughly $8 billion, aides estimated,
after the committee debated the plan for nearly 3{ hours and
approved several additions.
</P>
<P>
   By 23-3, the committee also adopted a provision by Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., that would require the next president to withdraw
American peacekeeping troops from Kosovo by July 2001 unless
Congress has approved leaving U.S. forces there.
</P>
<P>
   The House narrowly rejected a similar amendment in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate panel's votes came more than a month after Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., backed by conservatives,
blocked work on a larger version of the emergency aid package. Lott
supports the smaller proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The funds the committee approved are less than the $13 billion
bill the House approved March 30 but more than the $5.2 billion
President Clinton initially requested.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a free-standing bill, the money was divided among
three routine spending bills for military construction, foreign aid
and agriculture for the coming fiscal year that the committee
approved by voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   By trimming the emergency funds and attaching them to must-pass
spending bills, Stevens was addressing Lott's objections that a
separate package would have been too expensive and time-consuming.
Lott and other GOP leaders want Congress to adjourn as early as
possible so lawmakers can return home and campaign for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Since stalling the earlier measure, Lott has come under pressure
from administration officials and others who argue the money is
needed urgently, especially aid to Colombia's embattled government
for fighting drug traffickers who control large swaths of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The new package contains $5.7 billion for U.S. peacekeeping in
Kosovo, anti-drug efforts in Colombia and other Defense Department
programs. Included was money for Pentagon fuel purchases and the
military's financially ailing health-insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
   Another $1.5 billion was for the aftermath of last fall's
Hurricane Floyd, which battered parts of the East Coast, and other
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate breakdown available of the money for
Colombia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton requested $1.3 billion for Colombia, on top of $300
million already provided, while the House approved $1.7 billion.
Clinton requested about $2.8 billion for Kosovo and other Pentagon
needs, while the House approved $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also sought $1 billion for disasters, while the House
provided $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill included $4 billion lawmakers added for the
Defense Department to upgrade weapons and other expenditures.
Stevens' measure excluded that money, which GOP leaders plan to
include in the Pentagon's regular 2001 spending bill to be written
in coming weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1444 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000509.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Ballet Theater Opens Season  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The American Ballet Theater opened an eight-week
season at the Metropolitan Opera House with a gala evening of
bravura and romantic duets and the premiere of a fine ballet by
Twyla Tharp.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographer Donald Saddler helped celebrate the company's 40th
season, which began Monday night, by sharing the stage with
Annabelle Lyon and Miriam Golden. The three danced in the first
opening night on Jan. 11, 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute Tharp ballet, set to Brahms' ''Variations on a
Theme by Haydn,'' followed the glittering duets. It is remarkably
well organized and clear. Tharp paints with big choreographic
strokes, showing that she can structure large forces. There are 30
dancers and sometimes there are two back rows of couples, dancing
different steps. But the work never looks muddled.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kent and Angel Corella worked well together and looked as
though they enjoyed dancing together. The other leading couples
were Susan Jaffe and Marcelo Gomes, and Paloma Herrera and Vladimir
Malakhov.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers in ''Variations on a Theme by Haydn'' wore simple tan
and beige. Strong technique is necessary -- and these dancers had it
-- but the lifts, carries and spins contributed to a solid,
substantial ballet, not to flamboyance. The ballet had its premiere
at the Kennedy Center in Washington, D.C., in March. This was the
New York premiere. Tharp has choreographed 16 ballets for the
company in the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Corella thrilled the audience with his dancing in a pas
de deux from ''Le Corsaire'' with Jaffe. Jose Manuel Carreno was
also thrilling in a Rudolf Nureyev staging of ''Diana and Acteon.''
Herrera danced the pert Diana.
</P>
<P>
   The evening began with a ''Swan Lake'' pas de deux by Julie Kent
and Corella. Nina Ananiashvili was the gallant but sad ''Dying
Swan.''
</P>
<P>
   Alessandra Ferri and Julio Bocca danced a passionate pas de deux
from ''Manon.'' Amanda McKerrow and Malakhov danced a fresh as
springtime ''Tchaikovsky Pas de Deux.'' Kent and Bocca led a large
cast in the finale of ''Theme and Variations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ermanno Florio conducted for the evening. During final bows,
many former dancers of the American Ballet Theater joined the
present company on stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1445 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
