<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hopkins Student Has Meningitis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- A Johns Hopkins University graduate student was
in critical condition Tuesday with bacterial meningitis, a
potentially fatal inflammation of the brain lining and spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   Students and staff at the university's Homewood campus were sent
e-mail urging them to seek treatment with antibiotics if they had
close contact with the student, Marcus Dale Weicker, 25, of
Hubbard, Ore. Doctors confirmed Weicker has bacterial meningitis,
Union Memorial spokeswoman Amy Strong said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there are about 3,000 cases every year. Bacterial
meningitis is fatal in about 10 percent and causes serious harm,
including brain damage, in another 10 percent, according to the
federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The infection is spread through close contact, such as kissing
or sharing a drink. Symptoms include headache, stiff neck, fever,
nausea and vomiting, with severe cases leading to convulsions and
delirium.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC recommended last fall that all U.S. campuses inform
students about meningitis and make vaccines accessible.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, the General Assembly this year passed a bill
requiring college students in the state to be vaccinated against
the bacteria that cause meningitis or sign a waiver stating they
understand the risks of contracting it.
</P>
<P>
   University spokesman Dennis O'Shea said about 1,000 of the 5,000
students at the Homewood campus took advantage of a meningitis
vaccination program offered last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.jhu.edu/ ~shcenter
</P>
<P>
   http://www.hopkins-HEIC.org/infectious--diseases/meningitis.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
