<HEADLINE> Russia Warns Chechen Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- A top Russian commander appealed Tuesday
to Chechen rebels to surrender before a May 15 amnesty deadline,
while Russian troops paraded through Chechnya's capital to mark the
55th anniversary of the Soviet victory over Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Russians' claims that they control most of the rebel
republic and have wiped out major resistance, the insurgents show
no sign they are ready to give up. Small rebel bands continued to
attack Russian posts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Gennady Troshev, head of Russian forces in the region, said
rebels should ''assess the situation, think hard and lay down their
arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People are tired of the war,'' Troshev said in a statement.
''They need peace and a normal life. Make use of the amnesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has offered amnesty through May 15 to fighters who
surrender with their weapons if they are found not to have
committed what federal authorities consider series crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian Interior Ministry troops and a pro-Moscow
Chechen militia paraded through the capital Grozny to mark Victory
Day, a major holiday across the former Soviet Union. Federal forces
have occupied Grozny since February.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen World War II veterans attended the parade through
the capital's shell-cratered streets. Russian troops sought out the
veterans in Grozny's basements, where most residents have been
living since Russia's bombing campaign began in August.
</P>
<P>
   Chechens who fought with the Soviet army feel betrayed by the
Russian military, and receive little of the acclaim showered on
veterans elsewhere on Victory Day.
</P>
<P>
   No major rebel attacks were reported Tuesday, despite Russian
fears of a large-scale offensive to coincide with the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighboring republic of Dagestan, however, security
officials disarmed two bombs Tuesday on the central square in the
capital Makhachkala, an hour before a Victory Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs were found by a sniffer dog near a statue of Soviet
founder Vladimir Lenin, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces also disarmed mines on six stretches of roadway
in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes were reported in the Vedeno, Nozhai-Yurt and Shatoi
regions. Rebels shot at Russian checkpoints in Grozny's Oktyabrsky
district, near Urus-Martan, and in Assinovskaya, ITAR-Tass said. No
Russian casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have occupied the northern, lowland part of
Chechnya, but for months have been hunting rebels in the southern
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Fog and rain halted air strikes in Chechnya over the past 24
hours, the air force said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, a top member of Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov's government, National Security Service chief Ibragim
Khultygov, was detained in southeastern Chechnya, according to
Russian officials in Gudermes. Khultygov took over the security
service when his predecessor and brother Lecha was killed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops entered Chechnya after Chechnya-based Islamic
militants seized villages in Dagestan in August, and after about
300 people were killed in Russian apartment building explosions
that the government blamed on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
