<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Opposition Cancels Rally  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   POZAREVAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav government blocked a
planned opposition rally in President Slobodan Milosevic's hometown
Tuesday, detaining critics and journalists, stopping buses from
heading for the rally and deploying hundreds of police to shut off
access to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the massive government effort, pro-democracy
opposition leaders backed down and canceled the rally in Pozarevac,
55 miles east of Belgrade. They cited ''repression, violence and
terror'' as reasons for the cancellation, saying the alternative to
giving in would have been ''clashes among the citizens, even civil
war in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We did not want to drag Serbia into chaos, anarchy and civil
war,'' said one of the opposition leaders, Vuk Obradovic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's opponents decided to reschedule the rally for Monday
and hold it in the capital, Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Pozarevac rally was scheduled to protest last week's beating
of three student activists who clashed with close associates of
Milosevic's son, Marko. It would have been the first big opposition
gathering in Pozarevac, a Milosevic stronghold known within
opposition circles as ''the forbidden city.''
</P>
<P>
   But early Tuesday, police deployed in Pozarevac, setting up
checkpoints and blocking access to the city. Authorities used
document checks to hinder foreign and domestic reporters from
coming, and several local journalists were detained.
</P>
<P>
   In other cities throughout Serbia, police prevented buses with
opposition supporters from leaving for the rally and detained
scores of anti-government activists.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, four buses were ordered to undergo ''technical
inspection'' before being allowed to leave. Police then stopped the
buses again on the outskirts of Belgrade, and about 200 of the
would-be protesters responded by blocking traffic on the highway
leading to Pozarevac and demanding passage. They sat on the road,
preventing hundreds of cars from passing for about two hours before
riot police moved them.
</P>
<P>
   In Novi Sad, in northern Yugoslavia, police arrested 17
activists of the student organization Otpor, or Resistance, who
were distributing leaflets saying, ''Death to Fascism + Down With
Milosevic  Freedom For the People.'' Eight reporters for
independent media were detained with them.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters and most of the students were later released, with
four student activists still held in Novi Sad by nightfall, Otpor
said. Authorities gave no reason why they had been held.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Milosevic met World War II veterans in Belgrade to
mark the 55th anniversary of the defeat of Nazi Germany. During his
speech, Milosevic referred to the Unites States as a ''fascist
power'' that wants to conquer the world with the help of domestic
''traitors.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the veterans that the Serbs, ''with their superior and
victorious ways ... will defeat this new fascism,'' according to
the state Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
   In Pozarevac, about 150 Milosevic supporters marked Victory Day
at the same venue where the opposition protest had been scheduled.
About 200 local opposition demonstrators confronted the
pro-government supporters, shouting ''Red Bandits, Thieves and
Killers,'' but there were no direct clashes.
</P>
<P>
   In its evening broadcast, state-run television reported that a
dozen ''hooligans and criminals, led by fascist members of the
terrorist Otpor group'' tried to disrupt the Pozarevac gathering
and that police arrested several individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade's most popular independent radio, B2-92, went off the
air amid its live broadcast from Pozarevac. The radio's director,
Veran Matic, said the broadcasts were being jammed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
