<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Tuesday, May 9, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ex-Presidents Push Chinese Trade
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Presidents Carter and Ford joined
President Clinton today in pressing Congress to grant permanent
normal trade relations to China. Ford said a vote against the trade
measure ''would be catastrophic, disastrous to American ...
products and services.'' Carter acknowledged that China has failed
to take adequate steps in terms of human rights, democracy and
labor standards. ''But ... a negative vote ... will be a serious
setback and impediment for the further democratization, freedom and
human rights in China,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Mega Ad Co. Merger Likely
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Madison Avenue mainstay Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. has
agreed in principle to be acquired by Britain's WPP Group PLC,
creating the world's largest advertising and marketing company,
sources say. The deal, valued at about $4.7 billion in stock, would
be the richest ever in the advertising industry. It comes at a time
when multinational companies are choosing agencies with the reach
and expertise to deliver their sales messages to consumers around
the world. The two ad powerhouses share clients such as Ford,
Mattel, Kraft Foods and Sears, Roebuck and Co. Shares in Young &AMP;
Rubicam were trading down 4 13/16, or 10 percent, at 45.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, GE Team on Satellite TV
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- BellSouth Corp. and a unit of General Electric
will team to offer digital television via satellite in the
telephone company's nine-state turf. BellSouth will become the
first regional phone company to compete with the satellite services
such as the DISH Network and DirecTV. The deal would expand
BellSouth's potential market for entertainment services from a
handful of cities to 14 million households. Stock in BellSouth fell
3 percent, or 1 9/16, to 44 15/16, while shares in GE also dipped 3
percent, or 1], to 51 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart 1Q Earnings Rise Sharply
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s first-quarter
earnings rose to sharply from a year ago, fueled by higher sales at
its stores in the United States and abroad. The world's biggest
retailer reported today that it earned $1.326 billion, or 30 cents
a share, for the quarter ended April 30, compared with $916
million, or 20 cents a share, a year ago. Sales for the quarter
totaled $42.99 billion, up from $34.71 billion a year ago. The
company's stock was up ~ to 53\.
</P>
<P>
   SEC Investigates Cisco Acquisition
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The Securities and Exchange Commission
is investigating possible insider trading in the stock of
ArrowPoint Communications Inc. ahead of an announcement Internet
equipment provider Cisco Systems would acquire it. The all-stock
acquisition is now valued at about $5.6 billion. ArrowPoint shares
soared 27 percent on the Nasdaq Stock Market a day before the Cisco
purchase was announced on Friday amid heavy Internet chat room
speculation of a takeover. Shares in Cisco, which will release
third-quarter earnings today, have fallen } to 62 so far today.
Stock in ArrowPoint is down 3} at 127.
</P>
<P>
   Tech Sector Pulls Dow, Nasdaq Lower
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks pulled other stock market
sectors lower today in quiet trading. Bucking the downtrend in tech
stocks, shares of 3Com rose sharply after the maker of computer
network equipment said it would complete the spinoff of Palm Inc.
several months ahead of schedule. 3Com shares rose 8 percent, or 3
7/16, to 47[. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down
46.49 at 10,557.14 and the Nasdaq was down 92.62 at 3,576.76.
</P>
