<P>
   'Love Bug' Suspect Free for Now
</P>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Investigators searching for the
author of the ''ILOVEYOU'' computer bug freed a suspect today, but
said they are decoding 10 names that might be linked to the
worldwide virus attack. The FBI got the names from Sky Internet, a
Philippine Internet service provider. The names -- apparently chat
room or e-mail identifiers -- could be pseudonyms for a single
person or several people, investigators said. They are believed to
be connected to the Philippines' AMA Computer College.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent Fliers Favor Continental
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Readers of Frequent Flyer magazine ranked
Continental as their favorite airline. Continental was top-rated
for both long-haul and short-haul flights, leading second-place TWA
in the poll conducted by the magazine and the survey firm J.D.
Power and Associates. Continental scored 123 points for flights of
more than 500 miles, followed by TWA at 121, Southwest with 108 and
United with the industry average of 100 points on the magazine's
scoring system. For the shorter flights Continental received 122
points, TWA had 117 and Southwest 107.
</P>
<P>
   Lego, Spielberg Team on Movie Kit
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Steven Spielberg is teaming up with toy industry
giant Lego to create a digital moviemaking kit that lets children
create and edit their own films. The Lego Studios Steven Spielberg
MovieMaker will not appear in stores until November. The filmmaking
kit is the latest example of Lego's aggressive move toward
integrating technology with its classic building blocks. It already
has a number of popular CD-ROM games in stores and also has had
great success with its Lego Mindstorms, high-tech robots that can
be manipulated using microcomputers.
</P>
<P>
   BMW Agrees To Sale of Rover Cars
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Germany's BMW agreed today to sell the ailing
Rover car group to a British consortium. The Phoenix consortium,
led by former Rover chief executive John Towers, said it expects to
lay off fewer than 1,000 workers and make Rover profitable within
two years. BMW said it has agreed to lend Phoenix $765 million to
help the consortium get Rover off the ground. Phoenix said it would
take over responsibility to develop, produce and distribute Rover
cars, and also would acquire the MG brand.
</P>
