<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Closing 5 N. Irish Sites  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The British Army will close two
bases and abandon three observation posts in Northern Ireland, the
province's police chief said Tuesday, in response to the Irish
Republican Army's move to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Notwithstanding a significant ongoing threat posed by
dissidents, the weekend's events represent a real lowering of the
overall threat,'' said Sir Ronnie Flanagan, the chief constable of
the Royal Ulster Constabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Troop strengths of just under 14,000, the lowest in 30 years,
will not be affected by the closure of bases in Cookstown and
Londonderry, officials said. The latter was the army's last outpost
in the overwhelmingly Roman Catholic area of the city west of the
River Foyle.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came three days after the IRA announced it
would open its arms stockpiles to international inspectors in order
to verify that the weapons have been put ''beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish government then announced that they hoped
to restore power to Northern Ireland's new power-sharing government
-- the centerpiece of 1998's Good Friday peace agreement --on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Kelly, a Sinn Fein negotiator who served a prison sentence
for IRA bombings, said the announcement of the base closings was
welcome, but long overdue. ''The process of demilitarization should
have begun immediately after the signing of the Good Friday
agreement,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mandelson, the British Cabinet member in charge of
Northern Ireland, said he hoped ''that conditions on the ground
will enable us safely to make further changes in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the observation posts marked for closing is at Cloghogue,
south of Newry near the Irish border in southern County Armagh, an
area known as ''bandit country'' for its reputation as an IRA
stronghold. The other posts are at Broadway and New Lodge in west
and north Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   If the level of threat remains low, Flanagan said, he intends to
order the closing of the army's base in the center of Crossmaglen,
also in south Armagh, in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Flanagan makes his decisions in consultation with
the army commander, independent of the political process. However,
Sinn Fein and the Irish government had previously floated the idea
that an IRA gesture on arms could be made in return for a reduction
in the British military presence.
</P>
<P>
   The next critical decision for the peace process is in the hands
of the Ulster Unionist Party, which must decide whether the IRA has
done enough to satisfy its demand for disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Britain suspended the Northern Ireland government in February to
prevent a walkout by Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, whose
party gets the largest share of Protestant votes in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA said Saturday that it has agreed to allow two
independent inspectors -- Cyril Ramaphosa, former chairman of the
African National Congress, and retired Finnish president Martti
Ahtisaari -- to periodically assess its hidden weapons stockpiles to
verify they have not been used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
