<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Pulls Stock Market Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in quiet trading on Wall Street
today as technology shares gave up early gains and pulled other
market sectors lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was off 66.09 at 3,603.24, while the
Dow Jones industrial average was down 42.66 at 10,560.97.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 12.05 at 1,412.12.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks had started the day slightly higher but resumed
their decline as traders took profits from Friday's rally.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which was pummeled Monday following a negative
article in Barron's magazine, fell 3/16 to 62 11/16, and
Hewlett-Packard fell 3{ to 132 3/16. Other tech shares also edged
lower. Cisco reports earnings after the close of trading today.
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the downtrend in tech stocks, shares of 3Com rose
sharply after the maker of computer network equipment said it would
complete the spinoff of Palm Inc. several months ahead of schedule.
3Com shares rose 3 11/16 to 47] while Palm shares fell 3{ to 28}.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, which announced earnings that beat analyst estimates,
rose 1 1/16 to 53 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   With few major economic indicators coming out and the next
meeting of the Federal Reserve Board a week off, stock trading has
been slow in recent sessions. Monday was the quietest session of
the year so far.
</P>
<P>
   William P. Miller, chief investment officer of large cap
equities at American Express Asset Management Group in Minneapolis,
said investors were continued to trim their holdings of tech stocks
after a recent advance and parking their money in traditional
safe-haven stocks like drug and food makers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the market is moving to a consensus that the Fed is
going to raise rates, and that they might hgave to be more
aggressive than they thought,'' Miller said. ''People are booking
profits ahead of next week, and since much of the runup was in the
tech sector, that's where they're selling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 9.30 today at 490.78.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a 7-to-5 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 705.95 million
shares, moderately ahead of Tuesday's quiet levels.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas markets also had declines. In Tokyo, the benchmark
Nikkei stock average tumbled 355.42 points, or 1.95 percent, to
close at 17,844.54 points, its lowest level in six months.
</P>
<P>
