<HEADLINE> Court orders new trial because jurors advised colleagues  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Two nurses should not have provided medical
opinions to fellow jurors on evidence in a homicide case and the
convicted man should get a new trial, the state's highest court
ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member Court of Appeals panel also called on judges in
all future cases in New York to ''direct that jurors may not use
their professional expertise to insert facts and evidence.'' The
unanimous opinion was written by Judge Joseph Bellacosa.
</P>
<P>
   The decision concerns the case of Michael Maragh, 26, who was
convicted of criminally negligent homicide in Orange County Court
November 1997 in the death of his girlfriend and mother of his two
children in their Middletown apartment.
</P>
<P>
   His attorneys argued that 26-year-old May DeGroat died of an air
embolism caused by having sexual intercourse too soon after giving
birth. She had the couple's second child nine days earlier.
Prosecutors contended Maragh beat the woman and that the blood loss
killed her.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses, according to court documents, offered to the entire
jury their own professional opinions on the case, which they came
to after sharing a room while sequestered. One offered her own
calculation on the effect of blood loss on DeGroat. The jury
convicted Maragh on its second day of deliberations and one of the
other jurors later testified that the nurses' opinions directly
affected the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The court wrote Tuesday that when jurors who have professional
knowledge ''take the additional, forbidden step beyond the evidence
of the cases'' of advising jurors, ''that would violate the rights
of litigants to have their cases decided only on the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The nurses' remarks came to light through reports in The Times
Herald-Record in Middletown.
</P>
<P>
   A county court judge called for a retrial but the district
attorney's office asked for a reversal from the Appellate Division
of state Supreme Court, which reinstated Maragh's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's office had argued that the county
judge's instructions that the jurors could utilize their ''personal
experience'' in deciding the facts of the case entitled those with
medical backgrounds to share that knowledge with the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Maragh was originally sentenced to 1-1/3 to four years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to jail March 31 following the reinstatement of his
conviction and has not been allowed to see his two young sons, who
now stay with their maternal grandmother, said his attorney, Ben
Ostrer.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County District Attorney Frank Phillips said he will
press to get Maragh convicted again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
