<HEADLINE> Edwards Trial Jury Reaches Verdict  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Jurors reached a verdict today in the
racketeering trial of former Gov. Edwin Edwards but also suggested
their decisions might not be made public immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which began deliberations April 24 and was cut to 11
members after one juror was removed last week, told U.S. District
Judge Frank Polozola it had finished deliberations but needed time
to fill out the complicated verdict forms.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors' note also reminded the judge that they needed to
leave court no later than 4:30 p.m. CDT because one of them has an
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, a defense attorney representing Edwards son,
Stephen Edwards, said he would ask the judge to call a mistrial
because the jury had seen transcripts of secretly recorded
conversations that contained underlined phrases.
</P>
<P>
   The jury told the judge about the markings on Monday but said
jury members had not been prejudiced by what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys frequently made marks in the
transcripts throughout the four-month trial, but the judge had
asked that the jurors be given transcripts that were clear of any
notations from either side.
</P>
<P>
   The four-term governor, his son, a state senator and four others
are accused in a series of extortion schemes to manipulate the
licensing of Louisiana riverboat casinos from 1991 through 1997. If
convicted on all counts, Edwards, 72, could get more than 300 years
in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
