<HEADLINE> Black Policeman Sues City of Boston  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A black police lieutenant who said he found a
noose made out of yellow crime scene tape hanging over his
motorcycle is suing the city, claiming he was a victim of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Valimore Williams filed the Superior Court lawsuit Monday
because the department had taken more than a year to investigate
his complaints and still hadn't informed him of a resolution, said
his attorney, Henry F. Owens III. Williams is seeking unspecified
damages.
</P>
<P>
   An internal affairs probe is its final review, a police
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 56, found the noose over his police motorcycle in a
department garage in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A white officer admitted placing it there but said it was a
practical joke and had no racist intent. The officer was charged
with breaking department rules and reached a settlement with the
department, said Mary Jo Harris, a legal adviser to the department.
</P>
<P>
   Williams accused a second white officer of jamming his radio so
he could not communicate with other officers. The officer was
disciplined.
</P>
