<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Retreat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures declined Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade after forecasts called for a wet week ahead
in Midwestern growing regions.
</P>
<P>
   Corn dipped to a one-week low as the rainy outlook further
eroded concerns about dry soil conditions that have lingered for
months. Storms are now predicted in the corn belt both this week
and next, although despite recent precipitation moisture levels
remain below normal in much of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean prices also dropped for a second straight day, pressured
by not only the damp weather but by record soybean plantings so far
this season, which increase the significance of near-term moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat prices closed little changed, as pressure from corn and
soybeans was nearly overcome by support from a decline in winter
wheat crop conditions in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell \ cent to $2.57} a bushel; July
corn fell 2\ cents to $2.38} a bushel; July oats fell 2{ cents to
$1.20} a bushel; July soybeans fell 3 cents to $5.56 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were higher on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures were lower.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .13 cent to 68.70 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle rose .15 cent to 85.32 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .72 cent to 73.45 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell the
limit 3 cents to 90.57 cents a pound.
</P>
