<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voters Don't Heed All Endorsements  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS, AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the ritual of presidential peacemaking,
nominees in waiting minimize their differences with defeated
rivals, disputes are shelved and the loser endorses the winner with
a ''take-the-medicine'' smile.
</P>
<P>
   That is a step for party unity, but what comes later will
determine whether it also is a step toward re-enlisting voters who
preferred the other guy in the primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsements do not necessarily deliver votes in the general
election; even the enthusiastic campaign Sen. John McCain said he
intends to wage for Gov. George W. Bush for president doesn't mean
his reform-minded followers will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there are degrees of enthusiasm. And that
take-the-medicine line was McCain's, after he and Bush held their
90-minute Republican peace talk on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainties of such forced betrothals are written into the
campaigns of the past 40 years, since Richard M. Nixon, as vice
president, conceded platform points to New York Gov. Nelson A.
Rockefeller in a secret deal made to placate the leader of liberal
Republicans. Nixon was on his way to the 1960 GOP nomination, and
he didn't want a distracting issues fight at the national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   So just before it opened, he accepted the deal that came to be
called the Treaty of Fifth Avenue, with platform terms that angered
conservatives but avoided a Rockefeller challenge. Sen. Barry
Goldwater compared it to the appeasement of Munich, but told his
conservative followers to stick with the ticket anyhow, saying they
could take over later. They did, and nominated him in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon narrowly lost the 1960 election to John F. Kennedy. And
the Democratic ticket won Rockefeller's New York.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Republican peace in the 1964 campaign; Goldwater
saw to that when he defiantly told the national convention that
extremism in the defense of liberty was no vice, and that he didn't
expect the support of those who did not agree with his conservative
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he was going to get it anyhow; Rockefeller was his
chief rival for the nomination and there was no bridging their
differences. It was a landslide year for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1968, they were the shattered party, torn by the war in
Vietnam. Vice President Hubert H. Humphrey could not rally anti-war
Democrats, and their candidate, Sen. Eugene J. McCarthy, did not
try to help him. McCarthy did endorse the Democratic ticket -- two
days before the election Nixon won.
</P>
<P>
   President Ford narrowly won the 1976 Republican nomination over
Ronald Reagan, then governor of California, and paid a
post-midnight call on the loser to seek unity. They appeared
together afterward and Reagan said he'd support the ticket. But he
did little national campaigning that fall.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, it was Reagan's turn. George Bush challenged
him until late in the primaries before conceding with a pledge of
wholehearted support, and winding up as the 1980 vice presidential
nominee, on the path that led him to his one term as president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he told George W. Bush that he did not want to be
considered for vice president. Bush said he took the senator at his
word.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy delivered the appropriate pledge
of support after losing to President Carter, but theirs was no
political embrace. There was friction between their camps into the
fall, over agendas that never really meshed, and over the bills the
Kennedy operation sent the Carter campaign for the senator's
travels and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   There can be other political costs in peacemaking efforts. Gov.
Michael Dukakis, the 1988 Democratic nominee, negotiated a truce
with rival Jesse Jackson, and Republicans later made it part of
their argument that Dukakis was too liberal to be president.
</P>
<P>
   For the winner, the peacemaking goal is to gain the support of
the loser without capitulating on issues used in gaining primary
victories. For the loser, it is to demonstrate party loyalty
without surrendering on his issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will continue to pursue the issues of reform,'' McCain
assured his supporters on Tuesday, as he and Bush both said they
agreed on more issues than they differed about. That is usually
true of party rivals, of course.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he will campaign at a heavy pace, for Republican
House and Senate candidates and for the Bush ticket. He needs that
demonstration of party loyalty to be in position for a 2004
nomination bid should Bush lose to Vice President Al Gore. McCain
reached past the GOP this year to gain the votes of independents
and Democrats in open primaries. He'd need a more solid Republican
base for another try.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are limits to loyalty shows. Bush has his
nominating majority of Republican National Convention delegates,
but at least 240 delegates will be committed to vote for McCain. He
said nothing about releasing them before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears has reported on Washington and
national politics for The Associated Press for more than 35 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
