<HEADLINE> Rebels Attack Troops in Sri Lanka  </HEADLINE>
By DILSHIKA JAYAMAHA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A day after the Sri Lankan government
rejected a temporary cease-fire offer from separatist rebels, Tamil
Tigers attacked troops defending the northern Jaffna peninsula. It
was the first fighting there in nine days.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament also extended emergency rule for another month,
giving the military sweeping powers to seize property, ban
publications and demonstrations and make arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The two attacks -- with machine guns, rocket-propelled grenades
and mortars -- were the first since April 30 by the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam against soldiers manning a defensive line set
up to halt the rebel advance toward Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the rebels offered a temporary cease-fire to enable
Sri Lankan troops to withdraw from Jaffna, a city of 500,000 that
is considered the center of Tamil culture. The Tamils had used
Jaffna as the capital of their autonomous rebel state from 1990-95
and are pressing to recapture it.
</P>
<P>
   Ariya Rubasinghe, the government's chief spokesman and censor,
said the troops repulsed both the assaults and forced the rebels to
withdraw southward.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte told parliament that troops
had moved forward from their defensive line 15 miles southeast of
Jaffna city and plan to push the rebels ''back beyond Elephant
Pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels overran Elephant Pass, a strategic causeway that
links Jaffna peninsula with the mainland, on April 21. Ratwatte
released the first official government figures on that battle,
saying 358 troops were killed and 2,568 injured.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, police prevented a new nationalist party from holding
a public meeting to rally the country against the rebels. The
Sinhala Heritage party opposes special status for Tamils, who are
18 percent of country's 18.6 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Police holding batons asked the crowd of 300 people in Colombo
to disperse. The crowd did so after initially resisting.
</P>
<P>
   The party that says its aim is to safeguard the rights of the
majority Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   The group's call came as the government set up vigilance
committees Tuesday to protect the Tamils in Colombo and other
cities against a backlash from the Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, soldiers with assault rifles stood along the
streets; others patrolled on motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   ''This government will ensure that there is no violence of any
sort against anyone, especially against Tamils,'' Media Minister
Mangala Samaraweera said.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-Tamil wave in 1983 spurred the militancy. Enraged by the
deaths of 13 Sinhalese soldiers in the north, Sinhalese mobs
attacked Tamil homes in Colombo and other places, killing nearly
2,000 Tamils and driving hundreds of thousands to neighboring
India. Tamils of Sri Lanka and India share a language, culture and
family links.
</P>
<P>
   The government censors all local and foreign news reports about
the war and prohibits news organizations from contacting the rebels
for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1601 </TRAILER>
