<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Sri Lanka Receives Arms  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sri Lanka has received arms and
ammunition in order to rescue thousands of soldiers from Tamil
Tiger rebels advancing on the key northern peninsula of Jaffna, Sri
Lanka's top diplomat to India said Tuesday. He declined to describe
the arms or say where they had come from.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Mangala Moonasinghe's comments were the first
official confirmation that Sri Lanka had received arms since rebels
overran the strategic Elephant Pass causeway two weeks ago and
headed toward their former stronghold of Jaffna. The fighting has
been the fiercest in years.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the private Star-TV network Tuesday night,
Moonasinghe would not give details on the arms, according to the
United News of India news agency. But in the last week, Sri Lanka
has renewed diplomatic ties with Israel, and a team of military
officials from Russia visited recently.
</P>
<P>
   India has refused to offer military assistance to Sri Lanka,
fearing it would anger millions of Tamils in the southern state of
Tamil Nadu. Tamils in both nations share a language, culture and
family ties.
</P>
<P>
   Moonasinghe also denied reports that Sri Lankan Foreign Minister
Lakshman Kadirgamar asked for military help when he called on
India's prime minister in New Delhi last week.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, India sent its soldiers to help the Sri Lanka
government crush the Tamil uprising. Some 2,000 Indian soldiers
were killed and thousands of others were wounded in the fighting.
India pulled out its soldiers in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
