<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEP report cites nuclear plant complex as one source of fish loss  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A judge must rule on a motion to dismiss
a lawsuit seeking to shut down Millstone 3 nuclear power complex
during the flounder spawning season.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Coalition Against Millstone is seeking the
shutdown of Millstone 3 because of concerns over a decline in the
fish population. Superior Court Judge Seymour Hendel was expected
to rule this week on a motion by Northeast Utilities to dismiss the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a state Department of Environmental protection report
concludes that Millstone is responsible for the loss of some fish.
The report, described by the DEP as its best estimate and ''simply
speculative,'' claims the nuclear complex is responsible for 29
percent of the collapse in the Niantic River winter flounder stock
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ''One thing we are certain about is that the winter flounder
population in the Niantic River is at the point of collapse,'' Dave
Simpson, supervising fisheries biologist at the DEP, said Monday.
''The more difficult question is how much regional factors
contributed to that as opposed to a localized effect. And in that
localized case we're talking Millstone.''
</P>
<P>
   The evaluation is the most critical yet of Millstone as the
possible cause of the dramatic reduction in winter flounder, an
important commercial fish.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how much of the damage to the winter flounder is
caused by the massive intake of water sucked into the nuclear power
plants to cool the reactors. Billions of microscopic fish larvae
are destroyed in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of water intake increased dramatically with the
opening of the Millstone 3 plant in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   NU contends that most of the larval losses come from Niantic
Bay, not the Niantic River, and so would have a minimal impact on
the winter flounder larvae.
</P>
<P>
   NU also contends that overfishing is the primary cause of the
flounder decline.
</P>
<P>
   The DEP's estimate of the impact is greater than NU's
assessment, but lower than the findings of environmental groups,
Simpson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1639 </TRAILER>
