<DOCNO> APW20000509.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Warns on Korean Summit  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Given North Korea's track record, no one
should be particularly optimistic about next month's summit on the
divided peninsula, South Korea's ambassador said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans have ''great expectations'' for the June 12-14
meeting between their president, Kim Dae-jung, and North Korean
leader Kim Jong Il because of their decades-old hope for
reunification of the country, said Lee Hong-koo, ambassador to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's tightly controlled system, however, makes it
difficult for leaders there to change much, even should they want
to, Lee said in a speech at Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   ''Generally, when North Korea makes one step forward, the past
record is they take two steps back,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   He said leaders in the isolated and totalitarian North ''are
very much concerned'' that giving away too much to make peace with
the democratic South could destabilize their system of government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are now going through a very difficult period ... trying to
write a very last chapter of the history of the Cold War,'' said
Lee. ''Whether we can write that chapter successfully, and without
another war: that is the question today.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Koreas say reunification is their ultimate goal, but the
two Kims are expected to hold back on that mammoth task at their
June meeting. Even without any such breakthrough, their meeting
would be in itself the most significant diplomatic event on the
peninsula since its division into communist North and pro-Western
South in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides did not sign a peace treaty at the end of the
1950-53 Korean War and have remained technically at war, with
37,000 U.S. troops stationed in the South to help keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   The June summit, the first meeting ever between leaders of the
two countries, is to focus on economic issues and security, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope that a very positive atmosphere will be created in
that meeting, so that in subsequent meetings we can make major
progress,'' he said. ''But excessive optimism is something we
should refrain from.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea, impoverished and desperate for economic help, has
moved to improve ties in recent months with Italy, Australia,
Japan, the Philippines, the United States, Britain and others. Its
overtures are a break in its traditional policy of shunning most of
the outside world under the philosophy it calls ''juche,'' or
self-reliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1646 </TRAILER>
