<HEADLINE> Euro Higher After U.S. Stocks Drop  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro rose against the dollar on Tuesday as
traders bid up the price of the single European currency amid a
broad selloff in the U.S. stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 90.69 cents, up
from 89.70 cents late Monday. The slight push upward moved the euro
a full two cents above the record low of 88.45 cents it reached on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has suffered against the dollar in recent weeks as the
U.S. economy has shown no signs of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts believe Tuesday's optimism could quickly sour.
European Central Bank officials and other European financial
leaders are expected to provide little support to the flagging euro
at meetings scheduled to begin on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Monday, the dollar was quoted at 109.45
Japanese yen, up from 109.03. The dollar also was quoted at 1.7168
Swiss francs, down from 1.7276, and 1.4913 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.4917.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1566 German
marks, down from 2.1803; 7.2329 French francs, down from 7.3124;
and 2,134.92 Italian lire, down from 2,158.49.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound rose to $1.5332 from $1.5321.
</P>
</TEXT>
