<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer loses sex discrimination case  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A golfer who claimed she suffered sex
discrimination at the ritzy Westchester Country Club for 17 years
waited too long to file her lawsuit, a state human rights judge
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge who issued the decision was not the judge who
heard the case, and the plaintiff's lawyer is crying foul.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Administrative Law Judge James T. King agreed that Nancy
Saunders had been discriminated against ''solely because of her
gender,'' but said she would have had to sue within a year after
becoming aware of it -- by 1986 at the latest. Saunders sued in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also found that state human rights laws did not apply
to the club anyway before 1994 because it was ''distinctly
private.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders' lawyer, Susan Slavin, said, ''Something's wrong here.
Where's the judge who tried the case? This is an absolutely
devastating decision, it is a tragedy and it bears no resemblance
to what took place at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge who conducted the hearings last fall, Denise
Washington, was dismissed in January. She told The Journal News
last month that she was fired because she testified in federal
court that the human rights division needed 25 to 30 more judges to
cut into a six-year backlog of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Ellison, spokeswoman for the Human Rights Division, said
it is ''within our authority and jurisdiction'' to assign a new
judge to a case.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, 50, testified at the hearings that from the time she
joined the club in Harrison in 1982, she was barred, as a woman,
from the club's prestigious West Course for long stretches of time
each Wednesday, Friday, Saturday and Sunday. She also could not get
into the Men's Grill, which she said cost her business
opportunities. And when she married a fellow member, she claimed,
the club ended her membership on the ground that the husband is
always the member.
</P>
<P>
   The club now charges $45,000 for initiation fees and $5,500 a
year for dues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed because I still believe in this and I know
what happened,'' said Saunders, who lives in Greenwich, Conn., and
returned a call after completing 18 holes Tuesday as part of the
club's women's team.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision -- actually a recommendation to state Human
Rights Commissioner Jerome Blue -- King said Saunders should have
filed her suit within a year of joining the club or within a year
of when the club allegedly terminated her membership in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that although the club is the host for the PGA
Tour's Buick Classic, it is not ''a place of public accommodation''
that would have been subject to the human rights law before 1994,
the period covered by the suit.
</P>
<P>
   King also ruled that Saunders' claim of retaliation by the club
against her husband was not proven.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Miller, president of the club, said the club ''does not
discriminate against people by gender, race, religion or in any
other manner, and I am pleased that the state Division of Human
Rights has ruled in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Slavin said she would object to the recommendations within the
21 days provided and appeal the case if the commissioner accepted
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''This decision was not rendered by a judge who sat and observed
the demeanor of the witnesses and the credibility of the
witnesses,'' she said. ''How did he decide? From a record? You
can't tell from a cold record whether somebody is truthful. ...
Judge Washington gave us every indication during trial that she was
favorably persuaded. So we obviously think this is a travesty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1705 </TRAILER>
