<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Presidents Rally About China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The cause was trade with China, and, in a rare
display of Washington fellowship, it brought together two past
presidents, the present-day president and one applicant for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ford crossed his legs and settled back in his chair.
Jimmy Carter took long blinks to rest his eyes under the bright
lights. Bill Clinton, junior member of this club, jotted notes on
his speech text.
</P>
<P>
   Before them Tuesday was an assemblage of luminaries rallying
around Clinton's proposal to establish permanent normal trade with
China, facing opposition from many of his fellow Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The session was unusual. Clinton noted that ''it unites Henry
Kissinger, Andrew Young and Jesse Ventura -- and not at a wrestling
match.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford compared this trade battle to a 1949 vote that he, John F.
Kennedy and Richard Nixon cast in Congress to help Harry Truman
''undo the tragedy of the high-tariff, protectionist trade
policies'' that fed into the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Carter reminisced about secret 1979 negotiations with
then-Chinese Premier Deng Xiaoping, recalling his own passion for
human rights and his hopes for ''the well-being of the American
worker'' in a more open trade environment.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Clinton, president longer than the other two combined,
making his case in the most colloquial manner.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agreement has become like fly paper for the accumulated
frustrations people have about things in the world,'' Clinton said.
''If the Congress votes against it, they will be kicking themselves
in the rear 10 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   So near, but yet so far, sat Vice President Al Gore. Grouped
across the stage with Secretaries of State Madeleine Albright,
James Baker and Henry Kissinger, Gore could only gaze over at the
fraternity of presidents he is campaigning to join.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's session was the first time Carter, Clinton and Ford
have been together at the White House since Sept. 14, 1993, when
they united in support of the North American Free Trade Agreement.
They traveled together aboard Air Force One to the funeral of King
Hussein of Jordan in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush attended both those events but skipped Tuesday's
gathering due to a scheduling conflict. Ronald Reagan, suffering
from Alzheimer's, also did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ford's first visit to the White House this year. He came
last October to receive the Congressional Gold Medal. Carter, who
received his medal from Clinton in Atlanta last year, stopped by
last month to show his grandchildren where he used to live. He
wandered over to the West Wing again Tuesday, along with Clinton's
former chief of staff, Leon Panetta, and others.
</P>
<P>
   The three presidents entered the East Room in lockstep. Just as
he does in politics, Clinton claimed the middle, Carter on his left
and Ford on his right. On stage it was Carter in the middle,
leaning over now and then to lend Clinton an ear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell you, I was very, very proud that I have been able to
serve this country with all three of these gentlemen,'' said Young.
He was Carter's United Nations ambassador, served in Congress with
Ford and works with Clinton through the Southern Africa Enterprise
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ford provided a moment of warmth, introducing Carter, who
defeated him in 1976, as ''a very dear and good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton played the fawning admirer, saying that
having so many political heavyweights in the room was ''just
profoundly humbling for me.'' He covered his face and chortled with
laughter as Kissinger joked that many in the room ''could not even
be charitably described as colleagues,'' while Ford and Carter
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was so caught up in the moment that at the end, he sped
off from Ford and Carter to greet Kissinger and Baker. Then he
sheepishly returned to the microphone to invite his guests to drop
by the Blue Room, where he, Ford and Carter were gathering to
welcome the guests.
</P>
<P>
   ''I forgot my social responsibilities here,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1715 </TRAILER>
