<HEADLINE> Timeline Of Former La. Gov. Edwards  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Highlights of the life and career of former Gov.
Edwin Edwards:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Aug. 7, 1927: Born in Marksville, La.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1948-49: Navy Air Corps pilot.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1949: Earns law degree from Louisiana State University at age
21. Begins law practice in Crowley, La.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1954-62: Serves on Crowley City Council.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1964: Elected to state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1965: Elected to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1972: Elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1973: Pushes legislation that taxes oil by value rather than
volume, giving government a financial bonanza. Faces criticism for
gambling trips to Las Vegas. Internal Revenue Service investigates
his tax returns, but no charges are filed.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1975: Re-elected governor against token opposition.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1977: As federal investigators look into Korean
influence-peddling in Washington, Edwards admits he and his wife
received $20,000 in 1971 and 1972 from a South Korean government
agent. The Edwardses are called before grand juries and the U.S.
House Ethics Committee, but no charges are filed.
</P>
<P>
   Former aide Clyde Vidrine publishes ''Just Takin' Orders,'' a
book that details Edwards' frequent gambling trips, describes some
allegedly illegal activities and characterizes him as a notorious
woman-chaser. The book does nothing to diminish the governor's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1979: Looked at by FBI agents investigating possible
wrongdoing in the awarding of state group benefits contracts.
Edwards' top aide, Charles Roemer II, is convicted in bribery
scheme but Edwards is not indicted. Roemer's conviction is later
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1980: Leaves governor's office unable to serve more than two
consecutive terms under the state constitution. Appointed to a
brief, temporary term on the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1983: Elected to a third term as governor. Federal grand jury
criticizes Edwards for his involvement during his second term in a
tax shelter plan for state employees, but does not indict him.
Edwards' brother Nolan slain by former law client.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1985: Edwards indicted and goes on trial, accused of brokering
state hospital and nursing home permits while in and out of office.
Trial ends in hung jury.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1986: A second jury acquits Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1987: Tries for an unprecedented fourth term. Runs second in
the primary and shocks the state by dropping out of a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1989: Edwards divorces wife of 40 years, Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1991: Runs for a fourth term. Beats incumbent -- Buddy Roemer,
son of former Edwards aide -- in the primary and former Ku Klux
Klansman David Duke in a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1994: Marries for a second time, the 29-year-old Candace
Picou.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1996: Leaves office after fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1998: Indicted in gambling corruption case, along with son
Stephen and five other men. Federal prosecutors allege a scheme to
extort hundreds of thousands of dollars from businessmen applying
for riverboat casino licenses.
</P>
<P>
   -- 1999: Indicted in a failed insurance company case with state
Insurance Commissioner and president of Cascade Insurance Co. They
were accused of arranging a sweetheart liquidation deal for Cascade
Insurance. Edwards also named as an unindicted co-conspirator in a
set of indictments that charged former Houston Mayor Fred Hofheinz
and Edwards' good friend, Cecil Brown. Prosecutors say they believe
Brown gave money to Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   -- May 9, 2000: Convicted on 17 of 26 counts in the federal
racketeering case involving casino licenses. His son Stephen also
convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1726 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000509.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coalition: School construction should help revitalize cities  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Legislation creating a statewide school
construction program lacks the vision to revitalize decaying
cities, a new coalition that advocates urban renewal said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It should be rewritten, members said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the latest in the ongoing struggle over how to structure
the largest school construction program in New Jersey's history.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition, just now jumping into the fray after more than a
year of wrangling over the measure, is asking the Legislature to
incorporate provisions designed to help revitalize New Jersey's
ailing cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Our Children's Schools, which includes
community organizations, business leaders and child advocates,
wants lawmakers to scrap a plan to have a central state agency
oversee the jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, group members say districts, municipalities and
community organizations should control the projects, with state
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow towns to design schools that meet the
community's needs and give jobs to local people, said Alan Mallach,
of the Affordable Housing Network of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition members also want the legislation to allow districts
to create ''community schools'' that have everything from health
clinics to meeting rooms for community groups. They also want to
tie school construction to community projects, such as housing
development, to revitalize neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   They say the current measure misses a huge opportunity to
leverage funds that could fix blighted neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do this right, our children, our communities and our
state will benefit,'' said Diane Sterner, executive director of the
Affordable Housing Network of New Jersey. ''If we don't, the chance
might never come again.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't have strong schools in crumbling cities,'' added Tom
O'Neill, director of the Partnership New Jersey, a coalition of
major New Jersey companies.
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers have already rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Senate Education Committee passed a bill that
eliminated a provision that would have required school districts to
work with municipal governments to decide whether redevelopment
efforts could be incorporated into school construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   As part of continuing negotiations, the senators scaled that
back to encourage economic development around new schools in six
unidentified pilot cities.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have insisted that a state agency oversee the
construction in 30 of New Jersey's poorest districts because, under
the Senate version of the bill, the state would pay the entire cost
of construction in those districts. Suburban districts would get at
least 40 percent of their construction costs paid by the state,
under the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, sponsor of the Assembly
version of the measure, has reservations about the community
development idea, according to his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's afraid that proponents of community development are
trying to expand the scope of the program beyond building
schools,'' said Chuck Leitgeb. ''And the cost of this program, it
appears, is growing weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   Leitgeb said the speaker has asked the nonpartisan Office of
Legislative Services to explore the possibility of putting a cap on
the entire program, which is now estimated to cost $12 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When the construction program was first proposed a couple of
years ago, state officials estimated it would cost about $6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really need to start taking a step back and see what we can
reasonably afford,'' said Leitgeb. ''The goal was to build schools,
but there was only so much money to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   The state is under court order to fix crumbling schools in 30 of
New Jersey's poorest school districts. Gov. Christie Whitman and
lawmakers also have promised to help the rest of New Jersey's
school districts fix old schools or build new ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
