<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Tuesday, May 9, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco Earnings Top Expectations
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Profits for Internet equipment provider
Cisco Systems Inc. topped Wall Street expectations for the ninth
consecutive quarter, as companies snapped up its equipment for
routing Web and data traffic. For the three months ended April 29,
the company reported net income of $662 million, or 9 cents per
share, up from $636 million, or 9 cents per share, in the year-ago
period. The numbers include $488 million in research and
development write-offs as well as other one-time items. Excluding
those numbers, Cisco earned $1.03 billion, or 14 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   BMW Agrees To Sell Rover Car Group
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A British consortium clinched a deal Tuesday to
take over the money-losing Rover car business from Germany's BMW
and save thousands of jobs in Britain. The successful bid by the
Phoenix consortium, led by former Rover chief executive John
Towers, staves off the closure of the country's largest car
factory. For BMW, the sale ends a costly and embarrassing foray
into the mainstream auto market. The luxury carmaker invested $4
billion in a failed, six-year effort to restore Rover to
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Close To Deciding Cable Deal
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission is
nearing a decision on a merger that would position telephone giant
AT&AMP;T as the nation's top cable TV company, officials said today.
The proposed deal between AT&AMP;T and MediaOne has raised concerns at
the agency about how much control over programming the combined
entity would be able to exercise. For that reason, FCC staff have
proposed actions the companies could take to complete the deal,
while complying with federal limits on how many cable households
one entity can reach.
</P>
<P>
   CBS Rejects Christian Dot-Com Ads
</P>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Christian e-tailer iBelieve.com
wanted to advertise on the high-profile network miniseries
''Jesus,'' but CBS rejected the ads on the grounds that their
content is too similar to the program and might confuse viewers.
The two-part TV program begins Sunday night. At the same time, the
Web merchant says it is being courted by www.CBS.com to sponsor
online sites for ''Jesus'' and the ''Touched by an Angel'' series.
CBS said there is nothing inconsistent about one CBS division
rejecting advertising while another pursued it.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods To Market Soymilk
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Bestfoods this week plans to introduce a new
soymilk for the U.S. market. Other companies that have jumped into
the soy business include PepsiCo Inc.'s, Kellogg Co., Kraft Foods
Inc., H.J. Heinz Co. and the nation's two biggest dairy processors,
Dean Foods Co. and Suiza Foods Corp. Soy beverage sales reached
$126 million for the year, a 60 percent increase. Analysts expect
the soy market to continue growing, in part because the government
is allowing soy products to claim that soy protein lowers blood
cholesterol levels.
</P>
