<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness says she saw man kill boy witness, mother  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A courtroom was filled with the sound
of sobs Tuesday as a woman described the murders of 8-year-old
Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''They was trying to get away. They was running up the stairs,''
Josephine Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard a gunshot.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Her son was calling out, 'Mommy, Mommy, Mommy, Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee is the prosecution's star witness in the murder trial of
Russell Peeler, who is accused of plotting the killings of B.J. and
his mother, Karen Clarke, to stop the boy from testifying against
him in an earlier murder.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. had witnessed a 1997 driveby shooting in which Peeler had
allegedly tried to kill Clarke's fiance, Rudolph Snead Jr. When
Snead was shot to death in a Bridgeport barber shop eight months
later, B.J. agreed to testify against Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   As Lee described the boy's anguished cries for help, several
people in the courtroom cried. A female relative of Clarke's
yelled, ''Oh, God,'' then left the courtroom sobbing. Lee, still
seated in the witness chair, also began to cry, and rubbed her face
with a tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who lived across the street from B.J. and his mother, said
she was the lookout and watched as Peeler's brother, Adrian, gunned
down the mother and son in their Bridgeport duplex on Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   She also told the jury she overheard the two brothers planning
the killings the day before the murders.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee's testimony was challenged by Russell Peeler's defense
attorneys, who grilled her about the numerous and varied accounts
she has given to police and prosecutors over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lee admitted under cross-examination that she had lied numerous
times in her first three statements to police.
</P>
<P>
   But while she was testifying, Lee remained composed, even feisty
at times, as she insisted she was now being truthful.
</P>
<P>
   Lee stuck closely to a videotaped deposition she gave in
November, when she described acting as a lookout and an eyewitness
to the murders.
</P>
<P>
   She said that on the day before the killings, Russell and Adrian
were in her kitchen, cooking crack cocaine and talking about B.J.
and his mother.
</P>
<P>
   She said Russell Peeler first asked her if she would kill the
mother and son, and when she refused, turned to his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told Adrian, 'I want you to do me a favor and kill the lady
and the little boy across the street,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Adrian said, 'I'll take care of it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she agreed to page Russell Peeler when Clarke arrived
home. In return, Russell gave her a handful of crack, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Jan. 7, 1999, Lee paged Russell when Clarke and
her son arrived home from grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Adrian showed up at her house a short time later
carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said when she knocked on Clarke's door, Clarke cracked it
open.
</P>
<P>
   ''Adrian pushed (himself) in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she watched as Adrian chased B.J. and his mother. She
said she heard a gunshot as they ran up the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   After B.J. called over and over again for his mother, Lee said
she heard Adrian talking to Clarke in her bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard Adrian say something about her fiance ... about how
her son was a witness to some kind of shooting,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she heard another shot from the bedroom. The boy, she
said, ''was still hollering out for his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said Adrian then came out of the bedroom and shot the boy in
the head.
</P>
<P>
   During three hours of cross-examination, Peeler's lawyer,
William Koch, went after Lee's testimony -- detail by detail.
</P>
<P>
   Koch asked Lee to explain why Clarke's blood was found on
grocery bags near the front door if, as she claims, the first shot
was not fired until Adrian was chasing Clarke and her son up the
stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't tell you. I don't know,'' replied Clarke. ''It
happened so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch also asked Lee about how she was treated by police and
prosecutors once she told them in March 1999 that Russell and
Adrian Peeler were involved in the killings. She said she was put
up in a hotel, given pocket money and sent to a drug detoxification
program on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Lee answered matter-of-factly when asked about how she was
treated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ate good, I slept good, and that was that,'' she said,
shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit murder, received
a plea bargain in which she agreed to testify against the Peelers
and the state agreed to recommend a sentence of no more than seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Peeler, who has also been charged with murder, is
scheduled to go on trial once his brother's trial is completed.
Both brothers face the possibility of the death penalty if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The killings sparked a public outcry and led to an overhaul of
the state's witness protection program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1732 </TRAILER>
