<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auditors: Pentagon Books Way Off  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite some recent improvements, the
Pentagon's bookkeeping remains so convoluted and primitive that
assets worth billions of dollars cannot be properly accounted for,
congressional auditors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''To date, no major part of Department of Defense has yet been
able to pass the test of an independent audit,'' said a report by
the General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials admitted outdated business practices and
flawed systems are rife within the agency but said it would take
some years more to get all the agency's books in order.
</P>
<P>
   ''This continues to be one of my highest priorities,'' Pentagon
Comptroller William Lynn told a House Government Reform
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Steinhoff, the GAO's assistant comptroller general, told
the panel the Pentagon ''does not know the actual amount and value
of inventory for which it is responsible.'' He put the estimate at
$1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the GAO's detailed criticisms:
</P>
<P>
   --Around 58 percent of the materiel the Pentagon has in its
possession -- $36.9 billion worth of items -- it does not need.
</P>
<P>
   --A $600 billion Pentagon inventory of weapons systems and other
''national defense assets'' failed to include $5.7 billion in Army
communications equipment, $7.6 billion in Navy aircraft engines and
about $7 billion in Air Force electronic systems pods that attach
to warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   --The Navy lost track of $3 billion in equipment and other items
over a three-year period, but most of the items the Navy reported
as lost were delivered, and there ''was no evidence of theft in the
shipments we reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., chairman of the Government Reform
subcommittee on government management, information and technology,
said the Pentagon's ''financial information is simply not
reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report follows one in March by the office of the Defense
Department's inspector general that also concluded the Pentagon's
books were so messed up they couldn't be audited.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to believe that the department remains a few years
away from being able to achieve favorable audit opinions on most
major financial statements,'' Robert Lieberman, an assistant
Pentagon inspector general, told Tuesday's congressional hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The department is making progress,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: General Accounting Office: http://www.gao.gov
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department inspector general: http://www.dodig.osd.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
