<HEADLINE> Clinton thanks Pataki for leadership on ballistic fingerprints  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Saying that gun control should be a bipartisan
issue, Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton on Tuesday saluted
Republican Gov. George Pataki for his leadership on ballistic
fingerprinting.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also endorsed the Million Mom March, an anti-gun
protest in Washington on Sunday, Mother's Day, that she will
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I applaud Gov. Pataki here in this state who showed real
leadership in proposing a state-based ballistics program,'' she
said in a speech in Manhattan to the Newspaper Association of
America. ''I think it is something that needs to be done on the
national level. Gun safety measures should be a bipartisan
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Republican opponent in the Senate race, New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, is also a strong proponent of gun control
and has endorsed Pataki's ballistic fingerprinting proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Every gun leaves unique traces on bullets, and Pataki's proposal
would require that a sample ballistics test be performed on every
weapon sold in the state to create a database for tracing guns used
in crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also endorsed a proposal by Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., to require a license of anyone buying a handgun and
create a national registry of every new handgun sold in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In championing Sunday's march, Clinton said: ''Ordinary
citizens, women, who just finally had enough, are organizing and
marching for the changes they think would make their jobs as
mothers easier to do ... I will be one mom who will be proud to
march with all of the others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
