<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugees Flee Sierre Leone Town  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- United Nations peacekeepers,
followed by frightened refugees, have retreated from a key village
outside this West African capital, U.N. officials said Tuesday,
while regional leaders met in Nigeria in an effort to defuse the
week-old crisis threatening to push Sierra Leone once again into
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers withdrew from Masiaka, 45 miles east of
Freetown, on Monday after exchanging gunfire with unknown attackers
and running out of ammunition, U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said.
Word of the retreat did not reach Freetown for more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   While rebels of the Revolutionary United Front are believed to
be in the region, it was unclear if they were responsible.
Helicopter reconnaissance showed the city was completely empty
Tuesday afternoon, Wimhurst said, but added: ''Freetown is not
going to fall to the RUF.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of refugees from the Masiaka area had reached the edge
of Freetown by Tuesday afternoon, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In this seaside city, word of the fighting broadcast over the
radio quickly spread fear through the city after what had been a
peaceful Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are so worried ... that we heard that the rebels had
attacked Masiaka and Masiaka is so close to the city,'' said Edward
Moseray, a civil servant.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the country's rebel leader, Foday Sankoh,
added to the gloom. He had been under U.N. guard before Monday's
shooting outside his Freetown home. The rumor mill had Sankoh
anywhere from the Sierra Leonean jungle to an army safehouse, but
U.N. officials said they did not know where he was.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are anxious to find a way to contact him,'' Wimhurst told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Sierra Leone has become increasingly chaotic
since a Nigerian-led regional intervention force pulled out last
week. Since then, clashes have broken out intermittently between
peacekeepers and rebels and some 500 peacekeepers are being held
hostage by the RUF. At least one peacekeeper is believed to be
dead.
</P>
<P>
   In Abuja, Nigeria, presidents from around the region were
meeting to try to defuse the crisis. While it was unclear how many
leaders had made it to the mini-summit, it was planned to include
the presidents of Nigeria, Sierra Leone, Burkina Faso, Liberia and
Guinea, among others.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the United States had sent a ''fact-finding'' team
from U.S. European Command to Nigeria on Monday to assess what help
the U.S. military might provide if Nigeria or other African nations
decide to augment their peacekeeping role in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Press reports in Nigeria say that country is considering sending
soldiers back to Sierra Leone, perhaps as a fighting force that
would not operate under the peacekeepers' limited mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. has also said the U.S. Air Force was prepared to fly in
a battalion of U.N. peacekeepers from Bangladesh -- roughly 700 to
800 soldiers -- in coming days. The United Nations wants to speed up
deployment of that battalion and two others scheduled to arrive by
mid-July, bringing the U.N. force up to its full strength of
11,100.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a U.N. spokesman said the three remaining
battalions appear ready to deploy by next week but so far only the
Bangladeshi contingent has air transport.
</P>
<P>
   British helicopters, meanwhile, continued swooping into Freetown
on Tuesday, ferrying out frightened Britons.
</P>
<P>
   In London, a Ministry of Defense spokeswoman said about 320
British, European Union and Commonwealth citizens had been
evacuated so far. They were flown to Sierra Leone's main airport
and then most were taken by airplane to Dakar, the capital of
Senegal, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, the crowds of evacuees had thinned but some were
still waiting to be flown from a helipad near the now heavily
militarized Mammy Yoko hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations late Monday began evacuating some of its 266
nonessential civilian employees. Another 55 were staying in
Freetown, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the evacuations and Monday's clashes, the streets of
this seaside capital were calm Tuesday, with many stores open and
people moving about freely.
</P>
<P>
   At least four demonstrators were gunned down by rebels Monday
when thousands of rock-throwing marchers headed for Sankoh's house,
though doctors at Freetown's main hospital said 20 people had been
killed over the past night, and 54 more had gunshot wounds. It
wasn't clear, though, how many had been killed in the initial
gunfire and how many in other incidents. At least some of those
killed are believed to be rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leonean army soldiers, who under a July peace plan are
supposed to be disarmed, and fighters from the pro-government
Kamajor militia, fought the rebels for hours at Sankoh's home after
the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings in Freetown, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard
described Sierra Leone's peace process as being in ''deep
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Miyet, the head of U.N. peacekeeping operations, arrived
in Freetown on Monday night and was meeting U.N. soldiers and
officials to assess the situation and ''to demonstrate to ... the
world that we're determined to put the peace process back on
track,'' Wimhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone, among the world's poorest countries despite vast
diamond resources, was brutalized during eight years of civil war,
which ended with a peace accord last July that created a
power-sharing government. In principle, that deal included the
rebels and Sankoh, whose forces killed and maimed thousands during
the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1745 </TRAILER>
