<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.F. Fed Chief Defends Rate Hikes  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE M. PETERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Predictions that the Federal Reserve Bank
may raise interest rates more aggressively are not out of character
with the agency's cautionary approach, said regional Fed chief
Robert T. Parry.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we've moved cautiously but that doesn't mean that we
only have a single note to play. ... In addition, I'm not sure I
would necessarily consider a second note as being inconsistent with
caution,'' Parry told the Northern California Financial Planning
Conference meeting in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of
San Francisco would not indicate Tuesday which direction the Fed
might be leaning when it meets next week. ''I can't say where we'll
end up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe the Fed will raise interest rates at the
May 16 meeting, but it was unclear if the panel would stray from
recent increases of one-quarter point, or be more aggressive, going
up to a half point.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, the Fed has raised interest rates five times in
quarter-point increments in an effort to curb inflation in the
midst of a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of higher interest rates was fanned by the announcement
last week that the employment rate had hit a 30-year low of 3.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While strong job and wage growth is good for workers, economists
and members of the Fed worry that the combination could raise
inflation. They fear that employers scrambling to find scarce
workers will raise wages and benefits -- costs that could be passed
to consumers in higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the economy has exploded over the past
several years is because of productivity related to the advances in
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Parry, whose district includes nine states, said he believes
productivity could accelerate fast enough to push inflation down.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it's not something I think we can count on,'' he said.
''So, even though it's clear that technological advances are
expanding the supply side of the economy, we still have to watch
for conditions that raise inflationary risks.''
</P>
<P>
   He outlined several of these potential risks, including
increased energy prices, tight labor markets, and the growth of
consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a question about how far the Fed will have to go in
terms of raising rates over the next two years, Parry said
''there's just too much uncertainty to predict what's going to
happen over the next 2 or 2{ years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The real issue is whether we've done enough, and if we haven't
done enough, how much more will we have to do?'' he asked. ''No one
knows the answer to that question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1745 </TRAILER>
