<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart 1Q Profits Rise  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK BARTELS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s first-quarter earnings
rose sharply from a year ago, and the world's biggest retailer said
it expects to maintain healthy sales and profit growth for the
remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bentonville, Ark.-based chain reported Tuesday that it
earned $1.326 billion, or 30 cents a share, for the quarter ended
April 30, compared with $916 million, or 20 cents a share, a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's results include a 4 cent charge for a change in the
company's accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the quarter totaled $42.99 billion, up from $34.71
billion a year ago. Sales at stores open at least a year, an
industry gauge of performance, rose 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's results topped Wall Street analysts estimates of 28
cents a share. The company's stock rose 62{ cents to $53 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 15 percent in its Wal-Mart Stores division, which
includes its Supercenters that combine traditional discount stores
with supermarkets. Profits in the division gained 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Food sales were particular strong at its Supercenters,
increasing 36 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Its international division saw a 118 percent growth in sales and
profits more than doubled. The gains were largely attributed to its
acquisition last year of ASDA Group, the third-largest grocery
chain in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Its stores in Germany, however, continue to struggle. Wal-Mart
is spending heavily on distribution centers and remodeling of
stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Sam's Club warehouse division reported a 8.9 percent gain in
sales and a 10.5 percent rise in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's strength in the first quarter came despite
cooler-than-normal weather through most of April, which dampened
sales at many retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wal-Mart was a little affected by it,'' said Kurt Barnard, who
runs the consulting firm Barnard's Retail Trend Report in Upper
Montclair, N.J. ''But for other retailers, it was a washout, a
rainout, a snowout.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking forward, Wal-Mart expects earnings and sales growth to
continue in the coming quarters.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with analysts, David Glass, Wal-Mart's
former top executive who now head its board's executive committee,
said the chain does not sense a slowdown in consumer spending, even
though some Wall Street analysts and economists have said that
Americans will scale back their buying later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Historically, Wal-Mart has gained market share during those
periods. We position our assortment in a way that we limit our
upside potential in boom times but eliminate downside exposure to
the extent that we possibly can,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   The optimistic outlook from Wal-Mart caused many retail analysts
to raise their estimates for the coming quarters and full year.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, the company opened 32 Supercenters, seven
discount stores and two Sam's Club stores. It also opened 10
international stores in Britain, Brazil and China.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 30, Wal-Mart had 1,784 discount stores, 753
Supercenters and 465 Sam's Clubs. Internationally, Wal-Mart has
1,011 stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1747 </TRAILER>
