<HEADLINE> Other Defendants in Edwards Trial  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The other defendants in former Gov. Edwin Edwards'
federal
racketeering trial:
Stephen Edwards
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second of Edwin Edwards' four children and the only one to
follow his dad into law school, Stephen emerged as a key campaign
aide for his father in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Edwards' business performs consultant and legal work for
the riverboat casino industry. Prosecutors accused him of serving
as the manager of the elaborate extortion scheme they said his
father masterminded. But what prosecutors called payoffs, the
defense said were really legitimate payments for legal and
consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted Tuesday of 18 of 23 counts. If convicted of all 23
charges, he could have faced up to 280 years in prison and a $6
million fine.
Andrew Martin
</P>
<P>
   A former chairman of the State Mineral Board, Andrew Martin
became an aide to Edwards during his 1991 gubernatorial campaign.
He was bodyguard (who carried an automatic weapon), a legislative
committee monitor and right-hand man to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   As the administration ended, Martin would sit in on meetings of
committees that dealt with gambling issues, though he is not
registered as a lobbyist. Martin would tell reporters he was ''just
visiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accused him of demanding and receiving $100,000 in
monthly extortion payments from former Treasure Chest Casino owner
Robert Guidry. The money, prosecutors said, was divided between
Martin and the Edwardses. Guidry testified that he sometimes left
the money in trash bins for Martin to retrieve.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said Guidry, who testified under a plea
agreement, lied in hopes of getting a light sentence and to stave
off a federal investigation of his $300 million tugboat business.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of all charges Tuesday. Faces up to 120 years in
prison and a $1.75 million fine.
Cecil Brown
</P>
<P>
   A cattleman and auctioneer from Eunice, La., Cecil Brown met
Edwin Edwards during his first term in office when he asked Brown
to break in a horse.
</P>
<P>
   He often joined Edwards on the campaign trail and the two
started a few businesses together, including a paint and patch
company that was run by Edwards' son David.
</P>
<P>
   The cattleman acknowledges he was paid to help win Edwards'
favor for two projects: building a private juvenile prison in Jena,
La., and bringing a professional basketball team to New Orleans.
Edwards gave support to both deals during his last term but they
fell through and soon were under the scrutiny of federal
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and former Houston Mayor Fred Hofheinz were indicted in
November in connection with the projects. A date for their trial
has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, prosecutors said Brown extorted a group of
investors from the St. Louis area and worked with co-defendant
Bobby Johnson to extort the former owners of the Belle of Baton
Rouge. Defense lawyers said Brown was paid for legitimate
consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of all charges Tuesday. Faces up to 80 years in prison
and a $1 million fine.
Greg Tarver
</P>
<P>
   A powerful state senator who once was active in the civil rights
movement, Tarver runs a successful mortuary and insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged that Tarver gave Edwards a confidential
background report on applicants for the state's final riverboat
license and that Edwards forwarded it to San Francisco 49ers owner
Eddie DeBartolo Jr. But they were unable to come up with hard
evidence that it was Tarver who gave DeBartolo the report.
</P>
<P>
   Acquitted of all charges Tuesday. Could have faced up to 55
years in prison and a $2.75 million fine.
Ecotry Fuller
</P>
<P>
   A retired teacher and school principal, Fuller is a member of
the Louisiana Gaming Control Board. While he refused to give up his
seat, he had not attended a board meeting since he was implicated
in the case in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that in 1997 Fuller gave co-defendant Greg
Tarver a copy of a confidential state police report about
applicants for a riverboat license. They also claimed he lied to
the federal grand jury about whether he had given the report to
Tarver. As in the Tarver case, there was no hard evidence to show
that it was Fuller and Tarver who helped DeBartolo get the report.
</P>
<P>
   Acquitted of all charges Tuesday. Could have faced up to 60
years in prison and a $3 million fine.
Bobby Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Johnson is a millionaire contractor and real estate
investor even though he claims to be illiterate. Johnson said he
grew up on the streets of Baton Rouge after being kicked out of his
home as a teen-ager and never made it past seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said he extorted Jazz Enterprises Inc., which sought
and received a riverboat casino license. A government witness
secretly recorded several conversations with Johnson. The defense
cast Johnson as a braggart and buffoon whose threats and promises
were not to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of all charges Tuesday. Faces up to 90 years in prison
and a $2.25 million fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
