<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police: Atlantic City man killed witness who testified against him  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- A man who was acquitted of murder
last year after insisting ''I ain't capable of killing nobody'' is
now accused of fatally beating a witness who testified against him.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Jenkins, 22, of Absecon, is accused of bludgeoning
Arthur Thomas, 42, to death with a brick Monday outside a housing
project here.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins was acquitted last June in the Feb. 20, 1997 killing of
drug dealer Mark Cotton, who was found shot to death behind a
building. He was arrested more than a year after the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ain't capable of killing nobody,'' a tearful Jenkins told a
judge during his arraignment in the first killing. His attorney,
Ralph Paolone, said it was a case of mistaken identity; another man
shot Cotton, Paolone said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, one of two witnesses to put Jenkins at the scene,
testified that he saw Jenkins before the killing with a gun that
looked like the one used in the killing. He also said he saw
Jenkins running from the scene moments later, after gunshots rang
out.
</P>
<P>
   But jurors believed Jenkins, clearing him after a five-day
trial.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he allegedly made reference to Thomas' testimony when
he encountered him near a flight of steps outside the Lexington
Courts projects on Delaware Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Wielding a brick, he struck Thomas at least twice in the back of
the head, knocking him down the steps, where Thomas suffered
further head injury, according to First Assistant Atlantic County
Prosecutor Murray Talasnik.
</P>
<P>
   The brick fractured Thomas' skull and jammed pieces of it into
Thomas' brain, according to an autopsy conducted by Dr. Hydow Park,
the county medical examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a security guard at a supermarket who was engaged to be
married and had a daughter, died at the scene. For 90 minutes, his
body lay in full view of pedestrians and passing casino buses as
police documented the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, whose criminal record includes drug and weapons
arrests, was being held on $500,000 bail. In addition to murder, he
is charged with possession of a weapon for an unlawful purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, he stood handcuffed and wearing an orange jail
jumpsuit. He did not have an attorney as Superior Court Judge
Albert J. Garofolo read him his rights and asked him if he
understood the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Garofolo ordered him to submit to fingerprinting after Talasnik
told the judge that Jenkins had ''some unpleasantness'' when
officers attempted to get his prints in jail Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought my lawyer was supposed to be present,'' said
Jenkins. Garofolo said it wasn't required.
</P>
<P>
   Talasnik would not comment on the motive. He said witnesses in
murder trials occasionally get protection from law enforcement
during trial, but not afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Prosecutor Joel Mayer, who prosecuted Jenkins in the
first killing, said Thomas did not ask for or receive protection.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Thomas was a reluctant witness in my murder trial, but no
more so than most individuals who are exposed to high-crime areas.
I would hope, certainly, that there won't be a chilling effect (on
future crime witnesses). The overwhelming majority of the people
who live there still want to do the right thing,'' Mayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Talasnik said it would be up to a judge to determine whether
information about the Cotton killing is admitted into evidence if
Jenkins goes to trial for the second killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's certainly a terrible, tragic circumstance -- for Mr.
Thomas and his family, and for everyone in this neighborhood who
wants to do the right thing,'' Mayer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1808 </TRAILER>
