<HEADLINE> WPP, Y&AMP;R Reports Send Shares Down  </HEADLINE>
By SKIP WOLLENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wall Street sent the stocks of advertising
powerhouses WPP Group PLC and Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. lower Tuesday
following reports that the companies had agreed in principle on a
stock-swap combination.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies declined comment for the second day on
assertions by sources familiar with the talks that London-based WPP
Group had agreed in principle to acquire Y&AMP;R for stock in a deal
that would make WPP the world's biggest ad company.
</P>
<P>
   The sources, who spoke on condition that they not be named, said
the companies had agreed on a share swap ratio that valued Y&AMP;R at
about $5.3 billion as of Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   But WPP's American Depositary Receipts, the vehicle under which
WPP shares are traded in the United States, tumbled 11.4 percent on
Monday and another 5.4 percent on Tuesday, shaving the present
value of the deal to about $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   WPP ADRs fell $3.62{ to $63.25 on Tuesday on the Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R's shares, which lost 8 percent on Monday, were down another
7.3 percent, or $3.625 a share, to $46.18} in trading Tuesday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said WPP is offering 0.835 of its ADRs for each Y&AMP;R
share, valuing it at $52.81 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price declines could suggest the market doubts that
the deal will be completed.
</P>
<P>
   But the sources said the companies were ironing out legal
details of the deal and were enlisting support of key Y&AMP;R
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R executives are scheduled to appear Friday before the
company's annual shareholders meeting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Y&AMP;R and WPP Group have been discussing a deal for
about four months and their talks broke down twice only to be
revived later.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies share some powerful clients including Ford Motor
Co., Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. and Kraft Foods.
</P>
</TEXT>
