<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile Of Edwin Edwards  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN McGILL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- No story sums up the lore of Edwin
Edwards better than the one told since the early 1980s -- the one
about him on stage at a religious gathering where the preacher
asked everyone to stand who never drank, smoked or lusted after
another's mate.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards remained sitting. ''Two out of three ain't bad,'' he
said, to great laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Picture a non-smoking, Scripture-quoting teetotaler who loves
high-stakes gambling, beautiful women and ribald jokes. At age 72,
Louisiana's four-term former governor still wears the disparate
images comfortably -- although he makes it clear these days that his
35-year-old wife, Candy, is now the only woman in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' rakish image was cultivated over a 46-year public life.
Born in 1927 to a sharecropper and a midwife, he was elected in
1954 to the City Council of rural Crowley, La.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was a Cajun, a descendant of the Nova Scotian exiles
who settled southwestern Louisiana more than two centuries ago.
Edwards' softly Cajun-accented speech would become as much a part
of his persona as his neatly groomed silver hair and quick, deadpan
wit.
</P>
<P>
   From Crowley, Edwards moved on to the state Senate in 1964, then
to Congress in 1965. Then it was the governor's office and a 1972
inauguration during which he took the oath of office in English and
in French.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know this many Cajuns owned tuxedos,'' he quipped at
the inaugural ball.
</P>
<P>
   Hints of scandal would arise soon afterward. Grand juries would
look into his finances and campaign contributions in the early and
mid-1970s. There would be congressional hearings and grand jury
appearances leading to his admission in 1977 that he and his
then-wife, Elaine, received $20,000 in 1971 and 1972 from a South
Korean government agent. Nothing came of any of it.
</P>
<P>
   A disgruntled former aide, Clyde Vidrine, wrote a book in 1974
accusing Edwards of exchanging high-level jobs for campaign
contributions. Investigations followed but again, nothing came of
them.
</P>
<P>
   And Vidrine's allegations that Edwards indulged in rampant
womanizing seemed only to enhance the governor's image.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards was far from just a playboy.
</P>
<P>
   He was a deft politician, a populist Democrat who proudly touted
his courting of minorities and the poor as a source of personal
pride.
</P>
<P>
   As Louisiana's economic fortunes grew during the 1970s' oil
boom, he was able to take advantage of rising prices by having the
state switch its method of taxing oil from a rate based on volume
to a percentage of value.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards left the governor's office in 1979 at the height of his
popularity, constitutionally prohibited from a third consecutive
term.
</P>
<P>
   He came back in 1983, defeating his successor, Dave Treen, in a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   But 1983 also saw the murder of his brother Nolan, an attorney
shot to death in his Crowley office by a disgruntled client. And
there would be more personal and political travails once Edwards
regained office.
</P>
<P>
   While the state's financial and economic fortunes fell with the
price of oil, Edwards was indicted in 1985 on racketeering charges
stemming from hospital and nursing home investments.
</P>
<P>
   His 1985 trial featured characteristic Edwards humor. He arrived
one day in a mule-drawn carriage, saying it represented the pace of
the trial. Another time, noting that news photographers often have
to walk backward rapidly, he obliged them by backing into court.
</P>
<P>
   After one mistrial, Edwards was acquitted in 1986, but his
political fortunes were on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Either because of his trials or the state economy, he was
defeated for re-election in 1987 by Rep. Buddy Roemer. Edwards'
40-year marriage to Elaine ended in divorce in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts wrote him off as politically dead, but they had not
foreseen the rise of David Duke, the ex-Ku Klux Klan leader. Duke
narrowly won a state House seat in 1989 and garnered a relatively
small but politically significant power base.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Duke each got about a third of the vote in a 1991
gubernatorial primary, ousting Roemer. Edwards went on to win the
runoff in a landslide, aided by fears that having an ex-neo Nazi in
the governor's mansion would ruin the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vote for the crook, it's important,'' one popular bumper
sticker read.
</P>
<P>
   Going in to his fourth term, Edwards expressed hope of
burnishing his image.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I'm now thinking about is what will be said about me four
years, five years, 100 years from now,'' he said just before the
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   But federal prosecutors wanted him to be remembered for
allegedly conspiring with friends to extort money from applicants
for lucrative riverboat casino licenses. After a four-month trial,
Edwards was convicted on Tuesday of 17 counts of racketeering and
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have a saying, Edwards said after the verdict: ''If
you sit by a river long enough, the dead bodies of your enemies
will float by you. I suppose the feds sat by the river long enough
and here comes my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Edwards maintained his characteristic
composure and displayed his mischievous nature.
</P>
<P>
   One day, the doors had just closed on a crowded elevator near
the courtroom when Edwards leaned over to a Baton Rouge TV reporter
and asked her: ''Do you know the difference between sexual
relations and a Caesar salad?''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar with his ways, she eyed him warily and said, ''No.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughter erupted as the elevator doors opened and Edwards
responded, ''Could we discuss it over dinner some time?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1815 </TRAILER>
