<HEADLINE> Icahn Said Eyeing Penney Investment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Financier Carl Icahn, who gained a reputation as a
corporate raider in the 1980s by buying big stakes in undervalued
companies and pressed for changes, has indicated interest in a
major investment in struggling retailer J.C. Penney Co. Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing last week with federal regulators, Icahn indicated
he might make an investment exceeding $15 million but falling short
of 15 percent of Penney's outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Plano-based retailer said Tuesday they didn't
know Icahn's intentions and have not talked with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are aware of Mr. Icahn's filing and have had no direct
contact with him or his representatives,'' said Rita Trevino Flynn,
Penney spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Penney's stock, which has lost about two-thirds of its value in
the past 12 months, has improved in the last week on the
announcement that chief executive James Oesterreicher will retire
and on news of Icahn's interest.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Tuesday, Penney shares fell 75 cents to $18.06\ on
the New York Stock Exchange after gaining $1.62{ on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, Icahn profited handsomely through investments in
Texaco Inc., USX Corp. and Phillips Petroleum Co. He bought Trans
World Airlines Inc., which was later sold.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Icahn has indicated he is prepared to make a bid
for Nabisco Group Holding Corp., which owns 80.6 percent of the
company that makes Oreo cookies and Ritz crackers. He is one of
Nabisco Group's biggest shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   In his federal filing, Icahn also indicated intent to buy a
significant share in Seagate Technology Inc., based in Scotts
Valley, Calif., the leading computer disk drive maker.
</P>
</TEXT>
