<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blumenthal calls for investigation of vehicle emissions program  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Citing reports of widespread corruption
and criminal activity, Attorney General Richard Blumenthal is
calling for an investigation of the vehicle emissions testing and
safety inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said Tuesday he has received reports of bribes and
demands for payment for emission stickers as well as theft of
stickers, which are then sold on the street. The reports have come
from state police, consumers and emissions testing employees, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''These reports are extraordinarily credible, widespread and
alarming in their scope and magnitude and clearly warrant a full
investigation,'' Blumenthal said. ''These reports are very
troubling and even alarming because they mean a serious loss of
money due to the state and credibility significant to the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who requested the probe in a letter last week to
Department of Motor Vehicles Commissioner Jose Salinas, said his
office has received reports of Envirotest inspectors approving cars
with serious safety and emissions problems. His letter cites
reports of ''widespread corruption and criminal activity'' in the
emissions program run by Envirotest System Corp. in East Granby.
</P>
<P>
   Envirotest, which received a 10-year, $25 million state contract
in 1994 to run the emissions testing and safety inspections, denied
there is widespread fraud in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had two isolated incidents,'' said company spokeswoman
Martha Sanders. ''To me that does not mean widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   Those incidents, which occurred in Bridgeport and Darien, were
brought to light by the company, Sanders said. Employees were
arrested and fired, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Envirotest, which tests more than 1.2 million vehicles annually
at 25 stations, has a quality assurance department which conducts
daily record audits that look for irregularities, Sanders said.
Surveillance cameras monitor safety lanes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Envirotest also had an independent company recently conduct 34
covert audits at all stations, Sanders said. Employees were offered
$50 bribes to pass a vehicle and none took them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that since 1995 Envirotest has been fined
$425,000 by the state for its test records, inspection procedures
and record keeping. Envirotest officials said the fines resulted
from procedural issues, not fraud.
</P>
<P>
   DMV spokesman Bill Seymour said the agency has already been
looking into whether there is more widespread fraud after the
Darien and Bridgeport incidents. That investigation, which involves
state police, began about a month ago and has not reached any
conclusions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're hoping this is just a few bad apples in the barrel,''
Seymour said. ''We have made clear that the issue of fraud goes
directly to the integrity of the program and federal law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1827 </TRAILER>
