<DOCNO> APW20000509.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Issues Dominate Ethiopian Elections  </HEADLINE>
By ABEBE ANDUALEM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Land reform, better economic
management and respect for human rights have dominated a series of
unprecedented public debates in the run-up to only the second
nationwide elections in Ethiopia's history.
</P>
<P>
   The debates, attended by large crowds and rebroadcast by
state-run radio and television, have given political opponents of
the ruling Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Front a rare
opportunity to voice their complaints about the government.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, voters will choose a federal parliament, nine
regional assemblies and council members for the capital, Addis
Ababa, and the eastern city of Dire Dawa.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need a radical change in the Addis city administration,''
said shopkeeper Yoseph Desta, 46, complaining about high taxes and
few services. ''All of us are eagerly awaiting to see new faces
after the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The Front, a four-party coalition, has run the Horn of Africa
nation since 1991, when it ousted a Marxist regime that had been in
power for 17 years. It has gradually tolerated more open political
discussion in the impoverished nation.
</P>
<P>
   As it did in the country's first elections in May 1995, the
Front is expected to dominate Sunday's poll. The outcome is also
expected to confirm the fundamental role Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi and his Tigray People's Liberation Front plays in the
governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   One topic that did not figure in the public debate -- except when
support was expressed for the government's position -- is the
two-year border conflict with Eritrea which has left thousands of
soldiers and civilians dead on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more than 20 million of Ethiopia's estimated 29 million
eligible voters have registered, according to Akililou Merkuria of
the National Electoral Board. The population is estimated at 61.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   No elections will be held in the southeastern Somali region,
which has been hard-hit by drought and severe food shortages.
</P>
<P>
   The board says there are 65 legally recognized political parties
in Ethiopia. Seven are national parties, while the others are
regional groups.
</P>
<P>
   While international observers fanned out across the country to
monitor the vote five years ago, the government has restricted poll
watching this year to local groups.
</P>
<P>
   The pressing need for land reform and the uneven economic
development of Ethiopia's nine theoretically autonomous regions has
dominated debate in regional capitals.
</P>
<P>
   After the ouster of Emperor Haile Selassie in 1974, all land was
nationalized by the Marxist regime. The front wants to retain state
ownership of land, an issue that has divided opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition ranks are also split over an article in the 1995
constitution that grants regions and linguistic groups the right to
secede from the federation. But all opposition groups agree that
the allocation of federal funds is uneven and favors the country's
northern regions, the Front's political base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1831 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000509.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosectors Indict Alleged Drug Gang  </HEADLINE>
By DERRILL HOLLY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal prosecutors on Tuesday indicted 13
alleged gang members who prosecutors say were part of a citywide
drug dealing empire, an illegal enterprise reputed to have been the
most violent ever to operate in the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Within the 76-count indictment, individual members are accused
in 16 murders and 12 attempted murders. Investigators say they have
evidence that the group may have been involved in 17 other killings
in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin L. Gray, 28, the alleged ringleader who was indicted on 15
counts of murder, and Rodney Moore, 35, who is charged with seven
murders, have been held without bond since last October.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that since 1988, the two men supervised a
continuing criminal enterprise that included lookouts, drivers,
couriers, enforcers, street salesmen and runners. Some of the
employees of the operation were minors, presumably hired because
they faced potentially less severe punishments in the juvenile
justice system, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The organization distributed large quantities of cocaine,
heroin, crack cocaine and marijuana in several neighborhoods,''
said United States Attorney Wilma A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group protected their turf by robbing or killing
rival drug dealers and suspected informants, and they also robbed
their own customers, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ''These individuals also committed contract murders for hire,''
said Lewis, adding that cash or drugs were exchanged in return for
participation in murders.
</P>
<P>
   The 98-page indictment describes the use of a network of stash
houses, clandestine drug labs, cellular telephones, pagers, and
secret codes to evade detection.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the killings and much of the group's alleged criminal
activities occurred near housing projects and low income
neighborhoods, said Chief Charles Ramsey of the district's
Metropolitan Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   While 10 of the defendants are in custody, police and the FBI
were searching for Wilford Oliver, 52; Derrick Moore, 32; and Frank
Howard, 30.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, each defendant faces the possibility of life in
prison with no chance of parole. Eleven of them could face the
death penalty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1833 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
