<DOCNO> APW20000509.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Island Sound Bill Passes House  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Millions of dollars in federal money would go
to clean up Long Island Sound under legislation that sailed through
the House on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Partisan bickering last week threatened to scuttle the Long
Island Sound Restoration Act, but a coalition of New York and
Connecticut lawmakers united behind it and pushed it through.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over an unexplained die-off of lobsters in the Sound --
the nation's No. 3 lobster market -- helped rally support for the
measure, which passed 391-29.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Reps. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., and Nancy Johnson,
R-Conn., the bill would earmark $80 million a year for four years
to help upgrade sewage treatment facililties and decrease nitogen
runoff into the waterway. It would target runoff from roads,
parking lots and construction sites. And the bill would fund
habitat restoration projects.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most severe environmental problems facing the
110-mile Sound is hypoxia, which occurs when nitrogen released by
sewage treatment plants overstimulates algae growth. When algae
decays, it sucks up oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio-Johnson bill aims to cut nitrogen output by 58.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Govs. George Pataki in New York and John Rowland in Connecticut
have pledged $200 million and $260 million, respectively, for the
clean-up effort.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., is sponsoring a similar Long
Island Sound bill in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http/www.savethesound.org
</P>
<P>
   http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
