<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Aboards Boat in West Africa  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Navy has commandos aboard a patrol
boat in the waters off West Africa as a ''precautionary measure''
in light of the intensifying crisis in Sierra Leone, a Pentagon
spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, spokesman for Defense Secretary William Cohen,
said the Cyclone-class patrol boat USS Thunderbolt was not directly
off the coast of Sierra Leone but was ''in the area and will remain
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The boat normally carries about one dozen Navy SEAL commandos,
Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''(She's) prepared to provide any support or help that she's
called upon to provide,'' he said. ''Right now she's just there as
a precautionary measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the United States is not considering sending any
combat troops to Sierra Leone, but he confirmed news reports that
the Clinton administration has told the United Nations it is
willing to provide air transportation for a battalion of 700 to 800
peacekeepers from Bangladesh to join the embattled U.N. mission in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the United States might also help transport
additional peacekeepers from Jordan and India. He said it was not
yet clear what other kinds of military assistance the United States
might provide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Specifically, the types of help we will provide remain to be
determined because it depends on what the UN and the international
community, including the regional countries in West Africa, decide
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''So we are observing, assessing and listening, and then once
decisions are made about what's going to be done, we'll decide what
help we can provide,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1836 </TRAILER>
