<DOCNO> APW20000509.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lost tax returns boost surplus by at least $100 million  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- State budget officials on Tuesday
reported receiving thousands of income tax returns, which had been
stuck in the mail, boosting the state's surplus by at least $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   The debate already has begun over what to do with the extra
money.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers want to stick to the budget agreement,
which earmarked any additional surplus for school technology and
debt reduction. Some Democrats, though, say now is the chance to
reinstate a tuition freeze at public state colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats plan to raise the issue when the Legislature
reconvenes next month for a special session, needed to pass
technical bills to implement the budget. A date for that session
has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a golden opportunity for the Legislature to revisit one
important priority we didn't get to in the session,'' Democratic
Sens. Kevin Sullivan, Jose Crisco, Don Williams and Tom Gaffey said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers were finalizing the $12.3 billion budget in the
waning days of the session that ended May 3, they appropriated a
projected surplus of about $250 million. But lawmakers believed
that surplus could rise to $300 million as more money trickled in.
</P>
<P>
   With the late tax returns, the surplus is now expected to be
$325 million to $380 million, said state budget director Marc Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said that, as of Friday, 37,000 tax returns that were
presumably mailed by the April 18 deadline had been delivered late
to the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had obvious conversations with the Postal Service about
the delay,'' he said. Officials have not come to a conclusion, he
said, raising questions from Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's astounding that $140 million in additional revenue could
be misplaced in the mail,'' the senators said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Genuario, R-Norwalk, a ranking member of the
Appropriations Committee, called the inference ''political
nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   The state should be able to calculate the surplus definitely in
a week to 10 days, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the budget that was adopted, the first $10 million over
and above the $250 million surplus already spent would go toward
wiring classrooms for the Internet. Any extra would be used to
avoid issuing debt for school construction.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats said they support those uses for the surplus,
but feel extending the tuition freeze another year would cost just
a fraction -- $7.5 million, according to the nonpartisan Office of
Fiscal Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition has been frozen at the schools since 1998, but that
policy will end in June.
</P>
<P>
   The four senators also are calling for a portion of the
additional surplus to be shared with cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers called any plans to create new spending
programs irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure there are legislators who, within a couple of hours,
had a hundred ways to spend it,'' Genuario said. ''It seems to me
that virtually every legislator has acknowledged at one time or
another that one of state's fiscal problems is it has one of
highest debts per capita in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Bob Ward said increasing a one-time grant
to cities and towns may not be the best way to help them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best plan for new money,'' said Ward, R-Northford, ''is to
avoid debt and reduce the temptation to spend it as soon as it's
found.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-09-00 1840 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
