<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA: No Evidence Drug Led To Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- There is no evidence that substandard imports
of a well-known antibiotic led to 17 deaths, Food and Drug
Administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., sent a blistering letter to FDA
Commissioner Jane Henney on Monday contending her agency did not
take aggressive enough steps to stop imports of substandard
gentamicin from China.
</P>
<P>
   The letter arises from an investigation by Bliley's House
Commerce Committee of the importation of raw pharmaceutical
ingredients. Many active ingredients for prescription medicines are
sold in bulk form by overseas companies to U.S. manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is substantial evidence of imported counterfeit or
substandard bulk drugs silently infiltrating the U.S. health
delivery system, and harming the American people,'' Bliley wrote.
His example: gentamicin, an antibiotic used most often to treat
life threatening heart infections and blood poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the FDA halted bulk gentamicin imports by a Chinese
company, Long March Pharmaceutical, citing contamination with a
substance called endotoxin that caused 130 cases of fever, chills
and low blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But Bliley charged that tainted gentamicin may still be entering
the country. He said FDA documents list 17 deaths among gentamicin
patients between May 1, 1999, and Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths appear related to the tainted imports, and there is no
evidence that tainted gentamicin is still entering the country, FDA
drug chief Dr. Janet Woodcock responded Tuesday. ''We believe the
current supplies of gentamicin are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA collects reports of deaths and then must determine if
medications or the patient's original illness are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 17 deaths cited, five were duplicate reports and seven
discussed non-Americans using gentamicin sold abroad, FDA officials
said. Of the remaining five U.S. deaths, one was a premature infant
with a deadly lung infection and the other four people suffered
kidney problems, a well-known gentamicin side effect, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent pharmaceutical industry globalization ''has upped the
ante for us'' in ensuring drug safety, Woodcock acknowledged. But,
''we have programs in place to try and screen out and prosecute
people who would import inappropriate drugs into the U.S.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1848 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000509.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Ukrainian Leader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton met with Ukrainian Prime
Minister Viktor Yushchenko on Tuesday, urging him to continue
market and democratic reforms that the eastern European nation
began after the breakup of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Yushchenko met with Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger during a four-day visit to Washington
to drum up support for his government as it juggles an unsteady
economy and heavy debt. Yushchenko also outlined Clinton's trip
next month to the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president praised Yushchenko for Ukraine's progress,''
said Mike Hammer, a national security spokesman at the White House.
''He encouraged Yushchenko to continue on this path and he
encouraged their efforts to integrate Ukraine more fully into the
rest of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Yushchenko met with World Bank President James
Wolfensohn, who said that support for Ukraine hinges on tangible
progress on reform. Wolfensohn noted that the World Bank already is
working with Yushchenko's administration on a so-called Country
Assistance Strategy that will underpin future bank assistance and
lending to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expressed a strong desire on our part to assist the
government in its efforts to plan and implement its proposed
economic and social program, but I also stressed that, in
determining continued World Bank support, much will depend on
results in implementing the program,'' Wolfensohn said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's sister institution, the International Monetary Fund,
granted Ukraine a $2.21 billion loan in September 1998 and boosted
that amount to $2.6 billion in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The money was offered as temporary support for the government
during a period of dwindling export income, stemming from the
Russian financial crisis and also the war in Kosovo, which cut
important trade routes in the region.
</P>
<P>
   However, the IMF froze loan installments to Ukraine in September
last year, citing concerns about the pace of economic and fiscal
reform. Relations between Kiev and its international lenders
worsened earlier this year when it was revealed the Ukrainian
central bank had misled the IMF over the size of its foreign
exchange reserves between 1996-1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Ukrainian authorities released a report by
auditors PricewaterhouseCoopers into the central bank's activities
during this period, showing that reserves were overstated but that
there no signs of illegal use of the funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
