<HEADLINE> AG creates inspector general to monitor government activities  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The attorney general Tuesday created a new
state position -- inspector general -- to monitor government
practices and prevent corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer named Edward Neafsey, who is
currently the insurance fraud prosecutor, to the post.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general will be able to make recommendations on
management practices and examine procedures for inefficiencies. He
also will investigate tips and will likely oversee complex state
issues like allegations of racial profiling by the State Police,
Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   And, if he can't prevent misdeeds, he'll have the power to
prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
   Neafsey will supervise a staff of 30 attorneys, investigators,
accountants and management specialists. The office will have the
power to subpoena witnesses and file civil lawsuits, as well as
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer decided to create this post after his office was called
to investigate the racial profiling charges and dealings that led
to a faulty new auto emissions inspection service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general is especially needed now, as the state
considers ''significant expenditures'' for school construction and
open space, Farmer said. Such large-scale public spending has
potential for not only graft, but mismanagement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''History is history. There have been problems in the past and
we would like to think that the presence of a watchdog would
prevent some of that,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   If the state proceeds with the multibillion dollar school
construction plan, the inspector general would examine contracts
and local bidding ''to make sure cronyism does not enter into the
equation,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just to make sure whatever is being done is being done in the
right way,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman called the new office a ''win-win for New
Jersey taxpayers'' and pointed to the ''power to investigate
allegations of fraud, waste, abuse and misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It will also be able to detect errors and irregularities in
state programs, apply preventative maintenance and fix things
before they are broken,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, such duties were handled ''on an ad hoc basis,''
Farmer said. Racial profiling was reviewed by an internal team in
his office. To examine how a California company, Parsons
Infrastructure, wound up the lone bidder on the problem-plagued
auto emissions program, Farmer appointed a former state Supreme
Court justice. Currently, the State Commission of Investigation
probes organized crime and official corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Early in her first term, Whitman abolished the Office of the
Public Advocate, a state financed agency that often tackled
government on behalf of private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The highest ranking Democrat in the state Senate said that does
not lend credibility to this newest reform agency, which Sen.
Richard J. Codey, D-Essex, called the ''inspector corporal.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the State Commission of Investigation, the inspector
general would report to the attorney general, Codey said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason the SCI is effective is because it has the autonomy
to investigator outside the control of the politicians,'' Codey
said. ''It is ludicrous to suggest the fixed term of the attorney
general makes the office nonpolitical.''
</P>
<P>
   Neafsey was the first person to act as the state's insurance
fraud prosecutor, a post created in 1998. Before that he was chief
of the Environmental Crimes Bureau in the Division of Criminal
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's shown the ability to get something up and running on a
short-time basis,'' Farmer said. ''All in all he's the perfect guy
for the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
