<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Finally Rebound  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices broke their six session losing
streak, as investors swooped in to buy at depressed prices and
higher yields amid a down day in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 10-year Treasury note fell \ point,
or $2.50 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell to 6.52 percent from 6.56 percent late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond fell 15/32 point to yield 6.21
percent, down from 6.24 percent late Monday, according to Bridge
Telerate.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in bonds was considered by many a technical bounce as
traders looked to take advantage of attractive yield. But many
expect downward pressure on bonds to continue due to concerns the
Federal Reserve will enact several more interest rate hikes this
year to cool down the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates and higher inflation both hurt investments
with fixed returns, such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also looked more enticing Tuesday amid falling stocks
prices. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 66.88 to 10,536.75 on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Monday, short-term Treasury securities rose
1/32 point to 1/16 point, while intermediate maturities were
between unchanged at up \ point.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 6.13 percent as the
discount fell 0.06 percentage point from Monday's Treasury auction
to 5.96 percent. Six-month yields were 6.43 percent, as the
discount was unchanged at 6.15 percent from Monday's auction.
One-year yields were 6.30 percent as the discount fell by 0.01
percentage point from Monday to 5.00 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, fell to 5.81 percent from 6.00 percent late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell [ to 92 7/16. The average yield to
maturity rose to 6.19 percent from 6.18 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
