<HEADLINE> Senate Rejects Education Program  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate rejected a compromise offered by
moderate Democrats to consolidate more than 40 federal education
programs and target money to poor students, but unanimously
approved a Republican plan to protect teachers who discipline
students from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
	   The future of the entire education bill -- governing about $20
billion in federal aid to schools -- was left uncertain as the
Senate then turned its attention to other legislation governing
trade with Africa and spending on military construction. It may be
a week before the Senate comes back to the education plan -- and the
gun-control proposals it could still draw.
</P>
<P>
	   ''There's been good debate; it's my intent to come back to
elementary and secondary education,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said Tuesday after postponing further votes on the
bill. Education's popularity in voter polls has turned the normally
bipartisan renewal of the 35-year-old Great Society law into an
election-year public relations war between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Education has been a victim of its own success,'' said Joel
Packer, a lobbyist for the National Education Association. He said
if lawmakers can't agree on education policy bill before the end of
this session, they may use upcoming spending bills to push their
agendas and keep school programs funded.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, the Senate overwhelmingly rejected, 84-13, a
long-standing attempt by Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., and eight
other moderate Democrats, to bridge the gulf between Republicans
seeking increased local control of education dollars and fellow
Democrats pushing specific federal programs. In six days, senators
approved just two changes to the version offered by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton has promised to veto the GOP's first shot at
rewriting the law, angered mostly over Republican attempts to
dilute his teacher-hiring plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Lieberman, who spent more than a year promoting his ''third
way'' plan, said Tuesday his colleagues had the chance to
accomplish more than lengthy arguments about who controls spending.
</P>
<P>
	   ''It may be stimulating,'' Lieberman said. ''It may be
fascinating. It may even be educational. But if it's only a debate
without a result, it does nothing really for the children of our
country.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Evan Bayh, D-Ind., another backer, said the plan increased
federal education spending and targeted most of those new dollars
to the poorest school districts.
</P>
<P>
	   But in the end, the plan -- waved under the flag of the moderate
Democratic Leadership Council founded by Clinton -- was an
alternative few senators wanted.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass., said the plan cut into priorities set
by the president and reduced funds for poor students in 30 states.
Just 13 of 45 Democrats voted for the Lieberman bill.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no Republican support for it, not even from moderates
who have crossed party lines to vote with Democrats on other social
issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ''This proposal pits poor children of one school against poor
children in another,'' said Sen. James Jeffords, D-Vt., chairman of
the Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   GOP conservatives ultimately decided they could not back away
from plans to let poor children use federal funds for vouchers and
other options if their schools are failing to help them.
</P>
<P>
	   The vote on teacher liability protections, backed by Lott and
Rep. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., was 97-0. Sponsors said it would help
teachers regain control of classrooms routinely disrupted by
chronic misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
   The education bill is S.2.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The bill can be found at:
http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)labor
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
