<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Threatened by casino road deal, A.C. laundry gets a reprieve  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- In casino-era Atlantic City,
businesses who do battle with the gambling industry face long odds.
It is, after all, a casino town.
</P>
<P>
   But everything is coming up aces for Atlantic City Linen Supply
Inc., a commercial laundry that stood in the way of a road-widening
project aimed at improving access to Boardwalk casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Resorts Atlantic City agreed to donate land, Tropicana Casino
and Resort provided a $2.5 million loan and the state Casino
Reinvestment Development Authority pitched in with money for new
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The $7.5 million deal will allow the company, which had eyed
locations in Pleasantville and Vineland, to build a new plant that
remains within walking distance from home for most of the 300
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very happy ending: We stay in Atlantic City, and our
employees keep their jobs,'' said David Goldberg, co-owner.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1986 in a sprawling 19th century building at
North Carolina and Adriatic avenues, Atlantic City Linen stood in
the way when the Casino Reinvestment Development Authority and the
state Department of Transportation came up with a plan to widen
North Carolina Avenue, a key access road for incoming casino
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The $15 million road project, covering about a half-mile, would
force the re-location of Atlantic City Linen. With relocation help,
the business could do just as well elsewhere, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A job's a job, no matter where it's located,'' said James
Kennedy, executive director of the Casino Reinvestment Development
Authority. ''Early on, we argued it should be in another
municipality. But the mayor and the City Council president felt
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City Linen, it turns out, is more than a local
business. It is the city's largest non-casino private sector
employer, and 80 percent of its employees live in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some of the employees are people who might be
unable to find work in the casinos because of language barriers,
criminal backgrounds or other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we moved, they wouldn't be able to come with us,'' said
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Atlantic City Linen serves the casinos, cleaning
and pressing 100,000 pounds of table linens, serving jackets, chef
whites and other items a day.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement between the Casino Reinvestment Development
Authority, Resorts and Tropicana, Atlantic City Linen got a 20-year
lease on a Delaware Avenue parcel that is owned by Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Construction will begin in two weeks on a new 63,000 square-foot
building. Goldberg hopes to open the new building by next February.
Then the road-widening project will start.
</P>
<P>
   ''This place is like a family,'' said Laurie Ruiz, 33, a veteran
employee. ''I'd have hated to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
