<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Seeks Peace in Horn of Africa  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) -- Hinting at a possible breakthrough, a
U.N. delegation led by U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke shuttled
between the capitals of Eritrea and Ethiopia on Tuesday in an
attempt to avert a new round of fighting between the two Horn of
Africa neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation held talks with government officials in the
Eritrean capital Asmara early Tuesday then flew to the Ethiopian
capital later in the day to confer with Ethiopian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the issues are resolved,'' Holbrooke said after the
talks in Asmara, adding that a few technical differences remain
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year border conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia
already has cost the lives of thousands of soldiers and civilians
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   After indirect talks between the two sides ended bitterly last
week in the Algeria, Ethiopian officials warned ominously of a
return to war, sparking the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the delegation's apparent progress on Tuesday -- one day
after three hours of inconclusive talks in with Ethiopian Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi -- Holbrooke remained cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ''We sit on the edge of a vast and useless war,'' said
Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member delegation was to return to Asmara early
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries agree on a framework peace accord drafted by the
Organization of African Unity, but they disagree on how to
implement it. Eritrea wants a cease-fire before working out the
details. Ethiopia says it will not agree to a cease-fire until
everything else has been agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the United States was drafting a Security Council
resolution urging both sides to abide by the OAU framework
agreement, U.S. officials said. The resolution is expected to be
adopted after the council delegation wraps up its talks in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin accused
Eritrea of derailing the talks in Algiers. He said Eritrea had
demanded a cease-fire before it would move on to other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi told
foreign diplomats in a private briefing that his country's options
were shrinking quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who say force is not an option should show the way to
peace,'' a diplomat present at the briefing quoted the prime
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethiopian statements -- as well as reports of Ethiopian troop
reinforcements moving toward the border -- spurred an emergency
session of the U.N. Security Council on Sunday night in New York
and the Holbrooke-led delegation's visit to the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of renewed hostilities in the Horn comes at a
time when a major drought in the region threatens an estimated 7.7
million people with severe food shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 1919 </TRAILER>
