<HEADLINE> Clinton Presents Football Trophy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton presented the U.S. Air Force
Academy with the commander in chief trophy on Tuesday, praising its
football team for winning the shiny silver award nine of the past
11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The trophy, established in 1972, is awarded to the military
service academy with the best record in the annual ''round-robin''
football competition. The academy in Colorado Springs, Colo., has
won 28 games during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I try to be completely neutral in these things, but the Army
really was hurt that you beat them this year -- with a better ground
game,'' Clinton joked.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six members of the Falcons football team, dressed in blue
uniforms, were recognized during the ceremony in the Rose Garden of
the White House. Members of the team gave the president a blue team
hat and football jersey emblazoned with his name and the number
one.
</P>
</TEXT>
