<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charges Dismissed Against Hughes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOME, Australia (AP) -- Dangerous driving charges against art
critic and author Robert Hughes were dismissed by a magistrate
Tuesday, ending a year-long legal ordeal that followed a car crash
that almost killed him.
</P>
<P>
   After a two day trial in the town of Broome, Magistrate Antoine
Bloemen said prosecutors had failed to prove beyond reasonable
doubt that Hughes had caused the crash, which left him in a coma
for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the occupants of the other car sustained serious injuries
while the third suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back tears, Hughes whispered ''thank you'' and ''thank
God'' as Bloemen read out his decision to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, 61, had been charged with dangerous driving causing
grievous bodily harm in the accident that occurred on a deserted
stretch of highway near Broome on May 28 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian-born Hughes, an art critic at Time Magazine and
author of the book ''The Fatal Shore,'' was in the state of Western
Australia filming a television series for the British Broadcasting
Corp. at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Lloyd Rayney alleged Hughes had caused the crash by
driving on the wrong side of the road, plowing head-on into the
oncoming car after ignoring warning signs such as flashing
headlights and horn honks.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the court, Hughes said he was relieved the case was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am extremely glad that justice was done -- and it was done --
and seen to be done,'' Hughes told journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very wise and very decent decision by the magistrate,
obviously, how could I find any fault with it whatsoever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
