<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High ozone mixes with pollen, packing hospital ERs  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gasp! The rare combination of heavy spring
pollen, polluted air and a summer-like heat wave sent dozens of
people with respiratory problems to New Jersey hospitals Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency department workers and ambulance staff, particularly
in northeastern and southwestern New Jersey, where air quality
usually is worst, were swamped by patients with asthma attacks,
wheezing, chest pains and heart troubles exacerbated by hot, smoggy
air.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is spring pollen season and we're having inordinately hot
weather for this time of year. I don't recall the two ever being so
(bad) together,'' said Dr. Bernard Goldstein, director of the
Environmental and Occupational Health Sciences Institute in
Piscataway.
</P>
<P>
   One unidentified man, found unconscious from heat stroke on a
Newark street Monday afternoon, remained hospitalized in critical
condition Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   At Cooper Hospital/University Medical Center in Camden, 20
patients, most with weather-related problems, walked into the
emergency department in one five-minute stretch at midday Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We truly have just been inundated today. It started late
yesterday afternoon and has progressively gotten worse,'' said
Karen Slutsky, clinical manager of Cooper's emergency department.
''I can't even quantify it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we're trying to figure out where we're going to find beds
for all the people here,'' she added, because the hospital is full.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures hit about 90 degrees across most of New Jersey
again Tuesday. Air quality plummeted as sunlight combined with heat
and pollutants from autos, factories and power plants to produce
dangerous levels of ozone. At ground level, ozone is a pungent gas
that inflames lungs and breathing passages and sets patients up for
respiratory infections.
</P>
<P>
   ''Temperature, pollution and pollen: When you mix the three
together, you set up a chain reaction in the lungs'' that can be
very dangerous for anyone with allergies or lung disease, said Dr.
Leonard Bielory, director of the Asthma &AMP; Allergy Research Center
at the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey in
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the next 24 to 36 hours, people are just going to get
sicker,'' Bielory predicted.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, according to the Department of Environmental
Protection's forecast, air quality on Wednesday again will be
''unhealthy for sensitive groups:'' the elderly, children and
anyone with respiratory or heart disease. The department on Tuesday
issued air quality warnings for unhealthy levels of ozone and soot,
or particulate matter, in Bergen, Passaic, Essex, Hudson, Union,
Camden and Gloucester counties.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tree pollen counts remain extremely high -- about
1,800 pollen grains per cubic meter Monday and about 1,200 Tuesday
in Newark. Counts of 200-500 are considered high.
</P>
<P>
   At University Hospital in Newark, spokesman Rogers Ramsey said
the emergency department treated 20 people Monday and another seven
Tuesday for wheezing, asthma attacks and other respiratory
problems.
</P>
<P>
   One, an unidentified man found unconscious and with an elevated
body temperature, was being treated for heatstroke in the intensive
care unit. The 40-ish black male had not regained consciousness by
Tuesday evening. Ramsey said the man was found at 5th and Orange
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Even in areas where air quality was moderate, or just below
unhealthy, some hospitals felt the weather's effects. At Monmouth
Medical Center in Long Branch, the emergency department has been
extremely busy since Sunday with lung and cardiac patients, said
hospital spokeswoman Kathy Horan.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials were urging people to try staying in air
conditioning, limit exercise and drink extra water to avoid
becoming dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein added that people with respiratory problems should do
outdoor activities before 10 a.m., when ozone begins building up,
or after it dissipates in the late evening.
</P>
<P>
   While the heat wave is expected to break Wednesday night, the
pollen onslaught won't.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Jinnoti, a professor of biomedical engineering at Robert
Wood Johnson Medical School in New Brunswick, predicted ''a very
bad year'' for pollen because the mild winter and early spring
rains primed plants for growth spurts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have an extremely high ragweed season,'' he
added, unless a dry spell hits in June and July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
