<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.America Backs Off Single Currency  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ASTOR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- South America's troubled trading
bloc backed away Tuesday from adopting a single currency, saying
the region first had to more closely align its economies.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil and Argentina, the largest participants in the Mercosur
pact that also includes Paraguay and Uruguay, announced a first
step toward bringing their economies in line as a possible
preparation for a unified currency. The two nations said they would
standardize their ways of measuring finances and set common fiscal
targets by March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The World Economic Forum's Mercosur Summit opened Sunday with a
great deal of expectation after Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso called for re-launching the troubled trade bloc
and for a single currency in the ''medium term.''
</P>
<P>
   But two days later, Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro Malan said
the single currency is ''putting the cart before the bull.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The time frame will be as long as it takes. Our style is not
to hurry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fiscal measures are intended to help revive Mercosur, which
was hurt by Brazil's Jan. 1999 currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Following the devaluation, trade within the bloc dropped by 20
percent, which was especially hard on Argentina where 30 percent of
exports go to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The devaluation made products from Argentina, where the currency
is pegged to the U.S. dollar, almost twice as expensive in Brazil,
disturbing the trade balance and causing Argentina at one point to
slap unilateral trade barriers on shoes and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   The move prompted many here and in Argentina to declare Mercosur
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Today, anti-Brazilian sentiment in Argentina runs high as dozens
of companies move operations to Brazil, where labor costs are
cheaper. And many economists believe Mercosur is inoperable as long
as Argentina holds on to its dollar peg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
