<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florio backs plan to create New Jersey's first National Forest  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- U.S. Senate candidate Jim Florio Tuesday
promised to sponsor a wholesale freeze on development in
northwestern New Jersey to create the state's first National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement, Florio continued to maximize his ties to
the Sierra Club. He joined club officials, who did most of the
explaining about the plan to use federal funds to buy some 300,000
acres in New Jersey and New York over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club has endorsed Florio in his Democratic primary
contest with Jon Corzine. The other major environmental group in
New Jersey that makes endorsements, the New Jersey Environmental
Federation, may make an announcement by week's end, according to
director David Pringle.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine spokesman Steve Goldstein said his candidate has
endorsed any steps necessary to preserve land in the so-called
''Highlands'' region, and has been more aggressive on the matter
than Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups are among the most active nonprofit
agencies at work at the Statehouse and on the New Jersey policy
scene, yet they shrink from the field during election campaign
season.
</P>
<P>
   Clean Ocean Action, the New Jersey Conservation Foundation and
the New Jersey Public Interest Research Group, all with thousands
of dues-paying members, shy away from campaign endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Audubon is a nonprofit group and so cannot endorse
candidates, said Bill Neil, the group's director of conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America local representing state
employees at the Department of Environmental Protection has
endorsed Corzine. However, Local 1034 political director Jeff Scott
said the endorsement was based more on union and state worker
issues than on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said the rarity of ''green endorsements'' gives the
Sierra Club nod extra weight among voters who are primarily
concerned about such issues.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Florio is throwing his weight behind one of the
Sierra Club's national priorities, the formation of the first
National Forest that would encroach on the populous northeastern
corridor from Washington, D.C., to Boston. Currently there are no
federal forest lands in the 450 miles between Green Mountain
National Forest in Vermont and George Washington National Forest in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   As a congressman, Florio was central in the establishment of the
Pinelands National Reserve covering a million acres in southern New
Jersey, a persistent controversy because it imposed stringent land
regulation without purchasing the forests and swamps it intended to
save.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday this approach would not work in northern New
Jersey, adding that political times are more opportune to propose
some $250 million in outright federal spending over 10 years to buy
undeveloped land.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said, ''It is a different time and a different era, and
the fact is there is just too much private land here'' when
compared with the Pine Barrens tracts he worked to save through
regulation 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Tittel, director of the New Jersey chapter of the Sierra
Club, said the targeted Highlands region covers about a million
acres ranging from Phillipsburg on the Delaware River north through
forest valleys east of the Kittatinny Ridge into New York State and
east to West Point on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   A third of that land is already preserved, the single largest
piece being in the Harriman-Bear Mountain State Park in New York.
The National Forest plan would preserve, more or less intact, a
patch of forest to link Harriman with New Jersey's Delaware Water
Gap National Recreation area, a zone Tittel called essential to
protect water reservoirs supplying 4.5 million New Jersey
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McGrady, national chairman of the Sierra Club, attended
the news conference here to say the National Forest has been a top
national priority for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said Florio's support for the National Forest proposal
is late and an act of political convenience, claiming Corzine had
endorsed it more heartily from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jon was a forerunner in this position, and it is nice to see
Jim is a Jimmy-Come-Lately on this,'' Goldstein said. ''We are
grateful the Sierra Club has knocked some sense into him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
