<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill Targets Sex Trade  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House passed legislation Tuesday to help
thousands of foreign women and children forced into the sex trade
in the United States and crack down on their victimizers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fifty-thousand innocent women and young children are forced,
coerced, or fraudulently thrust into the international sex trade
industry with no way out,'' said Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J.,
the chief sponsor. ''This legislation will put these offenders
behind bars while protecting the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which passed by voice vote, would double to 20
years the maximum penalty for enticing and selling people into
involuntary servitude, and add the possibility of life imprisonment
when violations result in death or involve kidnapping or sexual
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It makes trafficking victims eligible for the federal Witness
Protection Plan and creates a new visa status for victims who
cooperate with law enforcement. Those entering this program, which
would be capped at 5,000 people a year, would be able to apply for
permanent residence after three years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also directs the State Department in its annual country
reports on human rights to include information on the levels to
which countries combat or tolerate human trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The president would have the authority, beginning in 2002, to
withhold nonhumanitarian aid to countries that fail to meet minimum
standards in eliminating the sex trade. The administration opposes
the bill based on this provision, but Smith stressed that the
president would also have the discretion to waive this authority.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 50,000 to 100,000 women and children brought into
this country every year for sexual exploitation are a small part of
the 2 million victims of the international sex industry. Smith said
an estimated 250,000 women and children from Russia, the newly
independent states and Eastern Europe are trafficked into Western
Europe, the Middle East, Japan, Canada and the United States each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he and Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., a co-sponsor,
recently talked to several women who had been held as ''virtual
slaves'' in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is so frustrating,'' Gejdenson said, ''is that often the
laws we have punish only the victims.'' He said the women often end
up getting arrested or deported while those who force them into the
sex industry go free.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation is under consideration in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 3244.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Rep. Smith's Web site:
http://www.house.gov/chrissmith/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
