<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher of Year Named  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Marilyn Jachetti Whirry started teaching
English in a California classroom 35 years ago, she tossed the
desks into the hallway and brought in beanbag chairs. The maverick
high school teacher replaced lectures with group discussions and
mixed classics with paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The school's principal, and even some of Whirry's colleagues,
didn't always support such unorthodox attempts to be a better
teacher: ''They just didn't like kids bothering them with other
questions. I was sort of alone for the first couple of years.
Still, I started causing some waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Whirry, 65, was named Tuesday the 2000 National Teacher of the
Year -- an honor she won for educating pupils at Mira Costa High
School in Manhattan Beach, Calif., and helping train their teachers
as well. With her title, she delivers a simple message for how the
public should treat teachers: more training, more pay, more
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think we come home at 3 and kick our shoes off,'' said
Whirry, who was California's teacher of the year for 1999. ''I
begin teaching at 7 in the morning before most people are up.''
</P>
<P>
   Her evenings and weekends are spent reading essays and planning
lessons; her summers, traveling the country as a consultant
training other teachers to help students read and write better.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of us have master's and Ph.D.s,'' Whirry said in an
interview. ''We could be out somewhere else, but we think education
is the most important thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what people have to understand,'' she said. So far, she
said, ''We show respect in our society by how much people earn.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the major teachers unions, which have opposed merit-pay
plans, Whirry said she could support some proposals that would give
successful teachers an edge in salary scales. She is a union
member, but Whirry said such plans don't necessarily have to pit
teachers against one another.
</P>
<P>
   ''The merit pay issue is workable if it's done fairly,'' she
said. ''But many teachers are afraid of it. Sometimes I think
teachers are too afraid of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers have to learn that it's OK to be out of the classroom
for professional development, said Whirry, who has attended and led
teacher training workshops over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If one missed day leads a teacher to grow and learn and know
more, it's wonderful for the kids,'' she said. ''The message has to
be sent out loudly and clearly that teachers need staff
development.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We would be afraid to go to a doctor who hadn't kept up with
changes in his profession,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, teachers have increasingly vented their
frustration with conditions of the profession. Teachers earn less
than other professionals. The stress of standardized tests and
zero-tolerance discipline policies also take their toll, even on
top teachers like Whirry.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of past national and state teachers of the year, released
Tuesday, suggests even teachers who are considered the best clamor
for more pay, support from parents and administrators and respect
for the jobs they do. The first-ever poll of top teachers has a
margin of error of plus or minus 2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Educators responding to the poll said teachers are bothered most
by excessive paperwork, nonteaching responsibilities, burned-out
colleagues and low staff morale. Fewer faulted large class sizes or
the learning abilities of today's students.
</P>
<P>
   Whirry, who teaches advanced 12th-grade college-preparatory
classes, said teachers need to take more charge of their own fate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's bad public relations,'' she said. ''We don't tell people
all the things that we do.''
</P>
<P>
   She will spend a year on promotional tours as teacher of the
year, being launched with a ceremony Thursday at the White House.
The Teacher of the Year award is sponsored by the Council of Chief
State School Officers and Scholastic Inc., the educational
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Whirry says she is fortunate that Mira Costa, where she has
spent most of her career, is in a community that supports teachers.
Manhattan Beach is an upper-middle-class suburb; few of the 2,100
students at the high school get free or reduced lunch -- the most
common measure of student poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But, Whirry said, her travels have taught her that any
community, with the right amount of encouragement, can help its
schools and teachers. She's invited parents in to observe her
classes and offered them summer courses on reading strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes a difference when parents know they are wanted and
needed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Council of Chief State School Officers:
http://www.ccsso.org/ntoy.html
</P>
</TEXT>
