<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drifter Executed in Texas  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GRACZYK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A drifter from Oklahoma was executed
Tuesday night for beating, raping and killing a woman 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   William Kitchens, 37, admitted strangling 25-year-old Patricia
Webb of Abilene and shooting her through the eye. After a federal
appeals court refused to overturn his conviction and sentence last
September, he asked that no additional appeals be filed for him.
</P>
<P>
   Just before his lethal injection, Kitchens apologized to his
victim's family and asked God to forgive him ''for the despicable
things I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens, an eighth-grade dropout who worked in construction and
as a painter, met the victim at a nightclub where she was attending
an office party. When the group left, Webb offered to take Kitchens
to his motel so he wouldn't have to pay for a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens admitted in a recent interview that Webb, who was
married to a firefighter, had ''made it clear she was not going to
fool around.'' But he said he wanted to scare her, ''to let her
know she shouldn't just go with someone to a motel room.''
</P>
<P>
   He raped and killed her and drove off in her car. He was
arrested at his parents' home and gave officers directions to a
wooded site where they found Webb's body.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens was the 14th inmate executed in Texas this year.
Another execution is set for Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 2003 </TRAILER>
