<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citadel To Buy 11 Radio Stations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Citadel Communications Corp. announced Tuesday
that its subsidiary has agreed to buy 11 southern radio stations
and take over operations at another in a $300 million cash deal.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas-based Citadel Broadcasting Company will buy the 11
stations from Dick Broadcasting Co. It also will take over a
long-term local marketing agreement formerly maintained by Dick
Broadcasting for another station, in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Citadel, one of the nation's fastest-growing radio companies,
will own more than 200 radio stations in 45 markets after the deal
is completed, which is expected to be this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 stations are in Nashville, Tenn., Birmingham, Ala., and
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fit is perfect for us,'' said Citadel Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Larry Wilson. ''They are in great growth markets
that dramatically enhance our southeastern presence, and
exceptional management is in place running the properties.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Dick, president and CEO of Dick Broadcasting, said that
after 47 years he felt it was time for the company to sell.
</P>
</TEXT>
