<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon: Militia Chief Must Give Up  </HEADLINE>
By HUSSEIN DAKROUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- The commander of Israeli-allied
militiamen in southern Lebanon must surrender and stand trial for
treason before demanding amnesty for his men, the prime minister
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is strange that Antoine Lahd is asking the president for a
general amnesty (for his militiamen) while he is still carrying out
attacks alongside the enemy of his country, against civilians of
his country, and sometimes does not spare the army of his
country,'' Prime Minister Salim Hoss said in a statement issued by
his office.
</P>
<P>
   Hoss' statement came a day after Lahd, commander of the South
Lebanon Army militia, or SLA, appealed to President Emile Lahoud to
grant his followers a general amnesty similar to a 1991 pardon of
militiamen across Lebanon for most crimes committed during the
devastating 1975-90 civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Israel plans to withdraw from an enclave it occupies in south
Lebanon by July 7, leaving the fate of Lahd's militia, which is
financed, armed and trained by the Jewish state, uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Prime Minister Ehud Barak expressed support for
Lahd's demands in an interview with Israel Radio on Tuesday. The
aspiration of SLA fighters for a collective and personal amnesty
must be met, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We of course feel responsible to see that the issue of the SLA
is resolved in a way that befits their deep connection with the
state of Israel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal Monday, Lahd maintained that he alone bore
responsibility for the actions of his 2,500 fighters, but he did
not indicate whether he would be willing to stand trial after the
Israeli pullout. Lahd, a retired Lebanese army general, was
sentenced to death in absentia in 1996 after being found guilty of
treason by a Beirut military court.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Lahd) must firstly turn himself over to the Lebanese
judiciary before asking for anything,'' said Hoss. ''He knows that
if he does so, he will be treated by the judiciary with justice,
transparency and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon, which is technically at war with Israel, prohibits
contacts or dealings with the Jewish state. Collaboration with
Israel is punishable by imprisonment in most cases. Treason is
punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the Iranian-backed guerrilla group leading the
campaign to oust Israeli troops and the SLA from south Lebanon, has
said if the SLA remained in control of the border area after the
withdrawal, attacks would continue.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, a U.N. special envoy discussed Israel's planned
withdrawal with the Arab League's secretary general on Tuesday. The
envoy, Terje Roed-Larsen, said the United Nations is ready to
deploy peacekeepers in the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdel Meguid said he had
told the envoy that the Israeli withdrawal should be ''complete,
unconditional and swift.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 2111 </TRAILER>
