<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Methodists Review Abortion Policy  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD N. OSTLING, AP Religion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- A panel of the United Methodist Church, the
nation's largest religious body that favors abortion rights, voted
Tuesday to fight a late-term procedure opponents call
''partial-birth'' abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now moves to the full conference for a vote, expected
by the end of the week. Though the full conference could decide
otherwise, it usually passes committee recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was approved by the committee 77-32. It opposes the
late-term procedure except when the life of the mother is in danger
and no other procedure is available, or in cases of severe fetal
abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   During emotional debate before a packed gallery, the Rev.
Gregory McGarvey of Greenfield, Ind., said: ''I stand to use my
voice for those who have no voice. We offer them no voice when we
use this procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. J. Philip Wogman of Washington, Hillary Clinton's
pastor, said ''my concern is both with the health and well-being of
the mother and the medical profession if we put this into law
without qualification. The effect can be very chilling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Methodists' General Conference meets every four years to set
policy for the country's second-largest Protestant denomination,
with 8.4 million U.S. members and 1.2 million adherents overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The conference's hottest issue, homosexuality, reaches the floor
Thursday. The same panel that dealt with abortion will be reporting
out bills to maintain current opposition to homosexual practice.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian activists plan a protest Wednesday during the
appearance of Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey, spiritual
leader of 70 million Anglicans and Episcopalians worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Methodist traditionalists won significant long-term
leverage in elections to the denomination's supreme court, which is
likely to face important decisions on homosexuality. For instance,
a 1998 ruling by the court gave a ban on same-sex union ceremonies
the force of law and was used to defrock a Nebraska pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in national conservative caucuses won three of five open
seats on the nine-member court, their best showing since the
homosexual issue arose.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Official Methodist news releases:
http://www.umns.umc.org/gc2000news
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
