<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hosts Costa Rica President  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Costa Rican President
Miguel Angel Rodriguez discussed trade, drug smuggling and other
topics Tuesday during the Central American leader's first trip to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said much of the 40-minute session in the Oval Office
concerned legislation moving through Congress that would elevate 48
nations of sub-Sahara Africa to full U.S. trading partners and
expand market access for Caribbean and Central American nations.
</P>
<P>
   The pact has passed in the House and is expected to clear the
Senate this week. Clinton intends to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said a treaty intended to stanch the flow of drugs to
the United States from Central America ''is working very well.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This year we have already stopped 283 ships in the Costa Rican
oceans and we are working in a very broad way with the U.S.
government in prosecuting the illegal drug trafficking,'' Rodriguez
said outside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   White House National Security Council spokesman Mike Hammer said
the two leaders also expressed mutual concern over recent electoral
irregularities in Peru and about the status of democratic reforms
elsewhere in Central and Latin America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
