<DOCNO> APW20000509.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposal Would Limit Forest Roads  </HEADLINE>
By ALISA BLACKWOOD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- The Clinton administration proposed a ban on
building roads in 43 million acres of roadless federal forests
Tuesday -- a decision that prompted complaints from both
environmentalists and timber industry officials.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 300 miles of planned logging roads would no longer
be built under the proposal, said Agriculture Undersecretary Jim
Lyons. That would eliminate at least 53 percent of the timber
cutting that would otherwise occur in the forests, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   But to the disappointment of environmentalists, local federal
forestry officials would get to decide whether to allow logging,
mining or off-road-vehicle riding.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our objective is really to preserve and protect the values
that draw millions of people each year to the forests that they
love,'' Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck said in announcing the
proposal in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ''These pristine areas are some of the last wild places in
America, and I am firmly committed to preserving them for future
generations,'' President Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 million acres of the 192 million acres of federal
forests are considered wild, or undeveloped. The rest of the
acreage is host to a wide range of activities, including logging,
camping, skiing and mining.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say roads cause runoff, disrupt plant and
wildlife and make it easier for logging, mining and
off-road-vehicle riding.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, local forest officials would make the final call
on what activities would be allowed. The plan also would leave it
up to local foresters to decide whether roads should be banned in
smaller forest parcels of 5,000 acres or less.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists said the proposal falls short of the
protection they had hoped for, since banning roads won't in itself
stop logging -- timber companies could use helicopters and cable
systems to log forests.
</P>
<P>
   ''While it prevents future road building, it still allows
logging and continued off-road vehicle use,'' said Rob Smith, a
spokesman for the Sierra Club in Phoenix. ''That can be as
destructive as anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry groups also complained, saying the proposal limits
their access to forests. ''It's another step toward zero harvest,''
said Jim Geisinger, president of the Northwest Forestry Association
in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The forest protection plan requires no congressional action,
relying on regulations to be issued by the Forest Service after an
environmental review and public comments.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal could gain final approval at the end of the year,
just before Clinton leaves office. But environmentalists expect
Republicans in Congress to try to delay the rulemaking until after
Clinton's term. Court challenges from industry groups are likely.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most controversial parts of the plan involves
deferring a decision until 2004 on whether to prohibit roads in 8.7
million acres in the Tongass National Forest in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the Tongass ''just leaves a gaping hole in this
policy,'' said Matt Zencey, campaign manager of the Alaska
Rainforest Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service roadless area Web site:
http://roadless.fs.fed.us/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
