<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA Judge Delays Thai Toddler Return  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT JABLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal judge Tuesday delayed the
deportation of a 2-year old Thai boy believed used in an
immigration smuggling scheme. The move came hours after a Thai
consular official attempted to pick up the boy for a flight home.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian issued a temporary
restraining order on the day Phanupong Khaisri was to be returned
to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, Phanupong's caretakers rebuffed a Thai consular
official at the home where the boy is staying, then sued the U.S.
government to block his removal.
</P>
<P>
   Phanupong has been in the United States since April 11, when he
arrived at Los Angeles International Airport accompanied by a
couple pretending to be his parents. The adults were deported after
it was determined they were not his relatives or guardians.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said they believe the adults were posing as
tourists and using the boy as a prop in a scheme to smuggle a
Chinese woman into the country as an indentured servant.
</P>
<P>
   Peter A. Schey of the Center for Human Rights and Constitutional
Law, which sued, said caregivers were concerned that ''given the
level of corruption'' in Thailand, if the boy is sent back he could
end up in the ''stream of illicit trafficking'' again.
</P>
<P>
   Tevrizian scheduled a hearing for May 23. In the meantime, he
said he would appoint two specialists to examine the boy, who
caregivers say is recovering from an ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the temporary restraining order, Tevrizian cited
allegations that the boy had been sold to smugglers and said he
wanted to ensure the toddler would have a safe home when he returns
to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't, as a parent ... just simply return this child back to
Thailand after what this child has been through,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
