<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trimark OKs Amvescap's Takeover Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Canadian mutual fund giant Trimark Financial
Corp. announced plans Tuesday to merge with global money-management
firm Amvescap PLC of Britain in a deal worth $1.81 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will create Canada's second-largest mutual fund
company and ends weeks of speculation as various Canadian and
global firms were rumored to be in the hunt for Trimark.
</P>
<P>
   ''Trimark is pleased to have the opportunity to partner with a
global investment manager of Amvescap's stature,'' Trimark chairman
Robert Krembil said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in London, Amvescap is one of the world's largest
independent investment managers with $392 billion in assets under
management. Amvescap already runs AIM funds in Canada, and the
company wanted to expand its Canadian operations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, a combination of cash and shares, values Trimark's
shares at about $18 each, Amvescap said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement follows a weak period for Trimark, whose
value-oriented investment style has been out of favor in
technology-propelled stock markets, prompting heavy shareholder
redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Trimark Financial reported Tuesday that its revenue for the year
ended March 31 fell 10 percent, to $367.3.
</P>
<P>
   Trimark is Canada's sixth-largest mutual fund company with $16.6
billion in assets; AIM Canada is ranked 14th with $6.4 billion
under management.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, must be approved by regulators and both companies'
shareholders, is expected to close in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   Trimark manages more than 57 mutual funds with more than 800
employees in offices in the Canadian cities of Toronto, Vancouver
and Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Amvescap is one of the world's largest independent investment
managers. Operating under the AIM and Invesco brands, the company
has more than 5,700 employees in more than 100 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
