<DOCNO> APW20000509.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firemen Push To Kill N.M. WildFire  </HEADLINE>
By PETE HERRERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUIDOSO, N.M. (AP) -- Aided by a brief lull in winds,
firefighters accelerated efforts Tuesday to extinguish two
wildfires that forced hundreds of evacuations and scorched more
than 9,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Winds died down on both fires, near Los Alamos in northern New
Mexico and near the southern resort town of Ruidoso. But the
National Weather Service said winds would rise again Wednesday and
really get roaring Thursday with gusts of up to 50 mph in Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't contain the fire today, the likelihood of it
jumping and going across into Los Alamos Canyon is really high,''
said Frank Hayes, one of five division supervisors on the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuees were allowed to return home to some neighborhoods
Tuesday -- but with the warning that they should not spend the
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos fire was started by the National Park Service to
clear brush at the nearby Bandelier National Monument but spread
out of control. It slowly grew to 3,365 acres Tuesday, and the
eastern edge of the fire burned to Los Alamos National Laboratory's
property line. The lab was closed for a second day and was to stay
closed Wednesday, as were Los Alamos schools and county offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Ruidoso fire grew to 5,700 acres Tuesday. It was started by
a campfire; authorities would not release details of their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Los Alamos National Laboratory:
http://www.lanl.gov/worldview
</P>
<P>
   Bandelier National Monument: http://www.nps.gov/band
</P>
