<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, May 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Backs Bush, Nixes Sharing Ticket
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- While comparing the action to taking a dose of medicine,
Sen. John McCain today endorsed George W. Bush, his rival in the Republican
primaries. McCain said that he doesn't want to be Bush's running mate. Behind
their smiles, the strains from a bitter Republican primary fight were still
apparent. Even as McCain said he looked forward to ''enthusiastically
campaigning'' for the presumptive GOP nominee, the vanquished rival had to be
prompted before using the word ''endorse.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Presidents Back Clinton on China
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an extraordinary assembly of Republican and Democratic
administrations spanning three decades, former Presidents Ford and Carter closed
ranks today with President Clinton to push for a China trade deal that appears
increasingly likely to pass. ''We want the voice of this meeting to echo across
the country and to embrace the Congress,'' Clinton told more than 200 VIPs in
the chandeliered East Room. ''I wish it weren't a fight, but it is.'' Two weeks
before the House opens debate on granting China permanent trade benefits,
supporters of the proposal are optimistic about winning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Refugees Flee Key Sierra Leone Town
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- United Nations peacekeepers, followed by
frightened refugees, have retreated from a key village outside Freetown, U.N.
officials said Tuesday, while regional leaders met in Nigeria in an effort to
defuse the week-old crisis threatening to push Sierra Leone once again into
civil war. The peacekeepers withdrew from Masiaka, 45 miles east of Freetown, on
Monday after exchanging gunfire with unknown attackers and running out of
ammunition, U.N. spokesman David Wimhurst said. Word of the retreat did not
reach Freetown for more than 24 hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Louisiana Gov. Found Guilty
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. Edwin Edwards was convicted today on
charges he extorted hundreds of thousands of dollars from businessmen applying
for riverboat casino licenses. The former four-term governor was found guilty
along with his son Stephen of fraud and racketeering. The scheme took place
during Edwards' final term and after he left office in 1996. He was convicted of
17 of the 26 counts, including two racketeering charges that each carry 20 years
in prison.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
General: Osprey Crash Not Mechanical
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The top Marine Corps general said today he is confident
that mechanical and structural failure can be ruled out as causes of the MV-22
Osprey crash that killed 19 Marines last month. As a result he has given the
go-ahead for the remaining Osprey aircraft to begin returning to flight. ''I
feel confident we can put them back in the air,'' Gen. James L. Jones, the
Marine Corps commandant, said in an interview. ''Everything appears to have been
working normally'' at the time of the accident.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More Rain Hits a Soaked Oklahoma
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Creeping floodwaters sent Oklahomans scrambling to
salvage what they could as schools closed and roads disappeared under water
today after a second round of heavy storms hit the northeast corner of the
state. Downpours that left 2 to 4 inches of rain in the region pushed creeks and
their tributaries over their banks in four counties. As the water continued to
rise in Vinita, tractor-trailers were pulled up to the fronts of a few homes to
haul out furniture and belongings. The flooding was the runoff of heavy rains in
Kansas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Methodists Review Abortion Policy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- A panel of the United Methodist Church, the nation's
largest religious body that favors abortion rights, voted today to fight a
late-term procedure opponents call ''partial-birth'' abortion. The issue now
moves to the full conference for a vote, expected by the end of the week. Though
the full conference could decide otherwise, it usually passes committee
recommendations. The proposal was approved by the committee 77-32.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Wednesday amid lingering worries over the
outlook for U.S. stock prices, with the Nikkei Stock Average shedding 254.98
points to 17,589.56 in early trading. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 66.88 to 10,536.75.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Courier Exits Tournament Tennis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jim Courier, who bludgeoned the ball like a baseball slugger
and often wore a cap to match, is walking away after 13 years of tournament
tennis. He joined Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi and Michael Chang in dominating a
decade of the men's game, and was the first of that group to win two Grand Slam
tournaments and the first to be ranked No. 1. Now he's the first to retire.
Courier, 29, will work as an analyst for cable networks TNT and CNN/SI at
Wimbledon this summer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
