<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deja Vu for the Devils?  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The New Jersey Devils aren't just
back in the Eastern Conference finals for the first time since
1995. They're playing like 1995, the year they won the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing says that better than the performance the Devils put on
Monday night in defeating the Toronto Maple Leafs 3-0 to win the
best-of-seven conference semifinals in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto had just six shots on goal against Martin Brodeur in
what arguably might have been the greatest defensive effort in NHL
history. The shot total was the fewest allowed in any game --
regular season or playoff -- since the league started its expansion
era in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, New Jersey had 27 shots, including six by Claude
Lemieux, the 1995 Conn Symthe Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's as close to perfect as it comes,'' Lemieux said. ''I
remember one game in 1995 that Jacques Lemaire thought was perfect,
but tonight might beat it. When you give up six shots, you're doing
something well. You're doing something right.''
</P>
<P>
   Like in '95, the secret to the Devils' success has been defense.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the physical play of Scott Stevens, New Jersey has given
up 15 goals in 10 playoff games. Opponents' top lines and players
have been all but silenced.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bure, who led the NHL with 58 goals in the regular season,
had one in the Devils' first-round sweep of Florida, while
Toronto's top line of Mats Sundin, Steve Thomas and Jonas Hoglund
had one goal in six games, after scoring 10 in the first round
against Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just didn't create enough chances,'' said Sundin, who was
blanked in the second round. ''We spent pretty much the whole
series in our own end and in the neutral zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The great debate is whether the Devils are again playing the
neutral zone trap favored by former coach Lemaire, or if new coach
Larry Robinson has them using some hybrid of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs swore it was the trap, a defense that clogs up
the center of the ice, takes skating out of the game and makes
hockey boring, except to the team that's winning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just closed the gap tonight,'' quipped Petr Sykora, whose
goal 18 seconds after the opening faceoff pretty much took the air
out of the Maple Leafs. ''You can call the trap, but it's not. It's
just playing smart.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the message Robinson has preached since replacing Robbie
Ftorek as coach on March 23 with the team slumping badly and eight
games left in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils went 4-4 under Robinson, but they have been nearly
unbeatable in the playoffs, posting an 8-2 record. They have
outscored their opponents 28-15 and allowed one power-play goal in
34 attempts, a 2.9 percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's (Robinson) made us a more disciplined team,'' said
Stevens, who is emerging as a leading candidate for this year's
Conn Smythe. ''The past few years, we've been cheating on offense.
Now we have forwards coming back and helping out the defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Larry talks to the players a lot, and he gets results,'' added
Stevens, whose big open-ice hits had Toronto players wary entering
the Devils' zone. ''He's got the guys believing in this system.
When everyone is pulling on the same rope that way, you can go a
long way in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs certainly believe that.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are rolling right now,'' forward Garry Valk said. ''Their
defensive game is playing well, and their goalie is playing real
well, and I expect them to go far.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Lou Lamoriello also believes the Devils are
capable of winning the Cup again if they continue to play the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows things can change quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you can look back and relate and compare (to
'95); that's the first step to disaster,'' Lamoriello said in a
telephone interview with The Associated Press on Tuesday. ''What we
are doing right now is, we are playing with a confidence and a
discipline that is needed to have success. But you have to
understand it's easy to get off track and it's difficult to stay on
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello admitted what might have made him the happiest after
Monday night's game was walking through the locker room and hearing
players say they still haven't done anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey will meet Philadelphia, which beat Pittsburgh 2-1
Tuesday to win their series in six games, in the conference finals.
The Devils won the regular season series 4-1 over the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had a lot of disappointments in the past, and we're kind
of turning the page,'' Brodeur said. ''Winning the first round was
not enough. We're there, and we're tasting it. Hopefully, we'll
keep going the same way. It's time for us to ride the wave and go
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
