<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.C. House Debates Confederate Flag  </HEADLINE>
By LEIGH STROPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The South Carolina House spent five hours
debating a measure to remove the Confederate flag from the
Statehouse dome, but no clear consensus emerged Tuesday on the
first day of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Republican House leaders support a compromise passed by the
Democrat-controlled Senate last month that would fly a similar,
square banner at a Statehouse monument to Confederate soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   As debate got under way, an amendment favored by black Democrats
that would remove the flag and create a new bronze flag monument on
Capitol grounds was defeated 65-43.
</P>
<P>
   The House also changed the Senate bill slightly to increase the
pole's height by 10 feet to 30 feet, to add lighting to illuminate
the flag and to remove the banner at the dome at noon July 1. An
amendment to allow a nonbinding public vote in November was
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're nearing the parameters of what can pass,'' said
Republican House Speaker David Wilkins. ''We're on track. We're at
the monument. We're staying at the monument.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's unclear if any factions have enough votes to approve a
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, I still think there are not enough votes to pass
any single idea,'' said Rep. Bob Sheheen, a Democrat and former
House speaker.
</P>
<P>
   While it was House Republicans who rebuffed previous attempts to
remove the flag, this time the opposition comes from black
Democrats who say the flag would be too visible at the monument,
which is near one of Columbia's busiest intersections.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather it stay on the dome than fly on the ground in
people's faces and create the total chaos that I know it's going to
create,'' said Rep. John Scott.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
which wants tourists to boycott South Carolina until the flag is
removed, also opposes the Senate plan.
</P>
<P>
   Some black senators said it was the best compromise they could
get.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP says the flag stands for slavery. Its supporters say
it is an important symbol of the state's heritage and honors those
who fought in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   NAACP: http://www.naacp.org
</P>
<P>
   Flag opponents: http://www.getinstep.com
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Heritage Coalition:
http://www.kudzumedia.com/schc.htm
</P>
<P>
   Sons of Confederate Veterans: http://wwww.scv.org
</P>
</TEXT>
