<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Wednesday amid lingering
worries over the outlook for U.S. stock prices. The dollar was
higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 254.98 points,
or 1.43 percent, to 17,589.56 in the first 30 minutes of trading.
On Tuesday, the average closed down 355.42 points, or 1.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 109.26 yen, up 0.38 yen from late Tuesday in
Tokyo but below its late New York level of 109.45 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index started lower as investors
remained bearish over continued weakness on Wall Street, where the
Dow Jones industrial average lost 66.88 points to 10,536.75 point
at Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Also in New York, the Nasdaq composite index closed at 3,585.01,
down 84.37.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 25.23 points, or 1.51 percent, to 1,643.91.
The TOPIX closed down 27.38 points, or 1.61 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's strength was
based on a belief that the Federal Reserve will raise interest
rates at its upcoming meeting in a pre-emptive step to ward off
inflationary pressure
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates tend to make a nation's currency more
attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's next Open Market Committee meeting is scheduled for
May 16.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 99.16 yen, up from
97.96 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond
stood at 1.7100 percent in early trading, unchanged from Tuesday's
finish. Its price remained unchanged at 100.77.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
