<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Upholds Miami Leaders Firing  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRADE CHERFILS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A judge on Tuesday upheld the mayor's firing of the
city manager, part of a City Hall shakeup that followed the federal
raid to remove Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Steve Levine's ruling dissolved a court order
issued last week that said Donald Warshaw could temporarily keep
his job. Mayor Joe Carollo, not waiting for the ruling, had already
named Warshaw's successor.
</P>
<P>
   With the ruling, Warshaw was officially out of a job. Carlos
Gimenez was sworn in immediately as Miami's new city manager
</P>
<P>
   Levine ruled there was insufficient evidence to back up
Warshaw's claim to hold onto office.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo booted Warshaw just days after former Police Chief
William O'Brien failed to inform the mayor in advance of the armed
federal raid April 22 removing the 6-year-old Cuban boy from his
Miami relatives' home.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo demanded Warshaw fire O'Brien, but Warshaw refused and
instead praised O'Brien's involvement with the federal government
raid, infuriating the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Under the city charter, the city manager has the power to hire
and fire the police chief without consulting the mayor. The mayor
cannot fire the police chief, but can fire the city manager.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of April, Carollo fired Warshaw, and O'Brien
resigned. Warshaw on May 1 went ahead and appointed a new police
chief, Raul Martinez, a 24-year veteran of the force who had been
serving as an assistant city manager.
</P>
<P>
   Gimenez, 46, has served as a fire chief since 1991. His
appointment prompted a kind word Tuesday from his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a member of my own staff, a quality guy,'' Warshaw said.
''I have every reason to believe that the city will move forward in
the proper way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
