<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Continue To Discuss Summit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The two Koreas have agreed to continue
discussion on the agenda and other details of a summit of their
leaders through documents instead of meetings, South Korean
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The change is meant for effectiveness,'' said Kim Hyon-doo, a
spokesman for the Unification Ministry. ''We exchanged the first
documents yesterday (Tuesday), which proved effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The change came after the two sides failed to iron out
differences over the agenda and other details of the summit at a
fourth round of talks on their border on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea then proposed that the next and fifth round of
preparatory talks be held the next day at the border village of
Panmunjom but North Korea said no.
</P>
<P>
   Kim stressed that the change in the format of discussion does
not mean that the two sides have insurmountable problems. He said
that if differences are successfully resolved, the two sides then
will call a formal meeting to sign an accord.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials earlier said two issues remained
unresolved: the expression of the language of the agenda and the
size of the South Korean press corp.
</P>
<P>
   The June 12-14 summit in the North's capital of Pyongyang would
be the first ever between the Koreas which were divided into the
communist North and the pro-Western South in 1945. They fought a
three-year war in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea proposed a four-point agenda calling for economic
cooperation, peace measures, the reunion of separated family
members and the establishment of a permanent channel of government
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials said privately they would agree to a
broadly worded North Korean proposal which stresses peace and
unification.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea proposed sending an 80-member press corps but North
Korea asked the number to be cut by half, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Unification Minister Park Jae-kyu said at a breakfast
meeting with civilian leaders Wednesday that at the June summit,
South Korea will ask North Korean leader Kim Jong Il to visit Seoul
by year's end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
