<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, May 9, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Gives Endorsement To Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- John McCain endorsed George W. Bush for president today
but compared his action to taking a dose of medicine and said he didn't want to
be Bush's running mate. Behind their smiles, the strains from a bitter
Republican primary fight were still apparent. Even as McCain said he looked
forward to ''enthusiastically campaigning'' for the presumptive GOP nominee, the
vanquished rival had to be prompted before using the word ''endorse.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Law Catches Up With Ex-Louisiana Gov.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, who was known for
nod-and-a-wink politics but always evaded prosecutors, was convicted for the
first time today, on charges he extorted hundreds of thousands of dollars from
businessmen applying for riverboat casino licenses. The former four-term
Democratic governor was found guilty along with his son Stephen of fraud and
racketeering. The scheme took place during Edwards' final term and after he left
office in 1996, when he still wielded considerable influence in Louisiana
politics.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Gets Support on China Trade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an extraordinary assembly of Republican and Democratic
administrations spanning three decades, former Presidents Ford and Carter closed
ranks today with President Clinton to push for a China trade deal that appears
increasingly likely to pass. ''We want the voice of this meeting to echo across
the country and to embrace the Congress,'' Clinton told more than 200 VIPs in
the chandeliered East Room. ''I wish it weren't a fight, but it is.'' Two weeks
before the House opens debate on granting China permanent trade benefits,
supporters of the proposal are optimistic about winning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Big Game Jackpot Is $350 Million
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Tonight's Big Game lottery jackpot in seven states has
swelled to to $350 million -- the richest in U.S. history. The drawing is to be
held at 11 p.m. in Atlanta. Tickets were sold in Georgia, Illinois, Maryland,
Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey and Virginia. If a single person wins the
jackpot, the payout after taxes is either $8.9 million a year for 26 years, or a
one-time payment of $114 million.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft To Rebut Breakup Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft is about to get its chance to rebut a
government's proposal to rip the company in two. Tomorrow, Microsoft will
respond to the proposal made last month by the Justice Department and 17 state
attorneys to split it into one company that sells the dominant Windows operating
system and another selling virtually everything else. The plan was submitted to
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who on April 3 found Microsoft to
be a monopoly with business practices in wide violation of antitrust law. The
company said it will appeal the ruling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Push To Kill N.M. Wildfire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RUIDOSO, N.M. (AP) -- Aided by a brief lull in winds, firefighters
accelerated efforts today to extinguish two wildfires that forced hundreds of
evacuations and scorched more than 9,000 acres. Winds died down on both fires,
near Los Alamos in northern New Mexico and near the southern resort town of
Ruidoso. But the National Weather Service said winds would rise again tomorrow
and really get roaring Thursday with gusts of up to 50 mph in Los Alamos.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Singled Out By UN Statement
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A draft statement prepared by a U.N. conference on
nuclear disarmament has singled out Israel for being the only country in the
Middle East that hasn't signed onto the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. The
draft, which is still subject to revision before the conference wraps up next
week, also notes that subcontinental neighbors India and Pakistan, which
conducted nuclear tests in 1998, haven't signed and urges them to do so.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Wednesday amid lingering worries over the
outlook for U.S. stock prices, with the Nikkei Stock Average shedding 254.98
points to 17,589.56 in early trading. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 66.88 to 10,536.75.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Flyers Eliminate Penguins 2-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mark Recchi and John LeClair set up each other for goals
and the Philadelphia Flyers, winning for the third time in a week in a rink
where they once rarely won, eliminated the Pittsburgh Penguins 2-1 tonight in
the Eastern Conference semifinals. The Flyers went 3-0 in Pittsburgh -- they are
4-1 on the road in the playoffs -- to win the best-of-seven series 4-2. They are
the 13th NHL team to win a series after falling behind 2-0 at home.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
