<DOCNO> APW20000509.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Even Weather Goes Against Tigers  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY ATKINS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- There is some comfortable clutter on top of Phil
Garner's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stuff being perused by the Detroit Tigers' manager is
a video called ''Spring Free Agents'' and a soft cover book titled
''2000 Player Profiles.'' An open laptop computer sits on a work
table behind Garner's swivel chair.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like the Tigers are looking for help?
</P>
<P>
   Garner and Randy Smith, the club's general manager, talk every
day. Despite the worst record in the major leagues, however, the
only moves the Tigers have made this week was recalling reliever
Masao Kida from Triple-A Toledo on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (9-22) were on their way to a win Tuesday, leading
3-0 in the third inning against Kansas City when the game was
rained out. If they should drop to 9-23, they would match the worst
32-game start in club history. The Tigers have scored two runs on
18 hits in their last 29 innings that counted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anybody saw this coming,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers also rank last in a number of offensive categories,
including batting average (.247), runs (113) and total bases (418).
The Tigers were held to two runs or less in 16 of their first 31
games.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the man who assembled this team, has come under
increasing fire. And the strain is beginning to show.
</P>
<P>
   In his worst nightmare, Smith never imagined something like this
could happen. Not to a lineup that included proven hitters like
Juan Gonzalez, Dean Palmer, Tony Clark and Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people would have said our Achilles' heel would be our
starting pitching, and I would have agreed with that,'' Smith said.
''But I never thought we'd have trouble swinging the bat. I would
never have said we wouldn't be scoring runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the two-time AL MVP, hit .326 with 128 RBIs and 39
homers for the Texas Rangers last season. With the Tigers, however,
he is off to a start as bad as the team's.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has been nursing a tight hamstring in his right leg all
season. He arrived at Comerica Park on Tuesday sporting a .220
average with eight RBIs and four homers.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who hit .263 with 100 RBIs and 38 homers in 1999, has a
.244 average with 13 RBIs and five homers. Clark, hitting .169, has
been dropped to seventh in the batting order. Higginson is hitting
.248.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if it's possible to feel worse,'' Smith said.
''We're disappointed. It's the same old thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow things do seem to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, for example, even the weather seemed to be going
against the hard-luck Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not worried about that,'' Garner said. ''The good news
is we were seeing some good stuff from out hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers took a 2-0 lead in the first on RBIs by Juan
Encarnacion and Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   Royals right-hander Mac Suzuki, making his first start since
being banished to the bullpen April 19, gave up an RBI single to
Luis Polonia in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, held to just four hits in an 11-inning loss Monday
night, had four hits in the first inning. When play was halted by
lightning, severe thunderstorms and hail at 7:56 p.m. EDT, the
Tigers had runners at first and third with a 1-0 count on Tony
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rainout, none of the statistics count. That came
as an especially bitter pill for Detroit starter Dave Mlicki, who
was looking for his first win of the season in his seventh start.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's frustrating for everybody,'' Mlicki said. ''I had
everything, unfortunately,'' Mlicki said. ''It was one of those
days you don't have very often. I felt like I could throw just
about anything I wanted and it would be a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   After a wait of 1 hour, 40 minutes, umpires called the game. No
immediate makeup date was announced, and Detroit said it would not
be played this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-09-00 2308 </TRAILER>
