<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Braves 10, Marlins 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Javy Lopez hit a grand slam to cap Atlanta's
five-run first inning as the Braves snapped a three-game losing
streak with a 10-5 win over the Florida Marlins on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett (1-2), who played for the Marlins in 1995-96,
allowed two runs and six hits in six innings for his first win with
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who had lost four of five since a franchise-record
15-game winning streak ended last Wednesday in Los Angeles, tied
their season high in runs. They beat Philadelphia 10-1 on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Penny (3-4) allowed six runs and three hits in 2 1-3 wild
innings. He walked seven, hit two batters, threw a wild pitch and
balked once.
</P>
<P>
   Penny, who had worked at least six innings in each of his
previous six starts, had control problems from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the first, he hit Andruw Jones and walked
Chipper Jones and Andres Galarraga, loading the bases. Penny then
hit Brian Jordan, allowing Andruw Jones to score.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who went 3-for-4, followed with his third career grand
slam, an opposite-field shot to right, to make it 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins scored a run in the bottom of the first on Mark
Kotsay's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves chased Penny in the third. Atlanta loaded the bases
when Lopez walked, Bobby Bonilla singled and Rafael Furcal walked.
With one out, Penny walked Quilvio Veras to make it 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves added single runs in the fifth and sixth before
scoring twice in the seventh. A run-scoring double by Galarraga was
the big hit, giving him 1,199 RBIs in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lowell hit a solo homer off Kerry Ligtenberg in the eighth
inning, and Mark Smith had a two-run shot off Bruce Chen in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Braves closer John Rocker has allowed five runs, seven hits
and three walks in his past three games. ... The Marlins have six
wins against the NL East. Last year, they didn't reach that total
until June 27. ... Mark Kotsay's third-inning RBI triple was the
19th triple of his career, tying Kurt Abbott for the Marlins'
record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
