<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-09 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel: Vote Needed On Kosovo Troops  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Appropriations Committee voted
overwhelmingly Tuesday to require congressional approval for U.S.
peacekeepers to remain in Kosovo beyond July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-3 vote reflected widespread concern among lawmakers about
an open-ended deployment of American soldiers, who make up 5,900 of
the 37,000 NATO-led peacekeepers in the breakaway Yugoslav
province. Sporadic ethnic violence lingers there, nearly a year
after the end of NATO's 78-day air war against the forces of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came as the appropriations panel approved roughly $8
billion for this year to keep American troops in Kosovo, help
Colombia's government battle drug traffickers, and assist victims
of last autumn's Hurricane Floyd and other domestic natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   White House budget chief Jack Lew criticized the committee for
coupling the money with other items the Clinton administration
opposes, including environmental provisions and limits on the
Justice Department's ability to pursue its lawsuit against the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The provision threatening the withdrawal of troops from Kosovo
was sponsored by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., one of Congress' most
ardent protectors of its constitutional powers, and Senate Armed
Service Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd argued that lawmakers had never approved or even debated
whether U.S. ground troops should be stationed in the region. His
language would cut off funds for U.S. troops in Kosovo after July
1, 2001, without Congress' consent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the committee that controls the only real, raw, basic,
fundamental power in this government. That is the money,'' Byrd
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Tuesday night in Denver, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright called the efforts by Congress to block money
for peacekeeping in Kosovo ''wrongheaded.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The exit strategy for our troops out of Kosovo is to provide
money for stability and the creation of institutions there,''
Albright told the World Trade Center, a business organization.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., one of the three Democrats who
voted against Byrd, said Milosevic would benefit if the provision
becomes law because ''all the butcher has to do is wait until the
U.S. withdraws.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the provision was unclear because the House narrowly
rejected a similar amendment in March and the Clinton
administration opposes it. Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said that White House National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger ''is very upset about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's language would also withhold 25 percent of the money for
Kosovo in the bill for this year unless President Clinton certifies
that European countries are living up to their promises to provide
reconstruction money for the province. He would have until July 15
of this year to provide that certification.
</P>
<P>
   By voice vote, the appropriations panel also adopted another
amendment by Byrd requiring the president to get congressional
approval to spend any money in Colombia beyond the funds provided
in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers of both parties have warned that the United
States risks getting dragged into a bloody civil war in Colombia,
where the government has been battling drug traffickers aided by
leftist guerillas and right-wing militias.
</P>
<P>
   Though the appropriations panel offered few specific details,
some Senate aides estimated that the committee had approved about
$1.2 billion for Colombia and about $1.8 billion for U.S. forces in
Kosovo, a bit less than Clinton requested.
</P>
<P>
   That money -- plus other funds for defense, farmers and other
programs -- was divided among three measures financing agriculture,
military construction and foreign aid programs in fiscal 2001,
which starts Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Adding momentum to a top farm issue, the Senate panel voted by
voice to add language to the agriculture bill lifting the embargo
on selling food and drugs to Cuba. A similar provision is in the
House version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lew complained that the spending bills contained language
reducing the administration's ability to limit waste sites produced
by hard-rock mines and removing some land on North Carolina's Outer
Banks from protection as a refuge.
</P>
<P>
   It would also prevent federal agencies from reimbursing the
Justice Department for the legal expenses of the government's
lawsuit against the tobacco industry, which Lew said would in
effect prevent the department from pursuing the legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't seem to me to be designed for a smooth path'' to
getting signed into law by Clinton, Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans planned to boost education spending by $2
billion over this year's levels in a fiscal 2001 spending bill they
planned to unveil on Wednesday, House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., announced.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been determined to be seen as defenders of
schools as education has emerged as a top issue in this year's
presidential and congressional election campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
